<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Continental jet suffers engine failure on takeoff  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Federal regulators and the maker of a
popular engine for large jetliners are scrutinizing why the models
of the engine suffered uncommon failures on three separate takeoffs
of Continental Airlines aircraft since April.
</P>
<P>
   The airline and the manufacturer, GE Aircraft Engines, a unit of
General Electric Co., on Tuesday expressed confidence in the
engine.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board is investigating ''to
see if there is any common thread,'' NTSB spokesman Ted
Lopatkiewicz said. The agency has not issued a safety
recommendation on the engines.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported during the incidents, which led to two
takeoffs being aborted. The other flight returned shortly after
takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   GE Aircraft Engines, of Cincinnati, suspects the failures are
linked to an exhaust nozzle at the rear of the engines, company
spokesman Rick Kennedy said. As the part came loose and rotated, it
wore away at the engine cases and caused parts to break loose, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, it appears we have a specific area that we're
focusing on ... to make sure it doesn't happen again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,400 of the CF6-50 engines, which are about 20 to 25
years old, are used on McDonnell Douglas DC-10s and early Boeing
747s around the world, many flying daily, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very reliable engine. It's a workhorse of the
industry,'' he said. ''The overall operational safety of these
engines is very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a recommendation GE issued after the first incident,
Continental has increased engine inspections on its 24 DC-10s,
airline spokesman David Messing said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of our maintenance meets or exceeds FAA requirements,
which are the toughest in the world,'' Messing said.
</P>
<P>
   Continental is responsible for routine maintenance on the
engines, while GE performs overhauls on the engines every few
years, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the airline, nor the manufacturer, could immediately
provide the date on the last overhaul on the three engines that
failed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Each suffered a rare breakdown, called an uncontained engine
failure, in which parts penetrate the engine housing.
</P>
<P>
   Only 25 such failures happened in the United States from
1985-99. Two of the Continental incidents this year happened at
Newark International Airport, one of its hubs, while the third was
Thursday in Amsterdam. All involved DC-10s.
</P>
<P>
   The engines are designed to eject parts out the rear, which
poses less of a threat to the aircraft and its occupants, said
William D. Waldock, a professor of aeronautical science at
Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Prescott, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The age of the engines is not a factor if they are maintained
properly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most common causes of engine failures are metal fatigue or
when birds are sucked into the engine. An unbalanced turbine blade
can also cause such a failure, but that is usually detected during
routine maintenance, Waldock said.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent engine failure was Thursday, when Flight 71 from
Amsterdam to Newark aborted its takeoff when one of its three
engines failed, the NTSB said.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days earlier, Flight 60 from Newark to Brussels,
Belgium, also aborted its takeoff with an engine failure.
</P>
<P>
   On April 25, Flight 60 returned to Newark after the engine under
the left wing spewed parts and knocked out a second engine.
</P>
<P>
   DC-10s can fly on only one engine if needed.
</P>
<P>
   After the April incident, GE advised operators to increase the
frequency of visual inspection of the nozzle area whenever the
engine cowling is removed, roughly every 100 to 200 hours of flight
operation, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides visual and manual inspections, Continental will use
electronic equipment to test the engines, Messing said.
</P>
<P>
   In another incident, passengers and crew were removed on Sunday
from a Continental Boeing 737 at Newark because of an engine
warning.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of Flight 675 to Kansas City shut the engine and
cleared the jet after seeing a warning light flash for the
left-wing engine, Federal Aviation Administration spokeswoman
Arlene Salac said.
</P>
<P>
   The jet was towed to a hangar. The engine was restarted, and a
fire that started in an engine tailpipe about 9 a.m. was
extinguished by maintenance workers, Continental spokeswoman
Catherine Stengel said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause appeared to be fuel dripping from one engine, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Continental Airlines: http://www.continental.com
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration: http://www.faa.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board: http://www.ntsb.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
