<HEADLINE> Arthur Eve survives against Peoples; Three incumbents lose  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The dean of the state Assembly survived a tough
challenge from a fellow Democrat but at least three other
incumbents in the state Legislature lost their party's backing in
Tuesday's primary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Democrat Arthur Eve, seeking his 18th term in the
Assembly, bested the chairwoman of the Erie County Legislature,
Crystal Peoples, 7,470 or 51 percent to 6,627 or 46 percent,
according to unofficial returns from 91 percent of the precincts.
Samuel Herbert had 424 votes or 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people when they went in the booth they had to say,
'Arthur Eve has delivered constantly for this community, for this
city, for the children, has provided opportunities for the young
people,''' a relieved Eve said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his long Assembly career, Eve had to run
television commercials as part of a re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eve race brought down another Democratic incumbent. A
strong turnout in the areas of Buffalo where the Eve district
overlapped that of state Sen. Alfred Coppola gave Coppola's
opponent Byron Brown the victory. With 94 percent of the vote
counted unofficially, Brown had 13,585 votes or 54 percent to
11,343 votes or 46 percent for Coppola.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact of the matter is he ran a good campaign,'' said
Coppola, who took his seat earlier this year after former Sen.
Anthony Nanula was elected Buffalo city comptroller. ''I said it
earlier, I was on the (Buffalo city) council with him for four
years and I taught him everything he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola said he would run in November as the Conservative
candidate. Bob Woolworth is the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democratic incumbents losing Tuesday were Assemblyman
Nelson Denis in the Bronx and Bronx state Sen. David Rosado. In
addition, Brooklyn Democratic Assemblyman Edward Griffith was
behind in tight balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Denis lost to former New York City Councilman Adam Clayton
Powell IV in a three-way race. Powell, 38, is the son of the former
Harlem congressman who is seeking to get back into politics for the
first time since 1997. That year, Powell resigned his seat on the
New York City Council and ran unsuccessfully for Manhattan borough
president.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel awesome,'' Powell said Tuesday night. ''Basically,
people here are very intelligent. They are very smart and they
realize they did not have any representation in the state
Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   With all precincts reporting, Powell had 5,882 votes or 53
percent to 4,410 votes or 40 percent for Denis. Frank Acosta, the
third candidate in the race, got 871 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Powell will face Republican Rose Pascale in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Rosado-Pedro Espada Jr. campaign for a state Senate seat in
the South Bronx was perhaps the most bitter of any legislative
primaries. Espada held the seat from 1992-96 before being unseated
by Rosado. Each candidate questioned the other's honesty.
</P>
<P>
   Espada faces prosecution in Bronx state Supreme Court for
allegedly diverting money from a health center he runs to help pay
for his 1996 race. Espada has contended that the prosecution is
being pressed by his opponents within the Bronx Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith, a 14-term veteran, trailed Diane Gordon 3,169 votes to
3,099 votes with 100 percent of the balloting unofficially
complete. Mary Warren had 1,356 votes.
</P>
<P>
   In Schenectady, Brian Stratton defeated Gerald Evans in a
Democratic primary to earn the right to meet incumbent Republican
state Sen. Hugh Farley in November. Stratton, a Schenectady city
councilman, is the son of the late longtime Congressman Sam
Stratton.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, Steven Cymbrowitz easily defeated Michael Hizme to
win the Democratic nomination to succeed his wife Lena Cymbrowitz
in the state Assembly. Lena Cymbrowitz died at age 43 in August
while in her first term in the Assembly. Steven Cymbrowitz will
face Republican Fred Fields in November in the heavily Democratic
district.
</P>
<P>
   There were only two Republican legislative primaries of
significance Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Staten Island, Robert DiCarlo led Charles Capetanakis in
their race for the Republican nomination for state Senate. DiCarlo,
who lost the seat in 1996 to Democrat Vincent Gentile, was seeking
another chance against Gentile in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   With 91 percent of the vote counted, DiCarlo led with 2,058
votes or 53 percent to 1,794 votes or 47 percent for Capetanakis.
</P>
<P>
   In the state's Finger Lakes region, incumbent Assemblyman George
Winner easily defeated Chemung County Legislator Sidney Graubard in
a Republican primary. Winner, an 11-term veteran, has no Democratic
opponent in November.
</P>
<P>
   The long-serving Eve, 67, had always been counted on to speak
out passionately in debates in favor of social spending for
impoverished New Yorkers and against measures he felt would
victimize young African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to the Assembly in 1966, he often referred to his role
during the 1971 Attica prison uprising, when he was one of the
observers let into the barricaded portion of the facility to hear
inmate grievances before the bloody retaking of the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing that people (opponents) are saying is that it's time
for a change, but they don't give any basis for it, in that I'm not
effective,'' Eve said on the eve of the primary. ''Seniority is
very important and I'm part of the leadership in Albany. That's
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Peoples, 48, was careful during the campaign not to personally
attack the political institution Eve has become, saying she had
''no disrespect to the gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peoples said Eve's legislative agenda was a throwback to the
days of looking for social programs to address people's problems.
She suggested Eve had been slow to promote economic growth in the
district with initiatives to create new businesses and jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
