<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Jolts Indonesia Island  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A strong offshore earthquake shook the
southwest coast of the Indonesian island of Sumatra, seismologists
and residents said Wednesday. There were no reports of casualties
or major damage.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's Meteorology and Geophysics Agency said the magnitude
5.7 temblor hit at 11:27 p.m. local time Tuesday. Its epicenter was
beneath the Indian Ocean, 140 miles southwest of the town of
Bengkulu, said seismologist Sutanto, who like many Indonesians uses
only one name.
</P>
<P>
   Seismologists at the Hong Kong Observatory estimated the quake's
magnitude at 6.1.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of tremors have rattled Bengkulu since June 4, when a
magnitude 7.9 quake killed at least 100 people and damaged hundreds
of buildings and homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very normal to feel aftershocks nowadays. We don't panic
like we used to,'' said Can Cahayawati, a resident of Bengkulu,
about 300 miles northwest of Jakarta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
