<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Weightlifter Sent Home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Taiwan, already hurt by two drug cases,
sent weightlifter Chen Po-pu home after a positive doping test.
</P>
<P>
   ''His entry has been withdrawn,'' Taiwan's Olympic delegation
said in a statement Wednesday (Tuesday night EDT).
</P>
<P>
   Chuang Tsun-che, chief of Taiwan's Olympic delegation, said he
received formal notice from the International Weightlifting
Federation that Chen had tested positive for ''prohibited drugs''
on Tuesday, Taiwan's Central News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Chuang immediately took Chen's athlete identification papers and
arranged for his flight back to Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was tested twice on Aug. 28 and failed the first test.
After he learned that he had tested positive the first time, Chen
waived his right to know the results of the second test, the agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The International Weightlifting Federation has already barred
world champion weightlifter Chen Jui-lien and her teammate Wu
Mei-yi from competing at Sydney because of drug allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0030 </TRAILER>
