<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers Beat Orioles 6-5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Kenny Rogers pitched seven strong
innings for his first win in seven starts as the Texas Rangers
completed a doubleheader sweep of the Baltimore Orioles with a 6-5
victory on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers (12-13) allowed three runs and seven hits in his first
win since Aug. 8, helping the Rangers to a sweep of their only
doubleheader of the season. Rogers struck out six and walked one
before allowing hits to the first two batters in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland earned his 33rd save, despite allowing a two-run
double to Greg Myers in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also took both ends of its last doubleheader on Sept. 6,
1999 over the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore was last swept on June 8, 1999 by the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Helling pitched three-hit ball for eight innings in the
Rangers' 9-1 opening-game victory.
</P>
<P>
   Helling (15-11) gave up Brady Anderson's homer leading off the
game and just two singles after that, winning for the first time in
six starts since beating Boston on Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Helling struck out five and walked none. In his previous five
starts, he had a 9.12 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the Orioles' rookie starters, John Parrish and Jay
Spurgeon, were able to get past the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Rangers' veteran starters shut down the Orioles
lineups, dominated by young players.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson went 4-for-7 in the doubleheader with a homer and two
doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Spurgeon (1-1) was hurt by five walks and two homers, lasting
four innings plus three batters in the fifth. Spurgeon allowed six
runs and four hits and struck out one.
</P>
<P>
   In the second game, Texas grabbed a 4-0 lead in the first inning
on Ricky Ledee's RBI single and rookie Pedro Valdes's three-run
homer, the first of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore closed to 4-2 on Delino DeShields' two-run single in
the third. Ledee's RBI single in the third and Luis Alicea's
leadoff homer in the fifth extended Texas' lead to 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   DeShields' sacrifice fly in the eighth narrowed the deficit to
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, Scarborough Green had the first three-hit game of
his career, and Bill Haselman went 3-for-4 with a homer and two
doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish (2-4) was tagged for five runs and six hits in 1 2-3
innings. He has a 22.22 ERA in his last three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hit Helling's second pitch into the right-field seats
for his 17th homer. Helling didn't give up another hit until Greg
Myers led off the seventh with a single. Anderson added a two-out
single in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Haselman will have surgery on Monday to repair a partial
tear of his right rotator cuff. Haselman has had the problem for
several years and team doctors decide to have the surgery in order
for him to be ready for spring training. Haselman will continue to
play through the weekend. ... The Orioles had split their first
three doubleheaders this season. ... Texas has won seven of 10. ...
Anderson has led off games with home runs 42 times. ... Parrish was
making his first start since being recalled from Triple-A Rochester
on Sept. 5. He had the shortest outing of his eight big league
starts. ... Orioles DH Jeff Conine left in the fourth inning of the
first game after mildly spraining his left ankle while running out
a popup in the first. ... Ruben Sierra, called up from Triple-A
Oklahoma on Sept. 5, went 0-for-5 in his first home start for the
Rangers since Aug. 29, 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0032 </TRAILER>
