<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former librarian in dead heat with Michael Forbes  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLPORT, N.Y. (AP) - Michael Forbes, the Long Island
congressman who switched parties 14 months ago, faced the prospect
of banishment from the November ballot after a little-known
challenger ran a dead-heat against him in a Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about the people of this community who have said in no
uncertain terms to Mr. Forbes, 'You're fired.' It's a really,
really amazing thing,'' said Regina Seltzer, a 71-year-old former
librarian who resented the former Republican running as a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am so proud of the people of this community for having the
courage to get up there and to buck the Washington bureaucrats,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   With 100 percent of the vote counted in unofficial returns,
Regina Seltzer was ahead 5,825 to 5,786 over Forbes. She had raised
just $40,000 for her campaign while her opponent had a budget of
$1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The eastern Long Island district includes the Hamptons,
playground for the rich and famous, as well as working class
suburban communities in central Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point I'm declaring victory,'' Seltzer said in a
telephone interview on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mike Forbes is a goner,'' added Jim Wilkinson, spokesman for
the National Republican Congressional Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said voting machines had been impounded for a recount
that would take several days.
</P>
<P>
   ''If my opponent is truly several dozen votes ahead, we're going
to support her and live by the will of the people,'' said Forbes,
who switched parties in July 1999 after being wooed by Democrats
trying to reclaim the House majority.
</P>
<P>
   He was personally welcomed into the Democratic Party by
President Clinton, but he voted for impeachment and opposes
abortion. Clinton attended a Manhattan fund-raiser to benefit
Forbes last April.
</P>
<P>
   Mailings from the Republican Party to registered Democrats in
his district gleefully touted his 100 percent rating from the
Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer entered the race after other local Democrats backed out
under pressure from party leaders in Washington. Seltzer said her
showing proved that local Democrats were not happy about having a
one-time Republican foisted on them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can only conclude one thing: The people of Long Island, of
the first Congressional District, don't want to be told by
Washington, D.C., who is going to represent them,'' said Seltzer.
''They want a Democrat who represents them to be really and truly a
Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer, a former school librarian, served on the Brookhaven
Town Council two decades ago and went to law school at age 50.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I don't think this is about me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer also got a boost when Newsday endorsed her two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   As an attorney, she now mostly works free of charge for groups
like the Long Island Pine Barrens Society. And she put her law
degree to good use recently, suing the state Democratic Party to
stop them from running ads on Forbes' behalf before the primary had
been held determining who the party's candidate is. She won.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of Tuesday's Democratic primary will face Republican
Felix Grucci in the November general election. Grucci, the
Brookhaven town supervisor and head of the famed fireworks family,
won an Independence Party primary Tuesday night over Jack Fisher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 0052 </TRAILER>
