<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Cops Hunt Jungle Labs  </HEADLINE>
By MARGARITA MARTINEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUMACO, Colombia (AP) -- Arriving aboard a U.S.-made combat
helicopter, the head of Colombia's national police and the top U.S.
drug official in the country watched as heavily armed officers
torched a drug lab and dumped coca leaves into a river.
</P>
<P>
   Other helicopters swept back and forth overhead, keeping an eye
out for gunmen, and police stood guard over four people they caught
at the site -- allegedly workers at the drug lab.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong operation Tuesday underscored Washington's deepening
involvement in the drug war in this South American nation. The
offensive is to get fully under way when 60 additional combat
helicopters arrive from the United States next year and U.S.
special forces troops finish training two Colombian army
battalions.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 rifle-toting Colombian police officers swept through a
section of jungle in southwest Colombia on Tuesday as part of
''Operation Mangrove.'' Police say 26 drug labs and 12,500 acres of
cocaine-producing crops have been destroyed by aerial fumigation in
the monthlong regional operation.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, 91,400 acres have been sprayed this year, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're fumigating all over the country, so the drug traffickers
know there is no safe place for them,'' national police chief Gen.
Luis Gilibert told journalists during Tuesday's mission.
</P>
<P>
   Gilibert and Leo Arreguin, chief of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration in Colombia, watched as a plane swooped down and
dumped a load of herbicide on a coca plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Three combat Black Hawk helicopters flew overhead, ready to fire
back at rebels who have been protecting drug crops and earning
millions of dollars a week by taxing drug producers. There was no
resistance to the raid, which was observed by about 30 journalists
flown in from the capital, Bogota, 370 miles to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Later, anti-narcotics police clad in combat fatigues found three
bags bulging with coca leaf, from which cocaine is made, in a
canoe. They dumped the contents into a river.
</P>
<P>
   The officers then torched a rudimentary coca-processing lab and
arrested three boys and a man who allegedly had picked the coca
crop and worked in the lab.
</P>
<P>
   The joint U.S.-Colombian effort, being financed by $1.3 billion
from Washington, is expected to level off coca production by the
end of 2001 and bring a ''dramatic reduction'' a year later, the
State Department said last week.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the early operations have barely dented overall
drug production in Colombia, which supplies more than 80 percent of
the world's cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   According to the DEA, there were almost 300,000 acres of coca in
Colombia at the end of last year. Evidence suggests there will be
an increase this year over the estimated 520 metric tons of cocaine
that Colombia produced in 1999, Barry McCaffrey, director of the
White House drug control office, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-drug effort has won support in Washington, but local
coca farmers often feel abandoned by Colombia's government and say
the crop is the only one from which they can turn a profit. Many
locals also fear the widespread fumigation will cause irreversible
ecological damage.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department says the herbicide, called glyphosate,
is only being sprayed on illicit drug crops and that it causes no
long-lasting damage.
</P>
<P>
   But a DEA agent said drug producers often replant the hardy coca
bushes in the same area after the herbicide washes away. Half the
sprayed areas are replanted with coca, said the agent, who did not
want to give his name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Messages Worry Anti-Terror Experts  </HEADLINE>
By THOMAS WAGNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terrorists holding civilians hostage in the Philippines are paid
millions of dollars to free them. Their little-known cause is
trumpeted around the world.
</P>
<P>
   They ridicule the president of the Philippines and win new
support for their insurgency. Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi,
who has a history of supporting terrorism, seeks to cast himself in
a humanitarian light by paying the ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the separatist Muslim rebel group Abu Sayyaf has freed
10 of its foreign captives, a consensus appears to be building
among experts on terrorism that the governments involved have
broken some generally accepted rules about dealing with terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ''A million bucks per hostage is a great way to fund your
revolution,'' said William Anthony Donohue, a professor at Michigan
State University who has analyzed the handling of other hostage
crises. ''If the profit is high and the risk is low, and you're a
terrorist group with nothing to lose, why wouldn't you try the same
thing again?''
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Merari, former head of Israel's hostage negotiation unit,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Experience shows that whenever you pay ransoms, you increase
the likelihood of other kidnappings. In most cases, authorities
have to negotiate with the captors. But that doesn't mean that you
show a willingness to submit to their demands,'' said Merari, who
now works as an expert on international terrorism at Tel Aviv
University.
</P>
<P>
   In a development that seemed to support this view, the Abu
Sayyaf rebels kidnapped three more foreigners in Malaysia on Sunday
night. That raised their total remaining number to 19, including
American Jeffrey Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   The new kidnapping came right on the heels of the most recent
hostage release: On Saturday, following long negotiations with
Libyan envoy Rajab Azzarouq, the rebels freed four Europeans it had
held hostage for months in a southern Philippine jungle. The two
Finns, a Frenchman and a German had been kidnapped April 23 from a
Malaysian diving resort. Libya paid the rebels $4 million in
ransom, negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Libya reportedly paid $6 million for the release of
six other foreign hostages: two South Africans, three Frenchwomen
and a German man. Libya said the money was for ''development
projects.'' The U.S. government and others saw it as a ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Malaysian officials and businessmen paid $5 million for
the release of nine Malaysians kidnapped along with the Westerners,
negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine President Joseph Estrada has faced calls in the
Philippine Congress to attack the rebels. But in May, European
Union envoy Javier Solana rushed to Manila to plead with Estrada's
government to do nothing that would endanger the hostages' lives.
That effectively closed the option of using force.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Sayyaf is an umbrella group of several armed gangs that
profess to be fighting for an independent Muslim state in the south
of the mostly Roman Catholic Philippines. But they are mainly
involved in kidnap for ransom. On Monday, one of the freed
hostages, Risto Vahanen of Finland, said the rebels raped some of
their female captives.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorism experts interviewed in the United States, Israel,
France and Britain echoed each other's views on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   They criticized the European Union for publicly pressuring the
Philippine military to avoid violence. They said reporters
shouldn't have been given free rein to visit the rebels and
publicize their demands.
</P>
<P>
   The experts also tended to criticize Manila for allowing Libya
to play a self-serving role and reward the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi had the 10 freed foreign hostages flown to Tripoli for
elaborate televised ceremonies during which they warmly thanked
Libya for its help. The deals appeared to be part of Gadhafi's
effort to improve his public image and distract the world's
attention from the trial in the Netherlands of two Libyans accused
in the 1988 terrorist attack on Pan Am Flight 103, which killed 270
people.
</P>
<P>
   ''In most hostage crises, authorities have to talk to the
captors, to open an avenue of communication with them,'' Israel's
Merari said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But that doesn't mean showing a willingness to submit to their
demands,'' he said. ''In fact, when you negotiate without the
threat of punishing the hostage-takers -- if your preclude a
military rescue -- then you negotiate from an obvious point of
weakness, and the result is pretty clear from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Xavier Raufer, head of the Institute of Criminology at the
University of Paris II in France, said the dense jungles and tribal
structure of the region where Abu Sayyaf operates would make it
hard to use force to free the hostages safely. Raufer also said
that even countries that oppose paying ransoms sometimes do so in
secret, or trade jailed prisoners for hostages.
</P>
<P>
   But he, too, faulted the Europeans for opposing the use of
force, and Libya for making clear how much money it would pay.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you go on TV and show potential hostage-takers around the
world that you are paying million of dollars per hostage, that
makes it riskier for other tourists,'' Raufer said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wilkinson, director of the Center for the Study of
Terrorism and Political Violence at the University of St. Andrew in
Scotland, said an increase in hostage-taking and kidnapping for
ransom, including U.N. peacekeepers in West Africa, is evident
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear,'' he said, ''that European Union countries do not
have a firm, clear policy on how to deal with these situations, and
they have tended to improvise. In the Philippines, they enabled the
release of hostages at an enormous price that increased the
resources to one of the most dangerous and active terrorist groups
in the Pacific region.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
