<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program Aids Former Child Soldiers  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID FOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- At age 10, when most children learn
math and spelling, Grace Karisio was taught how to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a child soldier at a rebel army camp in Africa's
war-torn Sudan, Grace watched one day as the rebel commanders
punished a young friend of hers. She didn't know what the boy had
done wrong, but the commanders were angry, and that always meant
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   They tied the boy's hands behind his back and beat him
unconscious. Then they propped him up in a chair and turned to
Grace.
</P>
<P>
   Shoot him, they said. If you miss, you will replace him in the
chair. So Grace stood 20 feet away, took careful aim and squeezed
the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   She did not miss.
</P>
<P>
   When the fighting in a war zone stops, how do you mold former
child soldiers like Grace -- schooled only in violence -- into
productive members of society?
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the thorniest problems highlighted this week in
Winnipeg by an international conference on war and children. The
United Nations estimates that 300,000 children under 18 serve as
soldiers, laborers or sex slaves in armed conflicts around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, more than 50 nations have signed a U.N. agreement
banning soldiers under age 18 in armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But signing a proclamation is simpler than helping former child
soldiers reintegrate into the community. Their families may be dead
or scattered. They have little education or ability to earn a
living. Neighbors fear them, or hate them for what they did while
carrying guns. They often are aggressive, violent. Many of the boys
are injured; many of the girls are pregnant from repeated rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Some are emotionally crippled by guilt over the killings, rapes,
lootings and beatings they participated in. Others -- and these
present the bigger challenge -- feel no remorse at all.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their concept of right and wrong is not the same as for
children brought up in a normal setting,'' said Roisin De Burca, a
UNICEF worker who helps rehabilitate child soldiers in Sierra
Leone. ''For some of these children, killing is normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is hope, De Burca says.
</P>
<P>
   Education of returning children is key. So is finding their
families, often a laborious process. Aid workers also try to
shoehorn reconciliation into a local cultural context -- from group
counseling in Kosovo to a tribal spirit-cleansing ceremony in
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, UNICEF and World Vision have put 2,000 youths
through a lengthy reintegration program in Sierra Leone, where a
brutal, nearly decade-long civil war has left the poor west African
country in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the child soldiers spend three months in a
rehabilitation center before being released to relatives, foster
parents, group homes, or independent living quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In the centers, aid workers divide the youths to break up the
command structure of their old fighting units. The first month,
called ''mad month,'' is dominated by fighting and behavior
problems. By the second month, once they've settled into a routine,
the children start honing learning skills for their return to
school.
</P>
<P>
   De Burca told of one aggressive, violent boy who came to a
rehabilitation center in the Sierra Leone capital of Freetown at
17, after seven years as a soldier. A turning point for the
teen-ager, De Burca said, was his first glimmer of empathy.
</P>
<P>
   When he realized that others had suffered even more from the war
than he had, De Burca said, the boy began to appreciate why people
would be bitter toward him as a former soldier.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to become a taxi driver, so the program helped him
practice for the driving test, bought him an old car and helped him
fix it up.
</P>
<P>
   ''He found a little house. He was in love with a girl. Now he's
18, driving his taxi around Freetown, doing very well,'' De Burca
said.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Karisio, now 18, had to find her own path to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Abducted and taken to a rebel training camp in southern Sudan in
1991 at age 9, she had already been separated from her parents
during a bombing raid.
</P>
<P>
   After five months in the rebel camp, where she learned to take
apart guns and put them back together, she escaped and spent the
next several years drifting from one refugee camp to another.
</P>
<P>
   Nightmares haunted her. She would see the blood of her friend
spurt out, or remember how the rebels killed her brother in front
of her.
</P>
<P>
   At age 16, in Kenya, she found Sister Lucy, a Roman Catholic nun
who befriended her and helped her attend high school. With the
sister's guidance, Grace discovered solace in the thought that she
had no choice but to shoot her friend.
</P>
<P>
   ''You do what you have to do to survive,'' Grace said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Grace emigrated to Canada, where she now lives by
herself in an apartment in Winnipeg. She still wonders about her
parents. But she has a job and is attending high school.
</P>
<P>
   She is a youth delegate to this week's conference and hopes it
will make a difference for children back in Sudan and other
war-scarred nations.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she suggests a vital step for helping any child
of war.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need somebody to support them, to let them know that what
happened is not their fault,'' Grace said. ''They need somebody to
give them love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0107 </TRAILER>
