<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Worries Plague Rio Grande  </HEADLINE>
By MEGAN K. STACK
<TEXT>
<P>
   McALLEN, Texas (AP) -- When the retired engineer at the back of
the room fired off his question, the room fell quiet for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ''What good is a water right if there's no water?'' Ralph
Niehaus asked. ''You can't irrigate with a piece of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads bobbed in agreement throughout the city chambers, where
farmers and families gathered last week to discuss a drafted plan
that would dictate Rio Grande Valley water use for the next half
century. ''Amen,'' muttered a gray-haired man.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, irrigators do have shortages,'' agreed Mike Personett, a
water consultant with the regional water planning group. ''Those
shortages can get better over time, but they're not going to go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   That realization is sinking in as these border communities hash
out a water usage plan for the next 50 years. Eight counties
between Eagle Pass and Brownsville must present a proposal to the
state by late September. All 16 Texas water regions are drawing up
similar plans.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, a draft of the South Texas plan is up for public
comment at meetings along the northern bank of the Rio Grande.
Hearings are scheduled Wednesday in Brownsville and Thursday in
Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearings, one thing was clear: These are sobering times
for South Texas farmers. Rio Grande irrigation will have to be
revamped -- and even drastic changes might not be enough to keep
farms afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation is getting worse and worse for the producer,''
said Rod Santa Ana, spokesman for the Texas A&AMP;M Agricultural
Research and Extension Service in Weslaco. ''And this is still a
huge agricultural area -- agriculture is what settled the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   When water runs low, irrigators are the first to feel a pinch.
Farms occupy a relatively lowly seat in the complicated realm of
water rights. Water goes to the fields only after cities, industry
and steam electric plants are satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ''Irrigators are the residual users,'' said Personett. ''They
get what's left over. Industry and municipal get an ironclad
right.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2050, population and water projections show the Rio Grande
Valley will have just half the water it will need.
</P>
<P>
   The planning group is urging farmers to line dirt canals with
cement, and bury open piping underground to reduce spills and
seepage. Water districts may end up metering flows more thoroughly,
or raising the price of water to encourage conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in irrigation can help stretch water's worth -- but can't
guarantee enough water for all Valley farmers. The water shortage
is fueled by two uncontrollable forces: Severe drought and foreign
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, Mexico has fallen deep into water debt. The nation
now owes U.S. farmers and cities about 1.4 million acre-feet of
water.
</P>
<P>
   The water debt is a burr in United States-Mexico relations --
South Texas representatives say they are no longer invited to
Mexico's meetings, and no change is in sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0107 </TRAILER>
