<DOCNO> APW20000913.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Port Remembers War Landing  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   INCHON, South Korea (AP) -- To figure out who, ultimately, won
the Korean War, gaze out from Inchon onto the mud flats of the
Yellow Sea, where a $5 billion airport is going up on reclaimed
land.
</P>
<P>
   While communist North Korea struggles to feed its people, its
southern rival is moving its economy full speed ahead -- and nowhere
more strikingly than around Inchon, the port city where American
and South Korean troop landings changed the course of the Korean
War.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, the fact that a celebratory re-enactment of
the landings was recently canceled is one of many signals that the
hatreds that have divided the Korean peninsula for 50 years may
finally be nearing an end.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is the 50th anniversary of the Inchon landings which,
after D-Day at Normandy, were the greatest and perhaps riskiest
amphibious assault in history. The invading communist north was
routed, and Gen. Douglas MacArthur, the American mastermind of the
United Nations-led operation, became a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Today, mammoth freighters ply the ''Flying Fish Channel'' where
U.S. warships had to navigate, with only a six-hour window for a
successful landing in the notoriously tricky tides of South Korea's
western coast. Giant spider-like wharf cranes dominate the
landscape of what used to be the mud flats and seawalls U.S.
Marines had to climb.
</P>
<P>
   But to the people of Inchon, the memory has not faded.
</P>
<P>
   ''History is alive. We know that what American and U.N. troops
did here saved our country,'' said Chung Sang-wan, 41, one of
dozens of people strolling on the hilltop Freedom Park, which
overlooks the now peaceful channel.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of U.S. and South Korean veterans and relatives will
gather here Thursday and Friday for ceremonies beginning with a
remembrance of the six ''Sitting Ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   These were destroyers that sailed up the narrow channel to test
North Korean defenses and trade shell fire. Two days later, an
American-led U.N. naval fleet with bigger guns crept up the
channel. At dawn on Sept. 15, 1950, shells slammed the shore and
U.S. and British planes swarmed over Inchon, knocking out the enemy
fire before 1st Division U.S. Marines overran Wolmi Island and
pressed on to Inchon.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-foot tides, hidden guns and seawalls, and the danger of
landing in an exposed harbor, made the operation seem suicidal. But
that also meant Inchon's beaches would be lightly defended. ''Hit
them where they ain't,'' was MacArthur's dictum, and he triumphed.
</P>
<P>
   About 13,000 Marines poured off flat-bottomed landing craft and
went ashore that day, at a cost of 21 dead and 153 wounded. The
communists' sweeping advance in the first weeks of the war was soon
reversed. Seoul, the capital, 25 miles inland, fell within 12 days,
and the allied forces pinned down on the southern tip of the Korean
peninsula were relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Graying Inchon veterans such as Kim Nak-hyun, 70, still revere
MacArthur and proudly carry ''MacArthur sunglasses'' on their
belts.
</P>
<P>
   The general later was fired after clashing with President Harry
S. Truman. MacArthur saw no substitute for total victory in Korea,
even if that meant full-scale war with China. Truman feared
hostilities might escalate into World War III.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur came home a hero, and delivered his memorable farewell
line: ''Old soldiers never die; they just fade away.''
</P>
<P>
   ''For us, he never faded away,'' said Hur Young-chul, another
70-year-old veteran.
</P>
<P>
   After their successes at Inchon the allies suffered severe
reverses when Chinese troops entered the war. The fighting became
stalemated and ended in a truce signed July 27, 1953.
</P>
<P>
   At Freedom Park, a 20-foot bronze statue built with citizens'
donations shows MacArthur gazing seaward. Frolicking kindergartners
chased pigeons near the inscription that in part said:
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a deed and this is a man to hold eternally in honored
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterans will remember the dead by setting flowers adrift on the
channel and near the ''Blue Beach,'' one of the three stormed by
allied forces.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the leaders of North and South Korea have met for the
first time, a tentative reconciliation has begun. On Monday, a
North Korean emissary arrived bearing gifts of mushrooms, amid
speculation he is scouting out sites for a historic visit by North
Korean leader Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the Inchon landings were to have been re-enacted for
the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of the war. But in the new
spirit of detente, the Seoul government canceled the event.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in their ramshackle office decorated with pictures of
the landing and slogans such as ''Old soldiers are still alive,''
the Korean veterans lamented the cancellation of the re-enactment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are all old,'' Kim said, ''and this would have been our
last chance to march in our proud uniform and let young generations
know that only a strong military guarantees peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0108 </TRAILER>
