<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Wins N.Y. Senate Primary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With 16 percent of precincts reporting, Hillary Rodham
Clinton won New York's Democratic Senate primary Monday. Clinton had 71,714
votes or 78 percent and orthopedic surgeon Mark McMahon had 20,481 votes or 22
percent. As nine states and the District of Columbia held contests on the last
big primary day of 2000, the first lady built a wide lead over McMahon en route
to her contest against unopposed Republican Rep. Rick Lazio in November. With 16
percent of precincts reporting, Clinton had 71,714 votes or 78 percent and
McMahon had 20,481 votes or 22 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Chase To Acquire J.P. Morgan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp. has agreed to acquire J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co. for about $36 billion in stock, creating a union between two of the oldest
and most prestigious financial firms in the United States, according to a
report. Citing people familiar with the matter, The Wall Street Journal reported
late Tuesday that the boards of both companies have approved the deal and could
make an announcement as early as Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vt. Lawmakers Ousted Over Gay Law
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- Five Republican state legislators who supported the
law granting gay couples many of the rights and benefits of marriage were
defeated in their primaries. And one Democrat who opposed the law was also
ousted. Four Republicans and one Democrat who backed the law and were targeted
for defeat because of it survived. Among lawmakers who were challenged because
of their opposition to the law, one was defeated and another was re-elected.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: 140 Unionists Vanished
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- At least half of the 140-plus union members who disappeared or
were killed last year came from Colombia, making it the world's most dangerous
place for organized labor, a labor group said in a report released Wednesday. In
its annual survey of violations of union rights, the International Confederation
of Free Trade Unions found that 676 death threats were issued against Colombian
unionists last year. At least 69 union members were killed, down from 91 the
previous year, and 22 were kidnapped.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bridgestone To Replace More Tires
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. announced Tuesday it will
replace the 1.4 million Firestone tires for which federal authorities issued a
warning. The company said it will replace the tires for free even if no defects
are found or reimburse up to $140 per tire for competitors' models. The National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration had issued a warning after the company
refused to expand a recall of 6.5 million tires. NHTSA said the tires could be
unsafe and suggested owners replace them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vaccinators Target Kids in Somalia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   QANSADHERE, Somalia (AP) -- Somalia recorded the world's last known case of
smallpox more than two decades ago. Six thousand workers fanning out across the
country, vaccines in hand, hope their beleaguered nation will not be the last to
eradicate polio as well. Armed with batches of oral polio vaccine and bottles of
liquid Vitamin A, the workers headed into the field Tuesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Dismisses 'Rats' Ad
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican TV ad that flashes the word ''RATS'' across
the screen is coming off the air amid charges the GOP sought to send a
subliminal message about Democart Al Gore. George W. Bush called the notion
''bizarre and weird,'' and his presidential campaign made light of it all. The
admaker said he was just trying to make the spot visually interesting. ''I've
never seen anything like it,'' said Gore. His running mate, Joseph Lieberman,
called the ad ''very disappointing and strange.''
</P>
