<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Applauds China Action  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The White House applauded China for
withdrawing more than 20 Olympic athletes who failed doping tests,
saying the action signaled that Beijing is truly committed to
cracking down on drug cheats.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Barry McCaffrey, director of the White House drug policy
office, said Wednesday he sent a letter to China's sports minister
congratulating him for the decision to drop 27 athletes and 13
officials from the team for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a tremendous demonstration of their seriousness of
purpose of acting against doping in their own teams,'' McCaffrey
told The Associated Press shortly after his arrival in Sydney.
''It's a terrific signal that they are committed.''
</P>
<P>
   After a week of saying that injuries, illness and poor
performance were involved in some cases, Chinese officials said
Tuesday that nearly all of the 27 athletes cut from the Olympic
team failed drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   He Huixian, the Chinese Olympic Committee's spokeswoman, said
''the overwhelming majority'' had suspicious results in blood tests
for the performance-enhancing drug EPO.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were six runners trained by famed coach Ma Junren,
whose record-smashing ''Ma's Army'' stunned the world in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese sports have been riddled with drug scandals in recent
years, but none involving so many people in one series of tests. In
addition to the athletes, the Chinese cut 13 coaches including Ma
from their squad.
</P>
<P>
   By leaving home those who failed drug tests, Chinese sports
officials may have improved Beijing's bid for the 2008 Olympics and
avoided a repeat of embarrassing doping scandals at the 1994 Asian
Games and 1998 swimming world championships.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some view these busts as a scandal,'' McCaffrey said. ''In our
view it's exactly the right signal that the Chinese and the
international community mean business.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, who met with anti-doping officials in Beijing this
year, said he will have more talks with the Chinese during his stay
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey had been a strident critic of the International
Olympic Committee and its anti-doping policies. But he said
Wednesday that important progress has been made in the past 18
months -- including creation of the World Anti-Doping Agency,
implementation of more than 2,000 unannounced out-of-competition
controls worldwide and approval of a test for the banned
endurance-boosting hormone EPO.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly this is the beginning of a new era,'' McCaffrey said.
''The Sydney Olympics will be the most drug tested games in the
history of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot to be proud of,'' he added. ''Having said that,
we are probably a third of where we need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said he will attend meetings of the World Anti-Doping
Agency in Sydney and hold talks with a number of international
officials, including IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch. One of
his priorities is to push for greater independence of WADA, which
is still based in the IOC's home city of Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   One of McAffrey's aides, Robert Housman, is among the 15
independent observers designated by WADA to monitor drug-testing
procedures in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question we will never see again a repeat of what
happened in Los Angeles (1984) and Atlanta (1996), where you had
missing samples, destroyed evidence,'' McCaffrey said. ''I think
those days are over.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said he also will meet with Canadian and Australian
government officials in Oslo, Norway, on Nov. 15-17 to review the
experience of Sydney and work on expanding the anti-doping efforts
for the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has to be a common list of banned substances and
accepted scientific standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   IOC members have complained about a study, financed and released
by the White House last week, that criticized the international
committee and other sports organizations for failing to do enough
to combat the use of banned performance-enhancing drugs in the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The report was prepared by Joseph A. Califano Jr., president of
the National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   IOC officials have called the report misguided and out of date.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said he found the IOC response ''curious.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers ''did a superb piece of work,'' he said. ''We
welcome their report. It gives a tremendous insight into the
problems we are facing. It's just really a call to action. ... The
question isn't finger- pointing. We don't need defensiveness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
