<HEADLINE> Mo. Man Executed for 1998 Slaying  </HEADLINE>
By JIM SALTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   POTOSI, Mo. (AP) -- A convicted killer was executed by injection
early Wednesday for the 1989 slaying of a man following a dispute
over machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   George ''Baby'' Harris, 41, was condemned for shooting to death
Stanley ''Hank'' Willoughby inside a Kansas City crack house.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Harris had won a large amount of money playing
an illegal game of craps on March 11, 1989. Another man at the game
needed money and offered to pawn two machine guns to Harris for
$500.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, concerned the weapons would be stolen from his trunk,
gave them to Willoughby for safekeeping. Willoughby took the guns
to the crack house, where other men hid them in bushes in the back
yard, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   When Harris tried to retrieve the guns, Willoughby told him he
didn't know where they were. Harris believed Willoughby was trying
to steal the weapons, according to testimony at Harris' trial.
</P>
<P>
   The two men later argued inside the house, and Harris shot
Willoughby in the face and throat with a .41-caliber revolver.
Harris fled but was caught by police four days later.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he shot Willoughby after the man moved toward him
and reached for a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ''This ain't no first-degree murder,'' Harris said in a recent
interview. ''I shot the man in self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris was the fourth Missouri inmate put to death this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
