<DOCNO> APW20000913.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators To Probe Media Content  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's shaping up to be a tough week for the
people who produce and distribute movies, video games, pop music
and television shows.
</P>
<P>
   First, a scathing Federal Trade Commission report claimed the
entertainment industry was peddling adult material to underage
audiences. Then federal media regulators announced they would take
a closer look at the amount of sex and violence on the major TV
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidential campaigns latched onto the issue -- one that
resonates strongly with Americans concerned about the exposure of
young adults to sex and violence. Al Gore said he was prepared, if
elected to the White House, to crack down on the industry if it did
not stop marketing violent movies, recordings and video games to
underage youth within six months.
</P>
<P>
   His Republican opponent, George W. Bush, questioned Gore's
credibility on the issue and said the solution should rest with
parents and political persuasion, not new federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gore's running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, a
longtime critic of explicit content in the media, was to confront
entertainment executives at a Senate hearing. Lieberman and Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., who was chairing the Senate Commerce
Committee hearing, backed a measure last year that requested the
FTC study on entertainment violence.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had their own representative at the hearing -- Lynne
Cheney, wife of the Republican vice presidential nominee and former
head of the National Endowment for the Humanities, who said
entertainment violence ''debases and degrades the culture our
children are growing up in.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC report decried the entertainment industry's ''pervasive
and aggressive marketing'' of adult material -- such as R-rated
movies or video games intended for mature audiences -- to children.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from the study was felt Tuesday in Hollywood, as the
Walt Disney Co. announced changes in its marketing practices,
including a prohibition against theater owners showing trailers for
R-rated films before movies released under the Walt Disney label.
The Disney-owned ABC network also will not accept advertisements
for R-rated films during prime time before 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Disney said it would not show R-rated films -- released under its
Touchstone, Hollywood Pictures and Miramax Films labels -- to focus
groups under age 17 and would urge theater owners to more strictly
enforce the age restriction. The company does not release R-rated
films under the Walt Disney label.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, head of the Motion Picture Association of America,
acknowledged it was not suitable to target R-rated films to very
young children, but asserted that the FTC's report was based on
subjective judgments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the commission determined that R-rated movies were
advertised on TV programs most popular with the under-17 group.
But, Valenti said, for many of these shows, the majority of the
audience is 18 and over.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not dealing with Euclid's geometry where the equations
are pristine and explicit,'' he said in remarks prepared for
delivery at Wednesday's hearing. Still, he promised that the
industry would examine how it advertises and conducts research so
that it does not deliberately target underage viewers.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop calls by South Carolina Attorney General
Charlie Condon for state prosecutors to band together in a lawsuit
against Hollywood, akin to the action states took against the
tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission extended the sphere of
scrutiny to the airwaves by announcing Tuesday it would examine
whether broadcasters were promoting inappropriate programming when
children were likely to be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that broadcasters' obligation is not only to
protect children from objectionable programming but also to offer
positive and educational programming for children,'' FCC Chairman
William Kennard said in a letter to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard scheduled FCC hearings on the content of broadcast TV
for October, after a group of senators, including Lieberman and
McCain, complained about sexual vulgarity and violence on TV
several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The senators have questioned whether broadcasters, who enjoy
free access to the public airwaves, are providing programming that
benefits the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard joined Lieberman in calling for broadcasters to revive a
voluntary industry programming code to ensure the appropriateness
of programming during times children are likely to be watching.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Broadcasters declined to comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Senate Commerce Committee site:
http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)commerce
</P>
<P>
   Federal Communications Commission site: http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America site: http://www.mpaa.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0137 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Trade To U.S. Increasing  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's been on the agenda of the government's
Africa experts virtually every day for the past two months: How
many of the 50 or so sub-Saharan African countries qualify for
trade benefits under new legislation that will take effect at the
end of the month?
</P>
<P>
   Domestic and cross-border strife afflict many African countries,
and there are even pockets of slavery on the continent. Officials
say the debate over eligibility for the benefits has been feverish.
</P>
<P>
   This past spring, Congress decided to upgrade Africa's status as
an economic partner by approving legislation to give certain
African products duty-free and quota-free access to U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   Beforehand, Africa and Antarctica were the only continents where
the United States did not have a trade policy. The great bulk of
Africa's exports to the United States has consisted of oil from
Nigeria and Angola. But with the passage of the Africa Growth and
Opportunity Act, the prospects of wider African sales to American
markets has increased.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Cold War has enabled the United States to deal
with African countries on their merits, as opposed to how they
stand ideologically.
</P>
<P>
   Trade is one of a number of fronts on which the Clinton
administration has been moving in its Africa policy. It also is
seeking congressional approval of $435 million in debt relief for
Africa's poorest nations. Assistance levels are reaching all-time
highs. And efforts are being made to help Africa deal with its AIDS
crisis, albeit on terms less generous than many African governments
want.
</P>
<P>
   The new law says African countries will be excluded from the
trade benefits if they are considered hostile to U.S. interests,
have a poor human rights record or pursue economic policies deemed
unsound.
</P>
<P>
   The task of administration officials is to decide which
countries will make the cut and which won't. They are reluctant to
talk about individual countries except to confirm that Sudan,
regarded here as having one of the continent's nastiest human
rights records, will not qualify. Two years ago, U.S. cruise
missiles destroyed a pharmaceutical plant believed to be linked to
terrorist operations. Sudan has denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Among the surest bets to make the list is Nigeria, a favorite of
Washington these days after a democratic government was installed
in 1999 following years of military dictatorships. President
Clinton visited Nigeria last month to show his support.
</P>
<P>
   Salih Booker, director of the Africa Fund, which advocates
positive U.S. policies toward the continent, says he believes about
30 African countries will qualify for the trade benefits, or about
60 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Booker is less enthusiastic about the trade bill than is
Clinton, who says the new approach ''reaffirms America's commitment
to open trade and strengthens the partnership between the United
States and our friends in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation says nations that qualify are entitled to
export, without duties or quotas, apparel made with U.S. yarn and
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing made from African fabric would be allowed to rise from
1.5 percent of U.S. imports to 3.5 percent over eight years,
boosting African exports of these products from about $250 million
a year now to as much as $4.2 billion, according to estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not generous,'' says Booker, citing an effective lobbying
effort by textile companies and textile unions.
</P>
<P>
   Over the short term, Booker believes the new law will lead to
expanded apparel imports from Kenya, Mauritius, South Africa and
maybe a few others. There may be increases in exports of leather
goods as well, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration contends that the legislation would
result in minimal job loss for U.S. workers and also would open the
way for increased investment in African countries.
</P>
<P>
   The suspense over which countries qualify will end in less than
three weeks when Clinton announces the administration's choices.
</P>
<P>
   Not all countries are eager to be chosen. They prefer not to
embrace U.S. prescriptions for economic reform, including
reductions in public spending, contending this would only leave
their peoples more destitute.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
