<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Sept. 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hillary Clinton Wins N.Y. Senate Primary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton won New York's Democratic Senate
primary Monday. Clinton had 71,714 votes or 78 percent and orthopedic surgeon
Mark McMahon had 20,481 votes or 22 percent. As nine states and the District of
Columbia held contests on the last big primary day of 2000, the first lady built
a wide lead over McMahon en route to her contest against unopposed Republican
Rep. Rick Lazio in November. With 16 percent of precincts reporting, Clinton had
71,714 votes or 78 percent and McMahon had 20,481 votes or 22 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chase Reportedly To Acquire J.P. Morgan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp. has agreed to buy J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
for about $36 billion in stock, according to a report. Citing people familiar
with the matter, The Wall Street Journal reported late Tuesday that the boards
of both companies have approved the deal and could make an announcement as early
as Wednesday. A potential merger between banking powerhouses Chase and J.P.
Morgan is seen by analysts as a good match because the two firms' array of
services complement each other.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Debate Goers Older, Educated
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Memo to the presidential candidates: More than half of
Americans plan to watch the debates and think they will be an important factor
in how they vote. A few other things you might want to know? Debate watchers
tend to be age 35 and older, middle-income or higher, at least partially college
educated, registered to vote and a member of one of the two major political
parties, says an Associated Press poll. More who plan to watch say Democrat Al
Gore will do better in the debates than Republican George W. Bush by 49-29,
according to the poll conducted for the AP by ICR of Media, Pa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bridgestone To Replace More Tires
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. announced Tuesday it will
replace the 1.4 million Firestone tires for which federal authorities issued a
warning. The company said it will replace the tires for free even if no defects
are found or reimburse up to $140 per tire for competitors' models. The National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration had issued a warning after the company
refused to expand a recall of 6.5 million tires. NHTSA said the tires could be
unsafe and suggested owners replace them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Organ Donation Edges Up
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Organ donation increased by nearly 4 percent during the
first half of 2000 after remaining flat in 1999, the government said Tuesday.
During the first six months of this year, there were 2,978 organ donors. That
compares to 2,875 during the first six months of 1999, according to statistics
compiled by the Department of Health and Human Service and the Association of
Organ Procurement Organizations. Organ donation rose 6 percent in 1998, the
first substantial increase since 1995, but was unchanged in 1999.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Dismisses 'Rats' Ad
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican TV ad that flashes the word ''RATS'' across
the screen is coming off the air amid charges the GOP sought to send a
subliminal message about Democart Al Gore. George W. Bush called the notion
''bizarre and weird,'' and his presidential campaign made light of it all. The
admaker said he was just trying to make the spot visually interesting. ''I've
never seen anything like it,'' said Gore. His running mate, Joseph Lieberman,
called the ad ''very disappointing and strange.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Surge
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks surged Wednesday morning on bargain hunting in
reaction to recent losses. The dollar was higher against the yen. The Nikkei
Stock Average gained 225.28 points, or 1.40 percent, to 16,265.51 at the end of
the morning session. In New York, the Dow rose 37.74 points to 11,233.23 at
Tuesday's close. The Nasdaq fell 46.84 points to end at 3,849.51.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knight Wants To Coach Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- While he's not sure where, Bob Knight says he wants
to coach again ''in the worst way.'' Knight, fired by Indiana for a pattern of
''unacceptable'' behavior, spoke out Tuesday on ESPN. ''I haven't retired,'' he
said. Indiana hired assistant Mike Davis as interim coach.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Applauds China Drug Action
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The White House applauded China for withdrawing
more than 20 Olympic athletes who failed doping tests, saying the action
signaled that Beijing is truly committed to cracking down on drug cheats. Gen.
Barry McCaffrey, director of the White House drug policy office, said Wednesday
he sent a letter to China's sports minister congratulating him for the decision
to drop 27 athletes and 13 officials from the team for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
