<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather woes stifle the hues  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - You may have to pay a little more for
your pumpkin this Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   That's the word from farmers and agriculture experts who say
this summer's wet, cool weather has significantly hurt much of the
upstate pumpkin crop.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pumpkins didn't get planted until very late because it was so
wet this spring. A lot won't make it in time for Halloween,'' said
Bob King, an agricultural expert at Cornell Cooperative Extension.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, pumpkins are likely to be late, more expensive and
maybe a little less orange this season.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Michaloski of Green Acre Fruit Farm in Greece predicts the
20 cents to 25 cents per pound average retail price could climb.
His advice: Buy early.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Herman of Herman's Farm Market and Cider Mill in Webster
planted his pumpkin crop over the Memorial Day weekend. But heavy
rain rotted all the seeds. So he replanted the entire eight acres
in early July.
</P>
<P>
   The unseasonable weather added insult to injury, as pumpkins
need heat and sun to ripen.
</P>
<P>
   These immature pumpkins have the heft but not the hue that makes
them desirable for Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   ''A green pumpkin isn't really marketable - maybe for
Christmas,'' said Herman, who hopes to start harvesting at the end
of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers expect to have pumpkins for sale by the last week of
the month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 0212 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers Negotiate Fate of Scientist  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- As prosecutors and defense attorneys
negotiated the fate of Wen Ho Lee, the man at the center of the
dispute -- once vilified, now pitied -- waited in solitary
confinement.
</P>
<P>
   A plea deal concerning the nuclear scientist underwent attempts
at revision Tuesday. Prosecutors filed a sealed document relating
to the plea but did not respond to calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys also had no comment on negotiations, and
nobody was predicting any outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   A court hearing was scheduled Wednesday to address the proposed
agreement that would drop 58 counts against Lee, leaving one count
and no further prison time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're optimistic that the plea bargain is going to go through
and that there won't be anything to make it hit a snag,'' Lee's
neighbor, Don Marshall, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall and his wife Jean, who plan a homecoming in Los Alamos,
visited Lee's wife, Sylvia. Marshall said the Lee family, too, was
''cautiously optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's plea bargain, as envisioned Sunday, was at least partly
based on a trade: Lee would tell prosecutors what they wanted in
exchange for the reduced charges. Then he could walk away a free
man having been sentenced to nine months he has already served in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   It included assurances that Lee had destroyed the seven tapes --
something he has sworn from the outset -- and that he would submit
to questioning under oath, take a polygraph and tell, in detail,
why he made the tapes and what he did with them.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was fired from Los Alamos in March 1999 and nine months
later was charged with downloading restricted nuclear data to
unsecured computers and tapes. He could have faced life in prison
if convicted of all 59 counts.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began as an offshoot of a fizzled Chinese
espionage case, with government attorneys making dire accusations
that Lee downloaded the ''crown jewels'' of U.S. nuclear science
and might be poised to hand them over to a foreign power.
</P>
<P>
   But the case began disintegrating last month at a renewed bail
hearing. FBI agent Robert Messemer, whose testimony was key in
initially denying Lee bail in December, said he repeatedly erred in
that testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal described Sunday by government sources, Lee also
was expected to drop allegations that he was targeted because he is
Chinese, claims included in a civil lawsuit against the FBI and the
Energy and Justice departments.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Washington-based Judicial Watch said it was suing
Lee and others on behalf of Notra Trulock, a former Energy
Department counterintelligence chief. Lee's lawyers have said
Trulock was among those who unfairly singled Lee out.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch said Trulock, in a defamation complaint, alleges
Lee and others ''scapegoated'' Trulock to divert attention from
security lapses at Los Alamos National Laboratory. Lee's lawyers
declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Lee: http://www.wenholee.org
</P>
<P>
   Department of Justice: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0213 </TRAILER>
