<HEADLINE> House Nears Trade Tax Breaks Bill  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hoping to avert a trade war with Europe, the
House was rushing to pass legislation enacting new tax breaks for
U.S. companies to replace a system ruled an illegal export subsidy
by the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is extremely important that we send a message to the
Europeans that we're serious about this,'' said Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee. ''The
mother of all trade wars is something to be avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed by the Clinton administration, Congress intends to pass
the bill before an Oct. 1 deadline set by the WTO, which
invalidated the U.S. Foreign Sales Corporation tax rules after they
were challenged by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO set the deadline to give the United States time to enact
a replacement law without retaliatory tariffs from the EU. European
officials contend that this new system is also illegal, but U.S.
officials said they would press ahead to prevent tariffs or
sanctions on up to $40 billion in U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstadt said the bill
represents ''the only way in which we can avoid the potential for
an immediate conflict with the EU, with the possibility of
significant retaliation on their part.''
</P>
<P>
   A final House vote was set for Wednesday. The Senate was
expected to follow suit in short order.
</P>
<P>
   Created to offset an EU tax rebate for its exporters, the
Foreign Sales Corporation program permits U.S. companies to reduce
income taxes by 15 percent through export subsidiaries set up in
offshore tax havens such as Barbados and the Virgin Islands.
Microsoft, Boeing and General Motors are only a few of the 6,000
companies, with 4.8 million workers, that get the $4.1 billion
annual tax break.
</P>
<P>
   The replacement legislation, costing the government roughly the
same amount each year, would set up new tax breaks that apply
equally to exports by U.S. companies and the products they make
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO ruling against the previous rules centered on their
nature as special exceptions in tax law. Efforts to reach a
diplomatic solution failed.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats decried the bill as corporate welfare and
expressed dismay that it was brought to the House floor under rules
preventing any amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it quacks like a subsidy and walks like a subsidy, it's
still a subsidy,'' said Rep. Fortney Stark, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to House GOP leaders, Reps. Lloyd Doggett of Texas
and Henry Waxman of California said the current program amounts to
a $100 million tax break for tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Estimating that smoking causes 3.5 million deaths a year around
the world, the two legislators said ''American taxpayers should not
be partner in this export of death and disease, where the result is
more children around the globe smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4986.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   To search for the bill: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
