<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 04:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Skeptical of GOP Offer  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clinton administration officials and top
congressional Democrats are suspicious of a pre-election Republican
offer to use 90 percent of next year's expected budget surplus to
drive down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans made the offer Tuesday at a White House meeting
among President Clinton and congressional leaders that also covered
health-care proposals and other issues remaining in this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The session, which lasted more than an hour, produced little
substantive progress.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans were hoping the meeting would be a prelude to a
bipartisan, end-of-year deal on spending and tax cuts that would
let lawmakers head home for re-election campaigns by mid-October.
The GOP proposal on the surplus would, in effect, leave about $27
billion for tax cuts and spending increases that lawmakers want for
fiscal 2001, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   With that money, ''We can provide the funding we need for
agriculture and education and tax relief for small businesses and
encourage savings'' and make pension plans more generous, Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' plan seemed to be an effort to establish
themselves as the party that favors debt reduction, and to draw a
line that Clinton dare not cross with his demands for billions in
extra spending. With control of both the White House and Congress
at stake in November, polls show that debt reduction is a favorite
of voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's own budget also would use more than 90 percent of
projected surpluses for debt reduction next year. He would use all
the remaining money for extra spending, not tax cuts. House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., suggested splitting the remaining funds
evenly between extra spending and tax cuts, said participants who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they, too, favor setting aside as much as
possible for debt reduction. But participants said Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers and others said the GOP plan could allow
tax cuts that would mushroom over the next decade and erode
Clinton's plans to eliminate the publicly held portion of the
national debt by 2012.
</P>
<P>
   ''We smell a rat,'' Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials and Democrats also argued that if the GOP
applied its 90 percent formula to the next decade, it would
preclude the $1.3 trillion, 10-year tax cut proposed by the
Republican presidential nominee, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need to tell us what it is they're for,'' said Daschle.
''If they're for a real plan, they're going to have to separate
themselves from their presidential candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, Republicans did not specify how they would
spend the $27 billion next year, attendees said.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans did suggest using some of the money to eliminate
the federal telephone tax and cut taxes on some small businesses,
pensions and development in inner cities, said participants from
both parties. That seemed to be an implicit acknowledgment that the
GOP's highest-profile tax cuts -- on many married couples and large
estates -- would not become law this year. Both have been vetoed by
Clinton, and Republicans lack the votes to reverse him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remaining priorities this year include more spending
for education and giving consumers the right to sue insurance
companies for inadequate care. He also wants new prescription drug
benefits under Medicare, an expanded hate-crimes law, a minimum
wage increase, a long-term health care credit and ''new markets''
tax breaks to spur investment in depressed communities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we ought to do just as much as we possibly can,''
Clinton said before the meeting began.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want reduced taxes for workers and small businesses,
and increased spending and for education. Lott said he hoped the
Senate would complete work this week or next on a major trade bill
with China.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said the meeting
left him dubious that broadened patients' rights or drug benefits
will be approved this year. Both have been considered long-shots
for some time because of political differences over the size and
scope of the packages.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla.,
said there would be no expansion of managed-care patients' rights
this year ''if people are going to be playing partisan games.''
Daschle said Republicans threatened to filibuster a House-approved
version of the bill, which Nickles said would increase health-care
costs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, just two of the 13 annual spending bills for 2001 have
been signed into law. Republicans are hoping that serious
negotiations on the remaining measures will now begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 0441 </TRAILER>
