<HEADLINE> Dow Slips 39; Nasdaq Gains 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading Wednesday on
news of a merger between two of the country's largest banks and
continued nervousness about third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 39.40 at 11,193.83.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 2.15 to 3,851.66, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 7.71 at 1,474.28.
</P>
<P>
   Before the market opened, Chase Manhattan Bank announced it was
acquiring J.P. Morgan for about $36 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan traded down $8.19 at $177.25 in early trading, after
weeks of its stock price inching upward on rumors that it was an
acquisition target. Chase Manhattan fell $2.63 to $49.88.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of corporate earnings unsettled the market.
</P>
<P>
   Most businesses won't report results until next month, but some
have already began hinting at what to expect. The market has fallen
into a pattern of rewarding those with strong results and outlooks,
and punishing those who falter.
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy closed Tuesday up $4.75 at $69.19 after the consumer
electronics retailer beat Wall Street estimates for second-quarter
earnings. The same day, the market sent shares of PRI Automation
down nearly 40 percent,, falling $16.81 to $25.88, after the
factory automation systems maker said fourth-quarter earnings would
not meet expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The market closed mixed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down Wednesday at 1.82 at 530.61.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Dow, Nasdaq and S&AMP;P all declined, continuing
losses from Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average was up 0.94 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 1.69 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 1.46 percent, and France's CAC-40 was off
1.48 percent.
</P>
<P>
