<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY Opera Season Opens Favorably  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A new production of ''Roberto Devereux'' has
scenery which looks like a modern nightclub, striking costumes and
a baritone who steals the show.
</P>
<P>
   Voices were good; one was better than that. But anyone who was
in the audience in 1970 when the company first did the piece --
opera lovers who Julius Rudel conduct, and saw Beverly Sills' Queen
Elizabeth I drum her fists on the arms of her throne -- missed the
passion and excitement of those performances.
</P>
<P>
   There is drama in Donizetti's music, so excitement wasn't
entirely missing. Tuesday's performance -- which opened the fall
season for the City Opera -- just didn't have that extra frisson of
thrill that great performances have.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Flanagan, the company's reigning soprano, hit her notes
squarely and produced volume when it was needed. But she has seemed
more comfortable in other roles. Mezzo-soprano Jane Dutton made her
New York City Opera debut as the Duchess of Nottingham. Her voice
has the clarity of a bell-like soprano. Tenor Fernando De La Mora
also was making his debut with the company, in the title role. His
voice is dark, and pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Delavan as the Duke of Nottingham has a warm, rich baritone
of remarkable beauty. Even when he berated his wife, his tones were
round. Delavan, like the late Leonard Warren, can unbalance a cast
of singers; he pulls the audience to him even when he isn't singing
the leading role.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lamos directed. Both the set designer, Andrew Lieberman,
and the costume designer, Judy Levin, make their City Opera debuts
with this production.
</P>
<P>
   And both the sets and the costumes are worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   The set had a red-floored stage at one side with three wide red
steps down. On one side of that stage was ''Gloriana'' spelled in
vertically in red neon. On the other side was a blue neon ''Regina
XIII'' -- for Elizabeth, the 13th queen of England. Across from all
that, the throne sat on a blue square lighted from inside. Above
the throne was a theater marquee with ''Elisabetta'' written on two
sides.
</P>
<P>
   The Elizabethan costumes were mostly red, black and white. The
red-wigged chorus -- which is a chorus in this opera, not
townspeople -- usually stood in rows on the red stage. This produced
attractive tableaux and, while the scenery and costumes were
incongruous, they didn't annoy.
</P>
<P>
   George Manahan conducted. The New York City Opera's fall season
runs through Nov. 19 at the New York State Theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1117 </TRAILER>
