<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 35; Nasdaq Rises 23  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Wednesday on news of a merger
between two of the country's largest banks and continued
nervousness about third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 35.15 to 11,198.08.
</P>
<P>
   But broader stock indicators moved higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 2.79 at 1,484.78 , and
the Nasdaq composite index rose 22.62 to 3,872.13.
</P>
<P>
   Before the market opened, Chase Manhattan Bank announced it was
acquiring J.P. Morgan for about $36 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan traded down $6.31 at $179.13 in morning trading,
after weeks of its stock price inching upward on rumors that it was
an acquisition target. Chase Manhattan fell $2.31 to $50.19.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also continued to monitor corporate earnings
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Although most businesses won't report results until next month,
some have already began hinting at what to expect. The market has
fallen into its pattern of rewarding those who deliver strong
profits and outlooks, and punishing those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   SCI Systems was off $13, about 23 percent, at $42.94 after the
electronics manufacturer said its quarterly results would fall
below expectations, because of seasonal weakness in demand for its
products. SCI also said it is acquiring an Australian-based
telecommunications business to expand its global reach.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sherwin Williams dropped $2.63 to $21.25 after the
paint company said quarterly earnings would not meet Wall Street
expectations because of higher raw material costs and tough
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still half a month away from actual earnings season, but
we've already had key reports like DuPont saying it will be down.
The market has not taken that news well,'' said Ricky Harrington, a
senior vice president at Wachovia Securities in Charlotte, N.C.
''It's somewhat subjective, but I think the runup of stocks that we
saw before Labor Day has set the stage for downside surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   DuPont shares fell sharply last week after the chemical company
said its earnings would be below expectations because of rising
costs and soft markets.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 345.09 million
shares, compared with 320.04 million in the last session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.57 at 533.00.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
