<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville: John Michael Montgomery  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PATTERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Serious is selling again in the country
music industry. And an old-fashioned tear-jerker is shaping up as
one of the year's most talked-about country singles.
</P>
<P>
   John Michael Montgomery's ''The Little Girl,'' written by
Nashville songwriter Harley Allen, is a song about child abuse,
murder and suicide. An orphaned girl sees a picture of Jesus Christ
while attending Sunday School for the first time. She identifies
him as the man who comforted her as she hid behind a couch on the
night her father killed her mother and then himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to show I could sing a song with a serious issue in
it,'' said Montgomery. ''It was kind of a 50-50 risk. ... We could
have had people going, 'It's talking about religious issues, it's
talking about killing people; we don't want that on our radio
waves.'''
</P>
<P>
   The single shot into the Top 15 on the Billboard country singles
chart just five weeks after its release. The song is included on
Montgomery's ''Brand New Me'' CD (Atlantic Records).
</P>
<P>
   ''We played the song once and got about 75 calls,'' said Michael
J. Foxx, the music director at WPOC in Baltimore. ''This song ranks
in the top five of all time in positive testing in the history of
the station.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, who admits he's recorded his share of ''bubble gum''
country, hopes ''The Little Girl'' will have the commercial impact
of Brad Paisley's 1999 hit ''He Didn't Have to Be,'' a song that
praised stepparents.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, mainstream country got decidedly lighthearted.
There were a few hits with serious themes: Garth Brooks' ''The
Thunder Rolls'' in 1991 and Martina McBride's ''Independence Day''
in 1994 both dealt with domestic violence. Collin Raye carved a
niche for himself with such issue songs as ''I Think About You.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the decade wore on, the industry increasingly promoted
breezy, upbeat songs in an attempt to win over younger listeners.
Hit singles included Montgomery's silly tongue-twisting hits ''Be
My Baby Tonight'' (1994) and ''Sold (The Grundy County Auction
Incident)'' in 1995; Tracy Byrd's 1994 dance song ''Watermelon
Crawl''; Faith Hill's ''This Kiss'' in 1998, a sunny ode to first
love; and Kenny Chesney's trifling 1999 hit, ''She Thinks My
Tractor's Sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the tide appears to be turning with some significant songs
about serious topics.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Ann Womack scored her biggest hit ever with this year's
inspirational ''I Hope You Dance.'' Sonya Isaacs' single ''Barefoot
in the Grass'' is about a woman with terminal cancer. Child singer
Billy Gilman's first hit was ''One Voice,'' which tackled the issue
of guns in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Moorer's ''The Cold Cold Earth,'' a hidden track on her
new album, is the story of her parents' murder-suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Is ''The Little Girl'' a true story? The answer isn't clear.
Allen got the idea from a story that was posted on the Internet and
e-mailed to him by his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had those conversations about whether it was too (serious
and depressing) to be a hit,'' said Rick Baumgarner, who promotes
singles to radio stations for Atlantic Records, Montgomery's record
label.
</P>
<P>
   ''We finally realized that we needed to swing for the fences and
let the listeners decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Baumgarner said the success of the Dixie Chicks' ''Goodbye
Earl'' single was a factor in the decision to go ahead. That song,
about an abusive husband who is murdered by his wife and a friend,
was criticized as treating premeditated murder as a lighthearted
romp.
</P>
<P>
   ''It created passion,'' he said. ''It got the phones ringing, as
opposed to other songs that do OK, but don't really create
excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, 35, said he recorded ''The Little Girl'' to display
his versatility. He plans to continue recording the lighter songs
and love ballads that have made him famous. Each is represented
alongside ''The Little Girl'' on his new album.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, I'm more mature now as a person and as an artist,''
he said. ''But nobody wants to hear sad songs or mature songs all
day long. And nobody wants to hear bubble gum songs all day long.
It's fun to mix and match them up.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   John Michael Montgomery: http://www.johnmichael.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1201 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Met Explores Pivotal Time  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Strolling through the Metropolitan Museum of
Art's first major American exhibit in three decades is an
awe-inspiring journey through the rise of money, power and
creativity in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ''The second quarter of the 19th century was an amazing time in
this city,'' said Catherine Hoover Voorsanger, who organized the
show with John K. Howat. ''The New York we know today was really
created during this period.''
</P>
<P>
   But ''Art and the Empire City: New York, 1825-1861,'' which
opens Sept. 19 and runs through Jan. 7, 2001, is also about much
more than the city itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about the art history of this country as seen through
the lens of New York, which becomes the cultural and commercial
capital of the country during this time period, and the largest
city in the Western Hemisphere,'' Voorsanger said.
</P>
<P>
   She said it is the first American exhibit of its size at the
museum since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The show covers the time between the completion of the Erie
Canal and the start of the Civil War, an era when artists first
found they had to come to New York if they were going to be truly
successful, and when the term ''shopping'' was coined.
</P>
<P>
   Lord &AMP; Taylor opened in 1826, Tiffany's (then known as Tiffany
and Young) opened in 1837 and Central Park opened in 1859 (the Met
itself was formed in 1870). The Associated Press and The New York
Times were both founded during this period.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's as obvious as the nose on our face. New York was the
center of things starting from 1825. But it's a period that's
really been overlooked,'' Voorlanger said. ''The density of
material is staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is ambitious and there's a lot to cover, a testimony to
the wealth and creative energy of the period. The exhibit has been
underway for five years during which a wish list of over 1,000
works was honed down to 310 gems from 84 lenders in the United
States and Europe. Many of the pieces have never before been on
public display.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is accompanied by a catalog of the same name, with
hundreds of color illustrations and a text by over a dozen writers.
</P>
<P>
   Opening with a replica of the Battery Park boardwalk -- complete
with a couple dressed up for a 19th-century stroll, ''Art and the
Empire City'' is divided into a dozen galleries organized
thematically within a chronological framework.
</P>
<P>
   It all starts with art works surrounding the 1825 competition of
the Erie Canal, which established the city as the gateway to the
West. Highlights include a full-length portrait of the Marquis de
Lafayette, much beloved at the time for his role in the
Revolutionary War, by Samuel F.B. Morse (on loan from City Hall),
and a pair of monumental silver vases given to Gov. De Witt Clinton
for his role in envisioning and overseeing the building of the
canal.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes a portrait gallery that recalls the Governor's Room
in City Hall as it looked around 1825. It is a window into the
important personalities of the time: Alexander Hamilton, the
nation's first Secretary of Treasury, painter John Trumbull,
President Andrew Jackson, newspaper editor and publisher William
Cullen Bryant and author Washington Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Next is a gallery on neoclassical architecture, with
architectural drawings and a facade from the Branch Bank of the
United States. And the fourth gallery, with furnishings dating from
1830 to 1845, gives you the feel of one of the period's upscale
homes. Besides stunning ceramics, glassware, silver and
furnishings, it includes pilasters -- rectangular supports or
columns -- and a mahogany door from a grand Grecian house built in
Brooklyn in the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   A gallery examines the interrelationship between the visual arts
and literature -- including masterworks like Thomas Cole's 1825
painting, ''Last of the Mohicans,'' inspired by the James Fennimore
Cooper novel.
</P>
<P>
   Another explores the world of connoisseurship and art
collecting. We see some of the works that city dwellers of the time
would have appreciated at a time when top quality foreign art works
were on public display or were acquired by wealthy New Yorkers for
their private collections.
</P>
<P>
   In the next is a sampling of works and displays seen in 1853 at
a major fair in The New York Crystal Palace, housed in a grand
building of cast-iron and glass in midtown Manhattan which stood
where Bryant Park, alongside the New York Public Library, is now
located.
</P>
<P>
   In counterpoint to the portrait gallery at the beginning of the
show, the gallery ''Photography, the New Medium'' shows early New
York daguerreotypes and paper prints. Suddenly, this new style of
portraiture becomes accessible for anyone from the illustrious P.T.
Barnum and Walt Whitman to a fireman (who poses with hat and horn)
and a grocery boy with his parcel. There are even a few of the
earliest art photos, which look startlingly contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Great Emporium'' makes you think of window shopping on
Madison Avenue or Fifth Avenue and shows what made some of the
city's first shopaholics drool. There are elegant gowns and
gleaming silver, ornate furniture and pearled jewelry from the
early Tiffany's worn by Abraham Lincoln's wife -- with lots in
between.
</P>
<P>
   The following gallery features early maps and plans of what was
by then dubbed the ''Empire City,'' and another shows works by
American artists who were famous when, in the 1840s, New York
became the center of the nation's art scene.
</P>
<P>
   The show culminates with a dramatic display of Frederic Edwin
Church's monumental 1859 painting, ''The Heart of the Andes,''
presented as it was originally -- as a single picture in a darkened
room. It is shown in a reconstruction of the original elaborate,
freestanding wooden frame.
</P>
<P>
   The work was displayed at a fair in New York in 1864, which
inspired the citizens of New York to call for a city museum. That
museum was the Met itself, and the show's grand finale comes full
circle back to modern day New York.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Museum of Art: www.metmuseum.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
