<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutor Talks About Depression  </HEADLINE>
By ESTES THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- James Blackburn was a legal star, the newly
minted prosecutor who convinced a federal jury that Jeffrey
MacDonald killed his pregnant wife and young daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is a man taking small steps on the road to reclaiming his
life, after detours that took him to the other side of the
courtroom and the inside of a state prison, then to a job waiting
tables at a restaurant where he was once a favorite guest.
</P>
<P>
   He relates that journey in a new book, ''Flame-Out: From
Prosecuting Jeffrey MacDonald to Serving Time and Serving Tables.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Life has been measured for me the last seven years in
milestones other people don't think about,'' Blackburn, 55, said in
the sparsely furnished state office where he now works.
</P>
<P>
   He still takes Prozac daily to treat the depression that helped
push him to take $234,000 from his law firm to pay -- among other
things -- a court judgment he had faked, including judges'
signatures, in a client's favor.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty to forgery, fraud, embezzlement and
obstruction of justice in November 1993 and was in prison for 3&AMP;frac12;
months, an eternity for a man accustomed to sending people there.
When he got out, he spent about a year running the office of his
mentor, Sen. Robert Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1995, he went to work at 42nd Street Oyster Bar,
a place where he had regularly lunched with colleagues and
celebrated with friends. He was a host until he realized he could
make better money from a waiter's tips.
</P>
<P>
   He became assistant to the director of the state retirement fund
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Blackburn shed some of his beloved possessions --
his law license, a BMW convertible, a country club membership -- and
gave the law firm his equity in the company and office furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Baptist minister, he was amazed by people he calls
angels -- people he didn't know who wanted to help him. He recalls a
man offering help as he waited for a hamburger the day before he
went to prison. Another man handed Blackburn a $100 bill while he
was waiting tables.
</P>
<P>
   He considers the book as marking the end of that part of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Like so much else, he said, his book came about with help from
friends. Blackburn formed Leslie Books -- his middle name -- and
borrowed $16,000 and supporters' expertise to get it printed. He
has a Web site that is also kept up with friends' help. The old
sedan he drives was a gift.
</P>
<P>
   His re-entry to society also came through the grace of people
who took him places he wouldn't go otherwise, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The book is mailed from his dining room with help from his
family: wife Marsha, son Jeff and daughter Stacy, who told her
father six years ago that a book would help him heal. It's also
being sold in some stores in North Carolina and on Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Blackburn, shy of publicity, wouldn't be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has my everlasting admiration because she exhibited at
least as much courage as he did,'' said lawyer Wade Smith, who
defended MacDonald, an Army doctor, on charges that he had stabbed
to death his pregnant wife, Collette, and daughters Kimberly and
Kristen at their home in Fort Bragg in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also was part of the defense team for his old courtroom
adversary, and later wrote the foreword to Blackburn's book.
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn was famous as a prosecutor who had a friendly manner
that charmed juries. He had been an assistant federal prosecutor
for less than two years when he tried his first murder case in 1979
and won a conviction against MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's problems began when he entered private practice
after serving two years as the U.S. attorney for eastern North
Carolina. When Blackburn began to slide, he was a managing partner
of one of the state's largest law firms.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was unable to accept defeat,'' Smith said. ''He expected
that he would win all his cases dramatically. He couldn't face the
truth about himself that all of us have to face -- no lawyer has
magic tricks. We just do the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn is no longer interested in reapplying for his law
license, and hopes the book will lead to a career as an author of
crime and court mysteries and as a public speaker about depression.
</P>
<P>
   ''People say I used depression as a legal defense,'' he said.
''That's the hardest part to talk about in the book because it's
the most personal. I'm the most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to beat myself up over that. If people like me,
great. If people don't like me, that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn's site: http://www.jamesblackburn.com
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from Jim Blackburn's book, ''Flame-out: From
Prosecuting Jeffrey MacDonald to Serving Time to Serving Tables'':
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''I developed an unnatural and unreasonable expectation of
myself and what I could accomplish for my clients. I never wanted
them to lose or be unhappy with the result of their case. Over
time, I developed tremendous difficulty with telling some clients
the bad news that they had no chance of winning a settlement or
staying out of prison. I believed, sometimes unreasonably, that
there was always hope.'' -- Blackburn on what led to his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no plan, except now I'd tell the truth. I tried not to
stop and think about the consequences of what I was now doing or
saying. I just kept to the plan: tell the truth.'' -- Blackburn's
strategy after being caught stealing from his law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are what we wear, then I had sunk to the bottom.'' --
Blackburn on checking into jail and being issued an orange
jumpsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Within these pages is hope for people who are battling
depression or whose loved ones battle it. Jim Blackburn became Job,
sitting beside the road, covered in ashes and dust. He looked in a
mirror and saw the truth and then, fearlessly, he spoke it. ...
Once he told the whole truth about himself, he was freer than any
of his detractors.'' -- Friend and MacDonald defense lawyer Wade
Smith, in the book's foreword.
</P>
</TEXT>
