<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Art Scene Bustles and Booms  </HEADLINE>
By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- In 1921, French art dealer Rene Gimpel wanted to
arrange an exhibition in London for a painter he knew.
</P>
<P>
   His book, ''Diary of an Art Dealer,'' records that only three
London galleries showed contemporary art, and one of those
restricted itself to English painters. All three galleries were in
the smart West End.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are more than 900 galleries in London for
contemporary art, spread all over the capital, with the largest
concentration in the tough East End.
</P>
<P>
   The East End, once an artistic desert, is home, workplace and
showplace these days for an astonishing 20,000 professional
artists, attracted by low rents and much space in disused
industrial and office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over 150 new galleries have opened in London in the past 18
months, and the launch of Tate Modern has had a euphoric effect,''
says Heather Waddell, who for 20 years has chronicled and
photographed the changing scene with her guidebooks to art in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth edition of her 280-page ''London Art and Artists
Guide'' shows what an industry art supports, with its lists of
galleries, studios, materials shops, publishers, print firms,
workshops, schools and museums.
</P>
<P>
   ''One successful gallery opening like White Cube in Hoxton --
another formerly very poor district -- quickly leads to others, like
those in Hackney and Spitalfields, areas which used to be dead for
art and despised as places to live in,'' she says. ''The art boom
makes them places to visit and can lead to rejuvenation of an
entire borough.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York City has over 1,300 galleries and is important for
selling, but London has the edge in producing new and exciting
works of art and there's an insatiable appetite for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell noted that this year's London Art Fair sold works
totaling more than $18 million in under a week, up from $15 million
last year and $9 million the year before that.
</P>
<P>
   The boom has been helped by corporate sponsorship as big
companies and banks pay for international exhibitions and buy art
to put on their walls, and is likely to go on for some time as
Britain's National Lottery, now in its sixth year, continues to
pour money into the arts.
</P>
<P>
   The new Tate Modern for 20th-century and contemporary art in the
disused Bankside Power Station on the south bank of the Thames is
just one of the many lottery-funded arts projects in London.
</P>
<P>
   Others are the Wallace Collection of antique arts, the expanded
National Portrait Gallery, the revamped central courtyard of the
British Museum, and the huge 18th-century Somerset House.
</P>
<P>
   ''The contemporary art explosion stems from the crossover
between pop and rock music, videos and artists, the power of the
advertising agent and collector Charles Saatchi and the publicity
for new art forms by Nicholas Serota, director of the two Tates in
London and others in St. Ives and Liverpool,'' Waddell says.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of many things done by Damien Hirst, who also owns
restaurants, was to make rock videos for musicians, notably Blur,
and the millions of youngsters who saw them became interested in
what else Hirst and his friends were doing,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Saatchi collects avant-garde artists' work and was behind the
Royal Academy's 'Sensation' exhibition, which then went to the
United States and had all that publicity when the mayor of New York
tried to ban it from Brooklyn. Everything comes together these
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the boom and millions of dollars made by artists such as
Hirst, Waddell noted that it's still hard for most artists to
scratch out a living.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell produced her first London art guide in 1979, offering
new editions every two-and-a-half years and spinoffs covering
similar ground for New York, Paris, Amsterdam, Berlin, Madrid,
Australia, Britain and Glasgow, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   This year, she also published ''The London Art World 1979-99,''
a book of her black-and-white photographs of the art scene, which
she hopes will become a document of the changes -- from clutter to
minimalism, from abstraction to figuration to conceptualism.
</P>
<P>
   But she has a wary word for one aspect of the boom scene.
</P>
<P>
   ''The opportunities for artists to exhibit and reach a wider
public are greater than they've ever been,'' she says. ''But
sometimes the hype of young artists is ridiculous and ignores some
exceptionally talented mid-career and older artists who were in
their 20s in the 1950s to 1970s.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1204 </TRAILER>
