<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 76; Nasdaq Drops 12  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Continued nervousness about third-quarter
earnings pushed stocks lower Wednesday, despite the announcement of
a merger between two of the country's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 76.21 to 11,157.02.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators also declined. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index fell 4.77 to 1,477.22, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 11.68 at 3,837.83.
</P>
<P>
   Although most third-quarter earnings reports won't come out
until next month, concerns that the numbers will be disappointing
have sent stocks in September. The market has fallen into a pattern
of rewarding companies that deliver strong profits and outlooks,
and punishing those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   SCI Systems was off $12.19 at $43.75, a nearly 22 percent
decline, after the electronics manufacturer said its quarterly
results would fall below expectations because of seasonal weakness
in demand for its products.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sherwin Williams dropped $2.63 to $21.25 after the
paint company said quarterly earnings would not meet Wall Street
expectations because of higher raw material costs and tough
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell $3.25 to $61.69 after a Banc of America Securities
analyst cut his rating to ''market perform'' from ''strong buy.''
Last week, a U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffries analyst to ''buy'' from
''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still half a month away from actual earnings season, but
we've already had key reports from companies like DuPont saying it
will be down. The market has not taken that news well,'' said Ricky
Harrington, a senior vice president at Wachovia Securities in
Charlotte, N.C. ''It's somewhat subjective, but I think the runup
of stocks that we saw before Labor Day has set the stage for
downside surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   DuPont shares fell sharply last week after the chemical company
said its earnings would be below expectations because of rising
costs and soft markets.
</P>
<P>
   Before the market opened, Chase Manhattan Bank announced it was
acquiring J.P. Morgan for about $36 billion in stock. J.P. Morgan
traded down $7.50 at $177.94, after weeks of its stock price
inching upward on rumors that it was an acquisition target. Chase
Manhattan fell $2.63 to $49.88.
</P>
<P>
   The merger news, which might be expected to lift stocks, was
instead overshadowed by the earnings uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 487.99 million
shares, compared with 457.83 million in the last session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 1.27 to 531.16.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
