<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trade Bill Being Sorted Out  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate on Wednesday neared a vote on
sanctioning Chinese weapons proliferation, settling a squabble that
was holding up what was expected to be a strong Senate vote to
endorse permanent normal trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the most important trade bill of this Congress was
within sight, but the Senate first had to dispose of the
proliferation issue and at least a dozen other amendments.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the proliferation amendment was set Wednesday
afternoon, ending an impasse that had postponed that vote and
delayed completion of the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment's chief sponsor, Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said
it was important to focus on the issue because the threat of
Chinese arms technology sales is ''not diminishing its growing. ...
The leadership of the Chinese government is basically giving us the
back of their hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The House in May passed the bill that ends the annual review of
U.S.-Chinese trade relations and grants China permanent trade
status in conjunction with that country's impending entry into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   To join the WTO, China has agreed to significantly lower its
tariffs and remove trade barriers, actions that could mean billions
of dollars in increased business for American companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to pass. It's time now we get to the closing,''
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott's effort Tuesday to schedule a vote on Thompson's
amendment was thwarted by fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Banking Committee chairman, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and
Sen. Mike Enzi, R-Wyo, a senior member of that committee, argued
that they should have more input in shaping the proliferations
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who chairs the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
shot back that ''this is the only amendment that deals with a
direct threat to this nation and we are talking about process.''
</P>
<P>
   His proposal, co-sponsored by Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.,
would set up an annual review of the weapons sales of China, Russia
and North Korea and require the president to impose
non-trade-related sanctions on individuals and companies that
violate nonproliferation agreements. The president also could
impose additional sanctions on key supplier nations.
</P>
<P>
   It also requires the Securities and Exchange Commission to
create a procedure to inform American investors when foreign
entities on the president's proliferation list invest in U.S.
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   The president would be able to waive the sanctions requirements
for national security reasons, but Congress could vote to override
that waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson acknowledged that he faced formidable foes in pushing
his measure. ''There's a powerful combination of forces out there --
the White House and the Chamber of Commerce -- working very hard
against this.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Chamber of Commerce President Tom Donohue, before leaving
for a weeklong trade mission to Asia, spent Tuesday morning on
Capitol Hill, buttonholing senators in a last-minute effort to
ensure passage of a clean China trade bill. ''Should this vote get
tangled up to the extent that it might not be passed, that would
have a very serious political implication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the bill, led by business and agriculture groups,
argue that it must clear the Senate without amendments so that it
doesn't have to be sent back to the House for further consideration
in the final days before this Congress adjourns.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday easily defeated three proposed amendments
linking the new trade relationship to such issues as China's ending
its subsidies to state-run enterprises, ending the export of
prison-made goods and improving its human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4444.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Association of Manufacturers:
http://www.nam.org/
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thompson: http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)thompson/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1236 </TRAILER>
