<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Review: Chemical Weapons Checks OK  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some U.S. industry fears over chemical weapons
inspections have so far been unfounded, a congressional
investigator said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The first seven companies to be inspected under the 1997
convention requiring destruction of chemical weapons have not
suffered a feared loss of trade secrets nor from bad publicity,
Jack L. Brock Jr. of the General Accounting Office told a House
panel.
</P>
<P>
	   The GAO was asked to review the experiences of companies under
the chemical weapons convention as a way to anticipate problems
that drug, agricultural, chemical and brewing companies might have
with another international agreement -- one still being negotiated
to cover biological weapons. On that, he said he couldn't make
definite conclusions.
</P>
<P>
	   ''I would like to caution that our ability to draw conclusions
... is somewhat limited,'' Brock said, because requirements for
judging compliance on biological weapons could be different for
those on chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
	   Brock was testifying at the House Government Reform Committee's
subcommittee on National Security, Veterans Affairs and
International Relations. The committee was looking into the
questions of whether it is possible to verify nations have stopped
producing biological weapons and are destroying old stocks -- and
whether in attempting to verify such things U.S. industry and
defense secrets might be compromised.
</P>
<P>
	   Susan Koch, deputy assistant secretary of defense, told the
committee that the Pentagon does not believe that the system being
negotiated -- the protocol for judging compliance on biological
weapons -- will work.
</P>
<P>
	   ''We do not believe that the protocol being negotiated will be
able to provide the kind of effective verification that exists in
other arms control treaties,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Committee chairman Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., criticized
representatives of the pharmaceutical industry for refusing to
attend the hearing -- saying the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America ''has not been shy'' about lobbying the
government for the best treatment possible on the issue.
</P>
<P>
	   The group did not return two phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
