<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Author's Wife Threatens Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER BODEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- The widow of journalist Edgar Snow, who
chronicled the Chinese Communist Party's early years as a guerrilla
army, has threatened to sue over a film about her husband's
friendship with Mao Tse-tung.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Wheeler Snow says the upcoming film, made by a Chinese
state studio, draws without permission on Edgar Snow's landmark
book, ''Red Star Over China,'' and her own account of his final
days.
</P>
<P>
   She accused China of hypocrisy, saying it praised her late
husband as a seeker of truth while curtailing a free Chinese press.
In modern China, it would be impossible to make a ''truthful,
independent film about my husband,'' she wrote in a letter to the
film's Chinese makers.
</P>
<P>
   Snow, who died in Switzerland in 1972, is officially regarded as
a ''friend of China,'' for his sympathetic coverage of the
communist struggle in the 1930s and 1940s. But his widow clashed
with the government this year when police in Beijing blocked her
from visiting the mother of a victim of the 1989 crackdown on
pro-democracy protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We strongly object to Edgar Snow's life story being used for
propaganda purposes,'' Wheeler Snow wrote. The letter said the
producers had no right to make or show the film without her
permission, and could face ''legal or other appropriate action.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow wrote ''Red Star Over China'' after living with Mao's
struggling communist guerrillas in their remote base in the hills
of northwestern China in 1936. It drew international attention to
the movement, which finally came to power in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Director Song Jiangbo denied his movie violated any copyrights,
saying screenwriter Li Chao relied on interviews and historical
works, not Snow's book.
</P>
<P>
   The lives of Mao and Snow are part of the public record, said
Song, who works for the Changchun Film Studio in the northeastern
province of Jilin, one of a trio of Chinese studios financing the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ''She clearly hasn't read the script or seen the movie and isn't
familiar with the content. If she brings the lawsuit, we'll fight
her to the end,'' Song said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler Snow also complained that the Chinese movie crew
illegally entered the grounds of her house in Switzerland to film.
</P>
<P>
   Song responded that the crew had been shooting test footage and
stopped when asked by Snow's son.
</P>
<P>
   Song said he had planned to return to talk to Wheeler Snow, but
the Chinese Embassy in Switzerland objected because of her sympathy
toward the pro-democracy movement. China's army killed hundreds and
possibly thousands of people when it crushed pro-democracy protests
in Beijing on June 4, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said we shouldn't see her to avoid being misunderstood,''
Song said.
</P>
<P>
   Song said the film was not shot on instructions from the
government and said that it delved into the disagreements between
Snow and Mao, as well as their friendship.
</P>
<P>
   The movie stars John A. Gardner, an American businessman in Hong
Kong and first-time actor, as Snow. Song said it would be released
in China next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1332 </TRAILER>
