<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Latin Grammy Awards Tonight  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Seven months after winning a Grammy for
record of the year, Carlos Santana had a chance at the same award
for a different song at the inaugural Latin Grammy Awards on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Santana's duet with the Mexican rock band Mana, ''Corazon
Espinado,'' competed with songs by Marc Anthony, Ricky Martin,
Ruben Blades and Carlos Vives for the honor. Among Santana's eight
Grammys in February was record of the year for ''Smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Producer and songwriter Emilio Estefan led with six Latin Grammy
nominations. His wife, Gloria, was to be host of the CBS telecast
from the Staples Center, along with Jennifer Lopez, Andy Garcia and
Jimmy Smits.
</P>
<P>
   Heartthrob Anthony and Colombian recording star Shakira had five
nominations apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin Grammys were started by an offshoot of the National
Academy of Recording Arts &AMP; Sciences, which produces the Grammys,
to capitalize on a growing interest in Latin music. The telecast
was to be seen in more than 120 countries.
</P>
<P>
   With a broad definition of Latin music -- anything sung in either
Spanish or Portuguese -- the first nominations caused some
controversy. The record company Fonovisa threatened a boycott,
complaining that the Latin Grammys slighted Mexican styles such as
norteno, tejano and ranchera.
</P>
<P>
   There also was some grumbling that television producers were
favoring artists who sing in English and are better known among
Americans. Martin, Christina Aguilera and 'N Sync were scheduled to
perform.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a first step, but it's a big step in the right
direction,'' said Francisco Villanueva, managing director of the
record label, BMG U.S. Latin.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,600 members of the Latin Academy of Recording Arts &AMP;
Sciences were eligible to vote in the 40 award categories.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Latin Grammys: http://www.grammy.com/laras/
</P>
</TEXT>
