<HEADLINE> Italian Opera Fans Protest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy (AP) -- It was the end of La Scala's long-standing
tradition: Angry opera fans showered pamphlets from the balconies
and marched in protest outside to denounce abolishment of the
house's venerable standing-room-only spots.
</P>
<P>
   La Scala on Wednesday stood by its decision to get rid of the
spots but offered one concession to the angry fans -- promising to
make 139 regular seats available at the old standing-room-only
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of opera fans walked in candlelight procession before
Tuesday night's performance of ''La Boheme.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first performance since the 222-year-old opera
house's summer break -- and the first since management announced it
was replacing the 160-200 standing spots with numbered seats.
</P>
<P>
   ''Back-row seats on the balconies are not the best for
visibility,'' La Scala spokesman Paolo Soraci conceded. ''But we
have to install them in line with Italian safety regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   La Scala cited fire-safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   La Scala's standees -- traditionally regarded as among opera's
most ardent fans and most knowledgeable critics -- used to line up
for hours for the last-minute tickets at $5 to $9 a spot.
</P>
<P>
   Top tickets for opening night can run up to $1,500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
