<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radical French Farmer Found Guilty  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE GANLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILLAU, France (AP) -- A militant sheep farmer was sentenced
Wednesday to three months in prison for vandalizing a McDonald's
restaurant in a protest that made him a hero in the eyes of the
French in the battle against rampant globalization.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 supporters of Jose Bove chanted and banged sticks
outside the small courthouse in this town in southern France. But
it was nothing like the raucous atmosphere of his June 30 trial
when he was carried to court in an ox cart amid cheering crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Bove and his lawyers appealed the verdict. The sentence exceeded
that sought by the prosecution during the two-day trial, which drew
15,000 people. The prosecution asked for 10 months with nine months
suspended.
</P>
<P>
   But presiding judge Francois Mallet said the stiffer sentence
aimed ''to make him (Bove) finally listen to reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The sprightly, mustachioed Bove, however, vowed prison would not
stop him from continuing his battle against multinationals and the
World Trade Organization, which he claims pose a threat to small
farmers, good food and a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court thinks this judgment is going to stop the battle,''
Bove said. ''But the fight is going on all over the world ...
against bad food.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight other defendants were given sentences ranging from $265
fines to two-month suspended prison terms. One was acquitted. The
McDonald's, located at the base of a hill where Bove lived in a
centuries-old farmhouse, was dismantled with farm equipment while
under construction on Aug. 12, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bove has already spent three weeks in prison, meaning he will
likely serve two months in jail, his lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not afraid of prison,'' said Bove, dressed in jeans and
sandals. ''I know it and think I'd be welcomed by inmates and
guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bove, nicknamed ''Robin Hood,'' has become a folk hero in France
since the attack, which he said was ultimately against the
''McDomination'' of the world. His $17,000 bail was paid for by
farmers and activists around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bove said his Farmers' Confederation, linked with movements
elsewhere, would continue to act, in particular destroying fields
of genetically altered crops.
</P>
<P>
   Bove, who coined a new French term -- ''mal bouffe'' (bad eats) --
gained international stature defending small farmers against what
they see as the encroachment of multinationals producing
standardized, unhealthy food.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on McDonald's was inspired by U.S. sanctions on
European delicacies, from foie gras to Roquefort cheese -- some made
from milk supplied by Bove's flock. The sanctions were designed to
punish the European Union for refusing to import American
hormone-treated beef.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
