<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holocaust Settlement Plan Detailed  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A court-appointed mediator says Swiss banks
should pay about $800 million of a historic $1.25 billion
settlement with Holocaust victims to those who deposited money to
hide it from the Nazis and never got it back.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $450 million would go to wartime refugees who were
denied entrance to or were expelled from Switzerland, slave
laborers forced to work for companies with Swiss accounts, and
victims whose belongings were plundered by the Nazis and apparently
wound up in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The allocation proposal was included in a voluminous draft plan
for dividing and distributing the settlement to Holocaust victims
and their heirs. It was made public Tuesday in Brooklyn federal
court by special master Judah Gribetz. A ''special master'' is a
person appointed by a court to conduct help research a particular
question.
</P>
<P>
   The plan gives priority to the so-called ''Deposited Assets
Class'' -- Jews and other victims with valid claims that the banks
failed to reimburse them after World War II. Gribetz estimates that
$800 million -- including interest -- will be needed to reimburse
bank account holders and heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Among other claimaints, the proposal estimates that each
surviving refugee would get $2,500 and laborers $1,000 apiece.
Their heirs would be largely excluded. ''There is simply not enough
money available,'' Gribetz cautioned in a letter to the millions of
potential claimants posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is consistent with Congress' decision to compensate
Japanese-Americans confined in detention camps in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' attorney Morris Ratner said the proposal ''does not
satisfy all my concerns, but I think it is plainly fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan still must be approved by U.S. District Judge Edward
Korman. The judge will hold a public hearing on Nov. 20 before
making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Gribetz -- a New York City attorney and former deputy mayor --
said his proposals rely heavily on the findings of a three-year,
independent investigation headed by Paul A. Volcker, the former
Federal Reserve chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The Volcker Committee identified 26,000 Swiss bank accounts
probably opened by Holocaust victims, and an additional 20,000
possibly connected. Gribetz recommended publishing account
information worldwide to find the claimants.
</P>
<P>
   ''The findings of the Volcker Committee must be acted upon,''
Gribetz wrote. ''They are not merely for history books.''
</P>
<P>
   Gribetz called for the Claims Resolution Tribunal -- a
Zurich-based body of judges, lawyers and accountants established by
the Volcker Committee and the Swiss banks -- to process the claims.
So far, about 560,000 people have expressed interest in making
claims; about 80,000 have identified themselves as Swiss bank
depositors.
</P>
<P>
   Korman approved the settlement in July after attorneys from both
sides convinced him that that an overwhelming majority of the
plaintiffs in the class-action lawsuit against the banks supported
it.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed by Holocaust victims who deposited money in
Swiss banks for safekeeping as the Nazis gained power in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the plaintiffs said, they ran into a stone wall
in trying to claim the assets. In some cases, they lacked detailed
account information; some bankers even demanded
impossible-to-obtain death certificates of people killed in Nazi
concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net
</P>
<P>
   Holocaust Victim Assets Litigation (Swiss Banks):
http://www.swissbankclaims.com/index.asp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1521 </TRAILER>
