<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian-Israeli Talks To Resume  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel-Palestinian talks are to resume Thursday
in New York, a Palestinian Cabinet minister said, following an
invitation from Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat met with his negotiations
steering committee Wednesday to discuss the invitation, described
by Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo as a ''surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Palestinian negotiators Saeb Erekat and Mohammed Dahlan
are to arrive in New York on Thursday to resume the talks.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton failed to break the deadlock over control of
holy sites in Jerusalem in separate meetings with Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in New York last week.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's chief negotiator, acting Foreign Minister Shlomo
Ben-Ami, discussed the stalled negotiations in Washington on
Wednesday with National Security Adviser Sandy Berger. Ben-Ami said
American officials would meet separately with the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians were poised to declare independence Wednesday, the
seventh anniversary of the signing of the first Israel-Palestinian
accord, but put it off to give the talks another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Israel suggested a solution to a territorial issue -- a bridge
over Israel to link the West Bank and Gaza in exchange for Israeli
annexation of parts of the West Bank where most Jewish settlers
live.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Ami said Israel demands overall sovereignty on the Temple
Mount, known to Muslims as Haram as-Sharif, the Noble Sanctuary.
Ben-Ami said the two sides must ''find some kind of accommodation
that will respect the needs of everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to counter Palestinian concerns that Israel excavate
under the Muslim shrines to uncover the ruins of the Temples,
Ben-Ami told the Al-Ayam newspaper, ''We will obviously take all
commitments not to dig, all international guarantees necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Aburdeneh, an aide to Arafat, rejected compromise.
''Jerusalem is a Palestinian city, and it should be under full
Palestinian sovereignty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has charged that Arafat's inflexible position on Jerusalem
stymied negotiations. Barak's spokesman, Gadi Baltiansky, said,
''We showed openness and flexibility, but the other side was not
ripe for it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 200 Israeli demonstrators marched to the Old City of
Jerusalem at nightfall, demanding that Israel allow the
Palestinians to declare a capital in their part of the city. The
dovish Peace Now group organized the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat complained that interim accords have not been implemented
and demanded international guarantees to force Israel to comply.
''It is sickening, it is frustrating, and Israel cannot get away
with it,'' he told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leftover interim commitments is handing over part of
the West Bank to Palestinian control. Barak hoped to incorporate
that into a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Barak wants to place blocs of West Bank Jewish settlements under
Israeli sovereignty. In exchange, Ben-Ami said, the Palestinians
could freely use a bridge that would be built between the West Bank
and Gaza, separated by 30 miles of Israeli territory.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Ami said Israel would maintain sovereignty over the elevated
road but would conduct no security checks there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1610 </TRAILER>
