<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dems Benefit More From Media Cash  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The entertainment industry has given $22.3 million to
the
political parties and their candidates since Jan. 1, 1999,
according to figures from the Center for Responsive Politics, a
nonpartisan group that studies money and campaigns. More than $6 of
every $10 goes into Democratic coffers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democratic Party and its candidates received $13.6 million
from the entertainment industry, compared with $8.6 million for the
Republican Party and its candidates. The rest went to third-party
candidates or independents.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore collected $927,965 from the industry
during his primary campaign, while Texas Gov. George W. Bush raised
$725,542.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the last presidential election year, the
entertainment industry contributed $18.4 million to political
campaigns, with $11.3 million going to the Democrats and $7 million
to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The figures include contributions from individuals and company
political action committees, as well as the unregulated donations
to the political parties known as ''soft money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
