<HEADLINE> Austria's Haider: Sanctions a 'Flop'  </HEADLINE>
By ROLAND PRINZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Hailing the lifting of European Union
diplomatic sanctions, Austria's right-wing firebrand Joerg Haider
on Wednesday labeled the measures a ''complete flop.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider, whose far right Freedom Party's inclusion in the
government led to the sanctions, said the measures failed in their
goal to force the party out of the ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Austria's 14 European Union partners lifted the seven-month
sanctions against Austria on Tuesday after a panel said the
measures stoked the nationalistic feeling they were meant to
punish.
</P>
<P>
   ''They ended as a complete flop,'' Haider said in Klagenfurt,
capital of Carinthia province, where he is governor. ''Democracy
cannot be unhinged by undemocratic means.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider also ridiculed a European Union statement stressing the
need to remain vigilant about the Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very pleased if we are being watched, like we will be
watching the others,'' said Haider, whose remarks sympathetic to
some aspects of Nazi rule raised alarm bells in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Haider also said it was time for small EU members to make sure
that ''a few self-appointed powers'' cannot ''run roughshod over
the small ones.''
</P>
<P>
   That touched on the outcry from Denmark and other small EU
members fearful of domination by France, Germany and other major
powers in the union.
</P>
<P>
   In a swipe against French President Jacques Chirac, whose nation
was among the strongest proponents for the sanctions, Haider said
the statement about vigilance was ''something to cheer up an
already sufficiently humiliated'' French chief of state.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, former leader of the Freedom Party, lashed out more
strongly against German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview to be published Thursday by the Austrian
magazine News, Haider said: ''Schroeder's monarchic arrogance is
unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   In excerpts of the interview distributed by the Austria Press
Agency, Haider said Schroeder is among those ''people who are
trampling without feeling on anyone endangering their sphere of
influence.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are people who have no scruples,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions took effect when the Freedom Party joined the
coalition government of Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel in February.
The Freedom Party had waged an anti-foreigner and anti-EU expansion
campaign in last year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Israel criticized the European Union's decision to lift
sanctions. Prime Minister Ehud Barak said they should have
continued so long as a party with ''neo-fascist characteristics''
remains in government.
</P>
<P>
   Former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres said Wednesday he
didn't believe ''Israel will follow (Schuessel's) advice'' and
return its ambassador, which it had withdrawn to protest the
inclusion of the Freedom Party in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations in New York, Austrian Foreign Minister
Benita Ferrero-Waldner said EU procedures on imposing punitive
measures against member states should be amended in wake of the
sanctions affair.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are all countries of rule of law so ... the European Union
has to be a union based on the rule of law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine told reporters at the
United Nations in New York that the sanctions had outlived their
usefulness and were becoming counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to know how to roll with the punches,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
