<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Nixes China Trade Measure  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. relations with China stood on the verge
of a new era as the Senate neared completion of a bill to make
normal trade relations permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The last major barrier to smooth passage of the trade bill was
cleared Wednesday when the Senate defeated an amendment toughening
sanctions on China and other countries that traffic in weapons of
mass destruction. The vote was 65-32 against it.
</P>
<P>
   Even supporters of the sanctions proposal, offered by Sens. Fred
Thompson, R-Tenn., and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., agreed that any
change in the bill could kill it for the year because the House
might not have the votes or the will to take it up again in the
final days of this session. The House passed the bill by 40 votes
last May.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen amendments remain to be dealt with, on issues
ranging from the business conduct of American companies in China to
China's human rights record, but none appeared to pose a major
threat. A final vote could come at the end of this week or early
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today we have cleared the final hurdle and moved one step
closer to enacting one of the most important pieces of legislation
in a generation for U.S.-China relations,'' said Sen. Max Baucus,
D-Mont., a chief sponsor of the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is very important momentum for final passage,'' said Bill
Morley, chief trade lobbyist for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ''We
took this amendment particularly seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber and other business groups in the past year have made
the China trade bill their top legislative priority.
</P>
<P>
   Also the United States must extend permanent normal trade status
to China as part of China's impending membership in the World Trade
Organization. If it does not, U.S. businesses would miss out on the
significantly lower tariffs China has agreed to as part of its
entry into the WTO, giving foreign competitors a major advantage in
entering the expanding Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is critical to American agriculture'' that the bill pass
without amendments that would force it back to the House, some 65
agriculture groups wrote to senators this week. Unilateral
sanctions, the groups said in opposing the Thompson amendment,
''have the effect of giving U.S. markets to our competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's amendment would have strengthened monitoring of
China's weapons proliferation to such countries as Pakistan and
Iran, required non-trade-related sanctions on companies and
individuals that violate proliferation agreements and set up
procedures for the Securities and Exchange Commission to make
public those proliferators investing in U.S. capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese activities have ''resulted in a more dangerous world,''
said Thompson, who originally tried to move his proposal as
separate legislation, where it would have garnered more support.
</P>
<P>
   The House-passed trade bill does contain some provisions dealing
with U.S. concerns with the Beijing government. It gives relief to
American industries and workers hit by a surge in Chinese imports,
creates a commission to monitor human rights in China and addresses
issues relating to the importing of goods made in Chinese forced
labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4444.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Association of Manufacturers:
http://www.nam.org/
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thompson: http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)thompson/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
