D-Mont., a chief sponsor of the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is very important momentum for final passage,'' said Bill
Morley, chief trade lobbyist for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ''We
took this amendment particularly seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber and other business groups in the past year have made
the China trade bill their top legislative priority.
</P>
<P>
   Also the United States must extend permanent normal trade status
to China as part of China's impending membership in the World Trade
Organization. If it does not, U.S. businesses would miss out on the
significantly lower tariffs China has agreed to as part of its
entry into the WTO, giving foreign competitors a major advantage in
entering the expanding Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is critical to American agriculture'' that the bill pass
without amendments that would force it back to the House, some 65
agriculture groups wrote to senators this week. Unilateral
sanctions, the groups said in opposing the Thompson amendment,
''have the effect of giving U.S. markets to our competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's amendment would have strengthened monitoring of
