<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $Adv18  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - What do you get when you mix murder, money and
sex - and soft Italian loafers?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion dynasty that started as a mom-and-pop shoe shop in
1920s Florence ended up with heir Maurizio Gucci executed in 1995 -
by order of his ex-wife, with the family business on the brink of
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   This week in New York, the moccasin-maker was on its feet again,
capping its five-year turnaround with the reopening of its Fifth
Avenue store.
</P>
<P>
   And the lurid tale behind the signature horse-bit label was just
around the corner - quite literally.
</P>
<P>
   On East 53rd Street, a Manhattan publisher was marketing ''The
House of Gucci: A Sensational Story of Murder, Madness, Glamour and
Greed'' - a real-life thriller tracing three generations of Guccis.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an account of passion, fashion and finance, all wrapped
into one,'' says author Sara Forden, a former Milan bureau chief
for Women's Wear Daily and editor in chief of the new Italian
lifestyle magazine L'Una.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, she takes a close look at the company Guccio Gucci
opened in Fascist Italy, with artisans working in a gilded
Florentine palazzo. His son Aldo eventually took the goods
overseas, making the Gucci scarf and bamboo-handle bag symbols of
clout worn by the likes of Jacqueline Kennedy, Grace Kelly and
Ingrid Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   But Aldo's three sons, his brother Rodolfo and nephew Maurizio
didn't appreciate Aldo's arrogance, and their meetings often ended
with ashtrays and poisoned words flying. After the Fifth Avenue
store first opened in 1980, the family squabbles got so bad that
Aldo's son Paolo publicized financial documents showing that his
81-year-old father had evaded taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Then Maurizio ousted his uncle and cousins and, in 1993, sold
his share of the company to a Bahrain-based investment group.
</P>
<P>
   As the wild-spending Maurizio was about to marry his mistress,
his jealous ex-wife, Patrizia Reggiani, paid a stylishly dressed
gunman to kill her 47-year-old ex at his Milan office, according to
court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The spurned socialite and the couple's two daughters attended
the funeral; months later, Patrizia posed for a photographer,
reclining on a sofa at home with a smile that could have been an
omen of what it took police two years to discover.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizio's once glamorous spouse was arrested on a winter dawn
in 1997 - now looking like a haggard middle-aged suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Her six-month trial the following year ''was the Italian
equivalent of the O.J. Simpson case in the United States,'' says
Forden. ''I couldn't have made up a more intriguing story.''
</P>
<P>
   She had a jailhouse correspondence with Patrizia, while Gucci
executives cooperated with the author as she researched the book.
</P>
<P>
   The woman the Italian press dubbed the ''black widow'' was
convicted of hiring her ex-husband's hitman and sentenced to 29
years in prison, later reduced by three years. Gucci store windows
worldwide displayed sterling silver handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the fashion empire itself was facing the law, with
exorbitant expenses and sinking sales.
</P>
<P>
   Incredulously, it would become the comeback kid of the industry,
with the Harvard Business School conducting a case study of its
rise and fall - and rise again.
</P>
<P>
   As the new Gucci-less Gucci Group, the company re-emerged on the
fashion map under the creative leadership of Texas-born designer
Tom Ford. Its Initial Public Offering was successfully floated on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But the goods behind Gucci would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   After all, when asked for the source of the original Gucci
magic, Maurizio's cousin, Roberto Gucci, replied: ''L'azienda era
la famiglia e la famiglia era l'azienda!!'' (The company was the
family and the family was the company!)
</P>
<P>
   And the family is gone, along with its signature style. Witness
the Gucci G-string on an all-but-naked man introduced in the 1997
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's for effect rather than to wear. It's to get talked
about,'' says Eleanor Lambert, a New York-based fashion expert who
has studied international style almost as long as the Gucci firm
has existed.
</P>
<P>
   The prim, classical Gucci look of the last century ''is a dead
issue. It's a brand that they want to sell,'' says Lambert. And,
though she has high praise for designer Ford's talent, ''he should
be on his own. And Gucci should be forgotten because there isn't
any more Gucci. It's nonexistent. It's too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's Web site now offers a sexy 21st century edge,
including some diaphanous ensembles for both men and women. The
moccasins still sport the trademark ''GG'' - Guccio Gucci's linked
initials - but the cool new image has coated the bloodied past.
</P>
<P>
   Only a touch of red is still attached to the Gucci name - a
crimson stripe on the latest black leather loafer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The House of Gucci, A Sensational Story of Murder, Madness,
Glamour and Greed.'' William Morrow, $26.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.gucci.com/index-flash.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 1700 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0144 </DOCNO>
