<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burglary at DNC finance office in Manhattan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Three laptop computers and a handheld electronic
organizer were reported stolen from the Democratic National
Committee's regional finance office in midtown Manhattan, police
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several other burglaries in recent weeks of
offices at 2 Penn Plaza, a skyscraper where the finance office is
located, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The burglary was reported to police shortly before 10 a.m.
Wednesday. The last person in the office left at 3 a.m. Wednesday,
so the theft occurred sometime after that, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not know what was stored on the computers or the
organizer, and DNC officials in New York and Washington said they
had not heard about the break-in.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had one back in 1972,'' joked DNC spokesman Rick Hess,
referring to the burglary that year of the DNC headquarters at the
Watergate complex. The Watergate scandal eventually forced
President Richard Nixon to resign in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the finance office did not return telephone calls
for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
