<DOCNO> APW20000913.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Trade Tax Breaks Bill  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rushing to head off European Union trade
sanctions, the House passed legislation Wednesday to set up about
$4.1 billion in new tax breaks for U.S. companies that would
replace a system invalidated by the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''Enactment of this law is necessary to avoid an immediate
confrontation with the EU, to ensure the United States is in
compliance with the WTO and to avoid possible sanctions,'' Deputy
Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat said. ''This legislation would
ensure that no U.S. companies are disadvantaged.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 315-109 to send the bill to the Senate, which is
expected to follow suit quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Congress intends to pass the bill before an Oct. 1 deadline set
by the WTO, which upheld an EU challenge claiming the U.S. Foreign
Sales Corporation tax law amounted to an illegal export subsidy.
The October deadline was set to allow the United States time to
replace the system without retaliatory tariffs on up to $40 billion
in U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unthinkable that we not pass this,'' said Rep. Bill
Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Created to offset an EU tax rebate for its exporters, the
Foreign Sales Corporation program permits U.S. companies to reduce
income taxes by 15 percent through export subsidiaries set up in
offshore tax havens such as Barbados and the Virgin Islands.
Microsoft, Boeing and General Motors are only a few of the 6,000
companies, with 4.8 million workers, that get the $4.1 billion
annual tax break.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, costing the government roughly the same amount
each year, would set up new tax breaks that apply equally to
exports by U.S. companies and the products they make abroad. The
WTO ruling against the previous rules centered on their nature as
special exceptions in tax law.
</P>
<P>
   EU officials have already argued the new system is also an
illegal subsidy, but it is not clear whether they would bring a new
challenge to the WTO once it is in place. Even under expedited
proceedings, such a challenge would likely take several months to
settle.
</P>
<P>
   ''My impression is that the initial criticism is posturing,''
said Kimberly Pinter, who oversees corporate finance and tax at the
National Association of Manufacturers. ''I'm sure they're still
unhappy. I'm not sure they're willing to start a trade war over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Information on the bill, H.R. 4986, is available at
http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1707 </TRAILER>
