<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State wants polluting plant to pay $5.2 million penalty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PITTSFORD, N.Y. (AP) - New York wants the owners of a former
asphalt factory to pay $5.2 million for spewing noxious fumes into
the air over 14 years in violation of state environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a judge ruled that the Monoco Oil plant in this
Rochester suburb was a public nuisance and ordered it shut down.
Since then, state officials say negotiations to get the company to
clean up an oil spill and other environmental damage have come to
naught.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the state Attorney General's office and the
Department of Environmental Conservation said they had returned to
court to try to force a cleanup and recover civil penalties of $5.2
million against owners Raymond, Norman and Gary Hurwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The trio were ordered to appear in court on Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Monoco Oil had stored liquefied asphalt at the factory since
1983. The state said it had received hundreds of complaints about
noxious odors wafting over the factory since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Pittsford sued the company in 1986 and again in
1992. A physical education teacher at nearby Pittsford Sutherland
High School told a judge that her outdoor classes often had to be
canceled because of the fumes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 1711 </TRAILER>
