<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Weigh Deutch Security Case  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- CIA Director George Tenet appeared before the
Senate intelligence committee Wednesday in the continuing
investigation of security breaches by his predecessor, John Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not totally completed our investigation,'' the
committee chairman, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., told reporters
afterward. He declined to say anything more about the closed-door
session, but said the committee ''should have a report soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We did have a full discussion with Mr. Tenet,'' said Nevada
Sen. Richard H. Bryan, the committee's top Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Both the committee and the Justice Department are investigating
the discovery that Deutch had worked on some of the nation's most
sensitive secrets on unsecured home computers that also had
Internet access and were used by other members of his household.
</P>
<P>
   The security violations were discovered by the CIA when Deutch
left his post in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing was done about it by the agency until 1999, when the
case was referred to the Justice Department for review and when
Tenet, Deutch's former deputy, stripped his former boss of his
security clearances.
</P>
<P>
   Deutch, now a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, has admitted violating security rules but said he did
so unintentionally and did not mean to put the nation's secrets at
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Six senior CIA officials who handled the case after the breach
was discovered were reprimanded in May.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet was not included in the reprimand, but officials said he
received stern words from President Clinton about his own role.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
