<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Club King-Bail,383  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Miami Beach nightclub impresario charged in a
mob murder case once sought the backing of the Colombo organized
crime family to expand his empire to New York City, a prosecutor
charged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor James Walden claimed investigators have evidence that
Chris Paciello, 28, and his ''business partner'' visited the
Brooklyn social club of Colombo captain William ''Wild Bill''
Cutolo in 1997 - the year Paciello and Cuban heiress Ingrid Casares
tried to open a branch of their popular Liquid nightclub in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Mobsters ''were going to provide contractors for the club, they
were going to provide some of the protection for the club, they
were going to provide some of the bouncers for the club, and he was
going to pay them,'' the prosecutor said. The club plan fizzled in
the face of community opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Walden leveled the new allegations in Brooklyn federal court
while arguing against Paciello's request to ease the conditions of
his house arrest on Staten Island. The defendant is set to go to
trial Oct. 17 on charges he conspired with a Bonanno crime family
crew in a fatal armed robbery and a $300,000 bank heist during the
early 1990s; he has not been charged in the Colombo investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, defense attorney Benjamin Brafman called Walden's
allegations ''patently untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   The case against Paciello ''is razor thin, at best,'' Brafman
said. ''That's why we're eager to proceed to trial. We're confident
he'll be acquitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Paciello's arrest last year, authorities have portrayed
him as a mob-connected thug who reinvented himself in South Beach
by opening a string of celebrity hangouts including Liquid, Bar
Room and Joia.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Brafman told Magistrate Joan Azrack that the
conditions of Paciello's bail - which include footing the
$20,000-a-month bill for private guards - were too taxing. He said
his client had been forced to sell Bar Room to pay lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Brafman called the guards ''a very expensive baby-sitting
service that he can no longer afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Azrack ruled that Paciello could use $250,000 posted with the
court as security on a $15 million bond to help cover his expenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
