<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate agrees to pay $1.1 million of false arrest award  </HEADLINE>
syfons
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A man jailed for a 1993 fatal drive-by
shooting has agreed to give the state a portion of a jury award he
won in a lawsuit over an unrelated false arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said Wednesday the
settlement with Eric Ham is the first time Connecticut has
collected under a law that allows the state to recoup the costs of
incarceration from a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Ham is serving a 50-year sentence for the 1993 murder of Marilyn
Vega in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe the settlement fully satisfies the state's interest
and eliminates the burden for taxpayers of incarcerating this
convicted murderer,'' Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   It costs the state about $101 a day to jail Ham, Blumenthal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ham agreed to give up $630,000 of the $1.1 million award he
received in 1996 after he sued two New Haven police officers for
false arrest in a 1991 murder case.
</P>
<P>
   A jury found that the officers should have included information
in an arrest warrant affidavit that could have cast doubt on Ham's
guilt. Ham was jailed for three months in that case, but the
charges were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The state sued Ham after the jury verdict. The state Supreme
Court ruled in June that Connecticut was entitled to more than
$898,000 from Ham's award for estimated costs of his incarceration
from Oct. 1, 1997 through January of 2022, the date he would first
be eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   Ham, 27, agreed to the settlement last month as a way to end the
state lawsuit, create a trust fund for his 3-year-old son and pay
his legal bills, his attorney, William S. Palmieri, of New Haven,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmieri said the state's action was retaliation against Ham for
his successful lawsuit against two police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eric had all the wrong things going for him,'' Palmieri told
The Hartford Courant. ''He was black, he was from an inner city and
he won a constitutional civil rights case against two police
officers for false arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said the state has several other collection cases
pending, including one against convicted murderer Kevin King. A
jury awarded King $2 million after he claimed correction officers
beat him in during an escape attempt; a judge reduced the payment
to $375,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''This action has nothing to do with Eric Ham's race or
background,'' Blumenthal said. ''It relates solely to the
seriousness of his crime, the length of his imprisonment and his
ability to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of New Haven paid out the $1.1 million last week,
sending portions to the state, Ham's two attorneys and the trust
fund for Ham's son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 1732 </TRAILER>
