<HEADLINE> Law expands health insurance coverage to actors, self-employed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Actors and the self-employed will be
eligible for state health insurance coverage under a bill that was
signed into law by Gov. George Pataki Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The measure amends the Health Care Reform Act 2000, expanding
its Healthy NY program to include those who are employed in
non-traditional fields or on a project-by-project basis.
</P>
<P>
   The existing Healthy NY Program, which takes effect in January
2001, established a state-sponsored health insurance coverage for
small businesses with 50 or fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
   The new law allows eligible working uninsured individuals to
purchase the same benefits package available to small business
employees. Pataki said people like actors who lose eligibility for
group health insurance coverage because they are no longer working
the required minimum hours may now qualify for Healthy NY.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether they are a future Tony Award winner or an entrepreneur
seeking to launch a new high-tech firm, thousands of budding young
stars of tomorrow will benefit from this expansion,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was joined by representatives of the Actors' Fund
of America at a bill-signing ceremony in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits will be available initially through health
maintenance organizations and other insurers approved by the state
Insurance Department. The department will also begin classifying
independent contractors and the self-employed as ''individual
proprietors,'' who may potentially qualify for Healthy NY coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   State Insurance Department: http://www.ins.state.ny.us
</P>
</TEXT>
