<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book Tells Clinton Scandal Secrets  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton dispatched his personal
lawyer to break the news to Hillary Rodham Clinton that he had lied
about the Monica Lewinsky affair, rather than break the news
himself, a new book about the scandal says.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney David Kendall went to the first family's quarters in
the White House in 1998 to tell Mrs. Clinton that the president had
lied, according to the account in ''The Breach: Inside the
Impeachment and Trial of William Jefferson Clinton,'' by Washington
Post reporter Peter Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton had backed her husband's January 1998 finger-waving
denial of a sexual relationship with ''that woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   She was visibly shaken and grim-faced in the days following the
president's August 1998 disclosure that he had, in fact, had an
''inappropriate'' relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Baker writes that Clinton was so distracted by the impeachment
trial later that year that aides at White House meetings sometimes
had to answer questions for him. Clinton was impeached by the House
and acquitted in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The book also says that a key adviser approached several
Democratic Party leaders about a strategy to urge him to resign
when impeachment seemed almost certain.
</P>
<P>
   In the late summer of 1998, Baker writes, former White House
deputy chief of staff Harold M. Ickes ''told people that the only
possible way to convince his ex-boss to give up power would be to
put together a coalition of interest groups and key senior members
from Congress to go to him as a delegation and tell him there was
no way to hold the White House in 2000 unless he resigned.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the book, Ickes broached the idea to AFL-CIO
President John Sweeney, a longtime Clinton ally who replied:
''Let's wait and see, Harold.'' The idea faded away.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes, who is now advising Mrs. Clinton in her campaign for
Senate in New York, said he has not read the account.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to read what he says before I'm going to comment on
that,'' Ickes said Wednesday. He refused to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about whether Kendall acted as an emissary to the first
lady, Ickes said: ''I know nothing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall did not immediately return a call to his office
requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Dion, a spokeswoman for Sweeney, confirmed the account
of the Ickes-Sweeney conversation is accurate: ''It speaks for
itself.'' Sweeney was out of the country at a labor conference and
therefore could not comment himself, she said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said he does not know whether
the Kendall and Ickes stories are accurate and has no plans to find
out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I heard everything there was to hear about that
period of our history,'' Lockhart said. ''These are two things I
hadn't heard before, but I don't intend to become a historian.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1736 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
