<DOCNO> APW20000913.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 22-year-old fliers aim to become youngest crew to circle Earth  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - After months of misadventure trying to
line up sponsors, two 22-year-olds took off in style in a
twin-engine plane Wednesday in a bid to become the youngest flight
crew on record to circle the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really excited - the day has finally come,'' Daniel
Dominguez said before joining fellow pilot Chris Wall aboard a
silver, 1957 Aero Commander 560E for a three-month trip they plan
to document with photographs and video on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The first of 36 stops in 32 countries was Bangor, Maine, with a
seven-hour flight from Newfoundland to the Azores islands in the
mid-Atlantic set for Tuesday. Another 22-year-old, photographer
Jesse Weisz, was to have accompanied them but can now afford to
travel ahead on commercial flights because of a late rush of
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ''World Flight 2000'' was originally supposed to take off in
June, but the high cost of fuel, landing fees and day-to-day travel
costs threatened to cripple the project. America Online stepped in
last weekend and more than doubled cash donations to $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''The flight's always been in jeopardy,'' acknowledged Wall, an
engineering senior at Rice University in Houston. ''A lot of people
saw the project as being risky.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez and Wall, who earned their pilot's licenses at age 17,
have downplayed the flight's ''youngest'' aspect. A 7-year-old
girl, Jessica Dubroff, was killed in 1996 while trying to become
the youngest person to fly across the United States, prompting
passage of a law banning record flight attempts by youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Aliengena, another California child also accompanied by his
father, became the youngest pilot to fly around the world at age 11
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation history buffs think it's highly unlikely that the
oldest crew member aboard any of the more than 160 noncommercial
flights around the world since 1924 was as young as 22. Such
flights usually do not mention crew members' ages.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez and Wall, both natives of El Paso, Texas, have logged
tens of thousands of flying hours. They bought the disused plane
with a $15,000 loan in 1998, renamed it ''Dreamcatcher'' and
refitted it with sophisticated avionics.
</P>
<P>
   After takeoff, Dominguez looped the plane back around the
Rochester airport. It zoomed past a crowd of well-wishers, less
than 100 feet above the runway.
</P>
<P>
   The longest leg will be a 14-hour, 2,042-mile hop from Hawaii to
San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez, who graduated in May with an economics degree from
the University of Rochester, said his biggest thrill has been
encouraging others to ''dream big,'' just like he has. ''That you
can inspire someone to do something is just fantastic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through a Web site, worldflight2000.com, youngsters will be able
to follow the trio on excursions to volcanoes, reefs, temples,
marketplaces and historic homes from Turkey to Australia and Nepal
to Hawaii.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 1737 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Leak Forces Evacuations  </HEADLINE>
By MARK STEVENSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Hundreds of people in central Mexico were
evacuated and 120 were hospitalized after an accident at a
pesticide factory released clouds of malathion pesticide,
authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred late Tuesday at a plant owned by the
Mexican chemical firm, Tekchem, in the agricultural hub of
Salamanca, 200 miles northeast of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ''People reported dizziness, vomiting, and skin and eye
irritations,'' said Arturo Gutierrez, the civil defense director in
Salamanca. ''The cloud was quite dense and large.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1,100 people were evacuated, with about 500 taken to
improvised shelters at government buildings in Salamanca. Most of
them were able to return to their homes Wednesday after the
two-mile-wide cloud dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six people remained hospitalized Wednesday, and five of
them were under close observation by doctors for more severe
reactions to the gas.
</P>
<P>
   Malathion is used in the United States to kill mosquitoes and a
host of agricultural pests. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control
has said it doesn't pose a serious risk to most people, but the
pesticide is suspected of sickening 123 people in Florida in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   However, the quantity and density of the gas cloud involved in
Tuesday's accident was apparently far above what people experience
in normal spraying of the pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred when emergency valves opened automatically
after pressure rose in tanks holding malathion at the plant,
Gutierrez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1740 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspects waives extradition, to be returned to New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A casino security guard accused of
killing three men in a roadside ambush fled New Jersey because he
and his family were getting death threats, his lawyer said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Massey II, 21, of Pleasantville, was charged with three
counts of murder in the slayings of three men on U.S. 30.
</P>
<P>
   After a confrontation in a bar with one of them early Friday,
Massey allegedly followed them into Atlantic City and then opened
fire with an AK-47 while they were stopped at a red light.
</P>
<P>
   He was arraigned Wednesday in Atlanta, where he traveled to stay
with an uncle and later surrendered to police. He waived
extradition to New Jersey to face the charges.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Georgia because he was worried for his safety, lawyer
Ann Shafer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Massey, who is not now, nor has he ever been, a fugitive,
was here staying with relatives because there have been numerous
threats on his life, as well as on the lives of his family,''
Shafer said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Massey, through his uncle, contacted authorities after
learning they wanted to talk to him. The uncle did not implicate
Massey in the killings, Shafer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to be concerned about Mr. Massey's safety and the
safety of his family. We have expressed these concerns to the
authorities from Atlantic City; we have been told ... they are
aware of these threats and we trust that they will take every
precaution possible to ensure his safety as well as the safety of
his family,'' Shafer said.
</P>
<P>
   Massey, a former football player and homecoming king at
Pleasantville High School, is a part-time security guard at the
Sands Hotel Casino, where he was worked for just over a year.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers there expressed shock at the news of his arrest.
Alfred Luciani, president of the casino, called it ''an
aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   The casino did a background check on Massey before he was hired
and a similar check would have been performed by state casino
regulators before he was issued a license, Luciani said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was always all right with me, I never knew him to do
anything like this,'' said Jamar Hunter, 19, of Pleasantville, who
played football with him in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say he had an argument with Michael Demps at a bar
in Egg Harbor Township and then followed the car Demps was in down
U.S. 30 before jumping out and spraying it with gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Demps, 20, of Pleasantville, and Richard White, 26, were shot to
death as they sat in the car. The driver of the car, Lamont Wilson,
21, was gunned down as he ran from the scene. A fourth man in the
car wasn't shot.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic County Prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz is refusing to release
that man's identity, nor will he name the passenger in Massey's
truck, who fled when the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   Blitz wouldn't comment when asked if Massey's life had been
threatened. But he said no information about Massey's whereabouts
would be given until he is lodged in the Atlantic County jail,
which will be late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, a service person at Seaview Marriott Resort, was laid to
rest Wednesday after an emotional funeral mass at Mount Zion
Baptist Church that was attended by more than 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   Several mourners interviewed outside said Massey deserved to
die.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Wilson) didn't deserve the raw deal he got,'' said Iziah
Alexander, 18, wiping tears from his eyes. ''Massey, I hope someone
gives him a raw deal like he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Others called for cooler heads.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is that it's a tragedy happening throughout
our country,'' said Teddy Bryant, who runs an anti-violence program
at Pleasantville High School. ''This is another sad story about
young lives being taken senselessly.''
</P>
<P>
   At the scene of the shooting, meanwhile, a roadside memorial of
teddy bears, flowers, photographs and candles has sprung up.
</P>
<P>
   ''We love you, Ty,'' read the handwriting on a laminated collage
of photos and memorabilia dedicated to White, whose nickname was
Ty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 1740 </TRAILER>
