<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collins wants amendment to block court ban on parental notification </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Supreme Court said his parental
notification law was wrong. Now the Assembly speaker wants New
Jersey voters to overturn that decision with a constitutional
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, said Wednesday his
amendment would give the Legislature clear authority to require
minors to notify a parent before an abortion or any medical
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the court ruled a law written by Collins was
unconstitutional ''because a minor's right to control her
reproductive decisions is among the most fundamental of the rights
she possesses.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Statehouse news conference, Collins said the court
overstepped its bounds with that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''Parents have a fundamental right to counsel, care and manage
their children,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   The only remedy is to change the state constitution, Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we have a constitutional right to say what we believe
should happen in New Jersey with something so fundamental,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill co-sponsor Assemblyman John E. Rooney, R-Bergen, said
voters should make this decision, not the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we have to go over the Supreme Court's head, that's what we
will do,'' Rooney said.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment does not mention abortion. It would only give the
Legislature the ability to pass laws on parental notification.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he would formally introduce the measure in the
Assembly on Sept. 21 and have the matter scheduled for a Judiciary
Committee hearing Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   His plan is to have the amendment on the ballot in November
2001. The bill would need 24 votes in the Senate and 48 in the
Assembly, or simple majority votes in two consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   If voters approve, Collins would then introduce a specific law
requiring notifications before abortions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents called that deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   ''What he wants to do is essentially mislead the entire New
Jersey public,'' Assemblyman Neil M. Cohen, D-Union. ''Really it's
a veiled attempt to have a vote on the woman's right to choose
without saying that in the amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendment would also be challenged for violating several
sections of the state constitution, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This could be unique in New Jersey constitutional law because
it's very likely that you could have a constitutional amendment
that violates the constitution,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's National Organization of Women also denounced the
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of our politicians are so committed to the anti-choice
lobbyists that they will alter the constitution, waste taxpayer
dollars and endanger young women's lives to get anti-choice
support,'' the group's President Elizabeth Volz said.
</P>
<P>
   The law voided by the state Supreme Court passed the Senate by
30-8 vote and cleared the Assembly by a 59-18 margin in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican lawmakers joined Collins to support both the
amendment and parental notification for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this case it's unconscionable to deprive a child of a
parent's involvement,'' Assemblyman Guy F. Talarico, R-Bergen,
said.
</P>
<P>
   The court has left unchallenged laws barring minors from
consuming alcohol or using tobacco, Talarico said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But when you talk about abortion, that's the holy grail. You
can't have any interference,'' Talarico said.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion groups attended the news conference Wednesday to
support the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It comes down to who makes the decisions, the parents or the
abortion industry that makes a profit,'' New Jersey Right to Life
spokeswoman Marie Tasy said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, said in a
statement that he will have the proposal reviewed to see if it
matches the intent of the original notification law.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman is also likely to support the amendment, a
spokeswoman said. Whitman does not need to sign the bill if it
passes the Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
