<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: France Removes Land Mines  </HEADLINE>
By EMMANUEL GEORGES-PICOT
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- France has eliminated land mines from its weapons
arsenal and should press other nations to do the same, a report
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   France won high marks from the National Commission for the
Elimination of Anti-personnel Land Mines for destroying its arsenal
of more than 1 million land mines by Dec. 20, 1999, more than three
years ahead of a deadline specified in a 1997 treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty, reached in Ottawa, bans stockpiles of mines and
commits participating nations to destroy stocks within four years
and clear all mines from their territories in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The commission can affirm that France has effectively
destroyed its entire stock of anti-personnel land mines as well as
the materials used to make them,'' said the report submitted
Wednesday to French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty specifically bans anti-personnel land mines, not
anti-tank mines.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty has been signed by 138 governments and ratified by
101. However, major producers such as the United States, Russia and
China have refused to sign.
</P>
<P>
   The United States says that land mines are necessary to deter
communist North Korea from invading South Korea, where United
States troops help to protect the border separating the countries.
</P>
<P>
   In accordance with the 1997 agreement, France preserved 5,000
mines for training purposes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the International Campaign to Ban Land Mines,
governments have destroyed about 17 million mines in recent years,
but at least 250 million remain stockpiled, and tens of millions
are scattered in more than 60 countries. The devices kill or injure
an estimated 20,000 people each year, mostly civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The French commission was created in 1998 to ensure compliance
with the treaty's provisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1807 </TRAILER>
