<DOCNO> APW20000913.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Urge Congress on Diamonds  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A lawmaker seeking to require that diamonds
sold in the United States list their country of origin believes
Americans should have the chance to reject ''blood diamonds'' --
gems whose sales fund wars in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know where our cars are from, and the parts in them. We
know where our clothes and our cheese were made. Why can't we know
where a diamond, which represents a significant investment of
money, was mined?'' Rep. Tony Hall said at a hearing of the House
Ways and Means subcommittee on trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether Congress likes it or not, American consumers will not
be a party to this blood trade,'' said Hall, D-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Americans buy two-thirds of the world's diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   An international diamond group urged lawmakers to hold off
action on Hall's certification bill.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Runci, president of Jewelers of America, who represented
the World Diamond Council at the hearing, said government officials
from more than 30 nations plan to meet in London next month to
coordinate action on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is simply not possible to legislate a national solution to
the conflict diamond problem in the U.S. market alone, without
inflicting significant economic damage on the diamond and jewelry
industries of the U.S., Israel, India, Belgium, Botswana, South
Africa, Namibia and Russia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee chairman, Rep. Phil Crane, said Congress ought
to ''send a clear signal that conflict diamonds are not forever,''
a reference to an advertising slogan. But he cited concerns about
enacting a requirement that would violate World Trade Organization
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   In July, in Antwerp, Belgium, the international diamond industry
adopted strict new measures to stop rebel groups who trade gems for
guns to fight some of Africa's most vicious civil wars.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to increasing pressure from governments and human
rights groups, the World Diamond Congress approved a package of
measures to track diamonds from the mine to the jewelry store. The
industry promised severe penalties for dealers who break the rules
and buy or sell ''blood diamonds.''
</P>
<P>
   The diamond trade, worth some $6 billion a year, has been
tarnished by revelations that rebel groups in Sierra Leone and
Angola have bought their weapons through diamond sales and gone on
to commit atrocities in their fight against elected governments.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The bill, H.R. 5147, can be found http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tony Hall's site: http://www.house.gov/tonyhall
</P>
