<HEADLINE> mdstf By MATTHEW DALY </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW DALY
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Supporters of Pat Buchanan filed a
lawsuit in Hartford Superior Court Wednesday seeking to place the
conservative commentator's name on the Reform Party ballot line in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's lawsuit names as defendants Secretary of the State
Susan Bysiewicz and Donna Donovan, state chairwoman of the Reform
party, who believes Buchanan rival John Hagelin should be listed as
the Reform Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit came after officials in Bysiewicz's office announced
Wednesday that Buchanan had won a spot on the state ballot as the
choice of the newly minted Freedom Party of Connecticut - not the
Reform Party. Bysiewicz's office said that Hagelin, an Iowa
physicist, probably will not be listed on the ballot in Connecticut
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bysiewicz made her determination after Hagelin and Buchanan
backers each submitted paperwork declaring their man to be the real
Reform nominee. Bysiewicz said her office could not sort out the
party's internal differences, and said that unless one of the
candidates withdrew or won a court challenge, neither would be
listed.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin's supporters also failed to gather enough signatures to
list him on the ballot under the Natural Law Party, the party
banner under which he ran for president in 1996, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's lawsuit comes a day after the Federal Election
Commission awarded him $12.6 million in federal campaign funds
belonging to the Reform Party, and hours after a California judge
ruled that Buchanan, not Hagelin is the Reform nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Cherilyn Gulbrandsen, state chairwoman of the Buchanan campaign,
said the FEC ruling, combined with Wednesday's decision by a judge
in Long Beach, Calif., virtually ensures that Buchanan will be the
Reform Party candidate for president in Connecticut and across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have every reason to believe that (Buchanan) will be on the
ballot as the Reform party candidate at this point,'' Gulbrandsen
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 35-page complaint, Gulbrandsen charges that Buchanan would
suffer ''irreparable loss'' if he is not listed as the Reform
nominee, and says Bysiewicz was wrong to declare the party
''over-nominated.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bysiewicz declined to comment Wednesday on
Gulbrandsen's suit.
</P>
<P>
   The decision means that as of Wednesday, six presidential
candidates had qualified for the Connecticut ballot: Buchanan,
Democrat Al Gore, Republican George W. Bush, Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader, Libertarian Harry Browne and Howard Phillips of the
Concerned Citizens Party.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, the Hagelin backer named in Gulbrandsen's suit, called
it ''typical of the slash and burn tactics (Buchanan supporters)
have been using state by state. Rules and facts don't seem to
matter to these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin's supporters announced Wednesday they have filed a
complaint with the state Elections Enforcement Commission alleging
that Buchanan supporters used fraud in gathering the Freedom party
signatures.
</P>
<P>
   In that complaint, Donovan charges that Gulbrandsen failed to
witness some signatures submitted to the state and submitted others
that were not genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Gulbrandsen angrily denied the fraud claim and said Donovan was
merely retaliating for a vote last month by Buchanan supporters to
remove her as state chair. Donovan does not recognize the Aug. 31
vote and says she remains the Reform leader in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey B. Garfield, executive director of the state elections
enforcement panel, said commission staff is reviewing Donovan's
complaint and will make a recommendation as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on Gulbrandsen's suit is scheduled Friday at 10 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
