<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family files civil lawsuit in Brooklyn to recover $300 million  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The family of Patrick Dorismond sued the city
and police officers for $300 million on Wednesday, aiming
particular criticism at Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for attacking the
man's character after his death.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, blamed
the city, Giuliani and former Police Commissioner Howard Safir, and
the officers for violating Dorismond's civil rights during a drug
buy-and-bust in Manhattan on March 16. The suit described their
combined actions as illegal, malicious, callous and negligent.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, a 26-year-old security guard, became the fourth
unarmed black man shot to death by police in little more than a
year when he was killed by an undercover police detective at the
corner of West 37th Street and 8th Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred during a struggle outside a Manhattan bar
after the officer asked where he could buy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Johnnie Cochran, who filed the lawsuit on behalf of his
family, said at a news conference that the Dorismond shooting was
''the ultimate case, we feel, of racial profiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran, who has defended other high-profile clients like O.J.
Simpson and Sean ''Puffy'' Combs, said Dorismond had told the
detective he did not have any drugs, and yet was shot.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the police department for searching Dorismond's
Brooklyn apartment after the shooting and Giuliani for releasing
sealed juvenile records to ''dirty up his character and
reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor at one point suggested that Dorismond had caused his
own death and refused to offer the family condolences.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to take him to task for demonizing a person who
was an altar boy,'' Cochran said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has since acknowledged that he made a ''mistake'' by
not expressing appropriate sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Goodman, a lawyer for the city, said: ''We have no
comment. We haven't even see the lawsuit.'' The police department
also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Rose Dorismond, the victim's mother, said she was pleased
that the civil lawsuit had been filed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess it's time for the justice to start,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
