<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman signs bill to expand DNA testing for criminals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - At first, only certain sex offenders were
required to give DNA samples to the state. Now samples from
murderers and other violent criminals will be collected by the
State Police.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman signed a bill Wednesday to expand the DNA
samples first allowed by Megan's Law in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the DNA files will help police crack future
crimes. They claim the samples are like genetic fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now the broadening of DNA collection will be yet another tool
in helping law enforcement win new battles in the fight against
crime,'' Whitman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Samples will now be collected from people convicted of murder,
manslaughter, second-degree assault, kidnapping and crimes
involving children where a victim is lured or when sexual conduct
impairs the morals of a child.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, only those convicted of certain sex crimes were
subjected to the DNA collection.
</P>
<P>
   The State Police now has over 5,000 DNA results on file.
</P>
<P>
   ''Testing sex offenders' DNA has proven enormously successful,''
bill sponsor Sen. Nicholas J. Sacco, D-Hudson, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will provide a great opportunity to help protect children
and adults alike from hardcore, dangerous convicts,'' said Sacco, a
sponsor of the original DNA collection law.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law is named for Megan Kanka, a 7-year-old Mercer County
girl raped and murdered by a neighbor. Residents claimed they did
not know he had two earlier sex assault convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows prosecutors to notify communities to the presence
of certain sex offenders deemed dangerous after court hearings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 1849 </TRAILER>
