<DOCNO> APW20000913.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel Approves Measure  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate committee approved a $104.7 billion
measure Wednesday financing veterans, housing, environment and
space programs that would ease some House-approved cuts in
President Clinton's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure, approved 27-1 by the Senate Appropriations
Committee, would still provide roughly $2 billion less than Clinton
wants for some public housing, environmental and science programs.
That gap could lay the groundwork for yet another chapter in this
year's budget battle between the White House and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the same meeting, the panel voted 27-1 to approve a separate
measure providing $441 million for the District of Columbia's
budget, just $4 million less than Clinton sought. The bill lacks
several controversial provisions included in the House's version of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The two measures are now among 11 spending bills financing
domestic programs and foreign aid for fiscal 2001, which starts
Oct. 1, that Clinton and Congress must approve before lawmakers
return home for the fall campaigns. So far, only two spending bills
for the coming year -- both covering military programs -- have been
signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders are hoping to negotiate compromises on the
remaining bills so that Congress can adjourn for the year in less
than five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's veterans-housing bill would boost spending
substantially over this year's levels for overall veterans,
housing, NASA, and National Science Foundation programs. And it
would provide $434 million for the AmeriCorps national service
program, a Clinton favorite that the House voted to kill.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate measure still provides less than Clinton wants
for housing vouchers for the poor, instead creating a $1 billion
grant program for states to use build new low-income units.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not only do vouchers not work well, but vouchers do not
produce a single new unit of affordable housing,'' said Sen. Kit
Bond, R-Mo., chairman of the Appropriations Committee's
subcommittee that produced the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would spend less than the president proposed
for the environment and the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ricci, spokeswoman for the White House budget office, said
the bill has ''inadequate'' funds for vouchers and other low-income
housing aid, and for the science foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia measure contains money the
administration wants for tuition aid for some of the city's
students and for a new Metrorail station. And it lacks
controversial language the House version has limiting distribution
of hypodermic needles to illegal drug users and contraceptive
coverage for city workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1855 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
