<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Cockfighting Bill Debated  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Collin Peterson isn't used to being
attacked by fellow sportsmen, and he wanted to make it clear
Wednesday that his anti-cockfighting bill doesn't mean he's soft on
animals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got more dead animals on my wall than anybody in this
Congress except for Don Young,'' he said, referring to the Alaska
congressman who has a bear hanging in his lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, a pro-hunting Democratic congressman from northern
Minnesota, is the sponsor of legislation that would ban the
interstate transport of birds for cockfighting. At a hearing of the
House Agriculture Committee Wednesday, he faced arguments from
cockfighters that his bill was just the beginning of an effort to
outlaw other forms of animal exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remind my colleagues in the sportsmen's caucus that this is
a pretty slippery slope,'' said Rep. Chris John, D-La., in a barb
directed at Peterson, co-chairman of the Congressional Sportsmen's
Caucus. ''Cockfighting today, what about bow-hunting tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law currently prohibits shipping animals for fighting
across state lines, except for cockfighting birds bound for the
three states where the sport is still legal -- New Mexico, Oklahoma
and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the legislation say that exemption needs to be ended
because it gives illegal cockfighters an easy out when confronted
by police -- they often say they are just raising the birds for
shipment elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a simple and straightforward bill which would see
birds treated and protected the same as dogs have been for more
than 25 years under federal law,'' said Lt. Sherry Schlueter, an
investigator with the Broward County Sheriff's Office in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition at the hearing came mainly from committee members and
cockfighters from the South, where many of the birds are raised for
cockfighting. Roughly 200 cockfighters packed the hearing room and
an overflow room.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Riley, R-Ala., said that when he was a farmer, he'd
kill 30,000 to 40,000 chickens a week -- they'd be hung upside down
and have their throats slit after a six- or seven-week life.
Cockfighting birds, by contrast, are raised for two years in a
''pampered'' environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I was the chicken,'' he said, ''and I had the option of
this two years of pampering and then one option to fight one
day...'' He didn't finish the thought.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Pacelle, a lobbyist and vice president of the Humane
Society, gave a different description.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cockfighting is a bloody and indefensible practice,'' he said.
Cockfighters pump the birds with stimulants to heighten their
behavior, inject them with blood-clotting agents so they can fight
longer, affix them with blades, ''and place them in a pit to hack
one another to injury or death,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said that he has the votes to win passage in committee,
but a committee spokesman said there may not be time left this year
to schedule a vote this year. The Senate Agriculture Committee has
already passed the legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1907 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Supports Hate Crime Bill  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Armed with more data showing hate crimes often
go unreported, President Clinton on Wednesday appealed to Congress
to pass hate crimes legislation. ''Only Congress can do what really
should be done here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only minutes later, the House agreed in a nonbinding vote to
make the hate crime legislation part of a defense appropriations
bill. ''Today, with this bill, we as a society say that we will do
everything we can to protect people from these heinous acts, that
we will not rest until Americans are free from all violence,'' said
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote was 232-192.
</P>
<P>
   ''This historic legislation will help fight hate crimes by
strengthening the law and providing state and local prosecutors the
tools they need to enforce it,'' Clinton said in a statement
released after the vote. ''I urge House and Senate conferees to act
swiftly on this legislation so I can sign it into law.''
</P>
<P>
   However, congressional sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott told Clinton at
the White House on Tuesday the hate crimes provision would not be
made part of the defense bill.
</P>
<P>
   According to one source, Lott told Clinton, ''we'll talk about
it somewhere else, Mr. President,'' possibly as part of another
bill.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Wednesday's vote was a
strong statement of support for tougher hate crimes laws,
''regardless of whatever comments were made yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Congress has an obligation to move on it this year,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton convened an event at the White House to release a new
report that shows information on hate crimes sometimes is not
forwarded to the FBI. Victims of hate crimes tend not to report
them and sometimes police lack sufficient training to handle such
cases, according to the study, written by Northeastern University's
Center for Criminal Justice Policy Research and by the Justice
Research and Statistics Association of Washington, D.C. The Justice
Department's Bureau of Justice Statistics paid for the report.
</P>
<P>
   He said a hate crime is ''an even more dangerous kind of
infection'' than ordinary acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think any of us believe we can ever root it out just
by punishing people,'' Clinton said. ''The most important thing is
that we do have the tools we need to take a strong stand before
these things spread even wider.''
</P>
<P>
   The president directed Attorney General Janet Reno to work with
state and local authorities over the next three months on a plan to
improve hate crimes reporting.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined by Sherialyn Byrdsong, the widow of Ricky
Byrdsong, a former Northwestern University basketball coach killed
in a 1999 hate-motivated shooting rampage, and Laramie, Wyo.,
police investigator David O'Malley, who handled the 1998 slaying of
gay college student Matthew Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acted as the House debated its nonbinding vote to add
the legislation to a defense bill. The Senate voted 57-42 in favor
of the hate provisions in June, and Clinton urged House lawmakers
to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans argued state courts could handle hate crimes
much better than the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''All murders are hate crimes and I think what we're trying to
do is legislate by headline,'' said Rep. Kenny Hulshof, R-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., said lawmakers know they can't
legislate hateful thoughts ''but we do understand that when hateful
thoughts turn into hateful deeds, Congress must act.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Byrdsong said the legislation must be passed to tell bigots
that their hatred will not become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tragedy my family and I experienced is becoming the
American way,'' she said. ''If we allow this evil to spread, I
believe it will rock the foundation of this society.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would add crimes motivated by sexual orientation,
gender or disability to the list of offenses already covered under
a 1968 federal law, and allow federal prosecutors to pursue a hate
crime case if local authorities refuse to press charges.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also provides assistance to local law
enforcement agencies in investigating hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The report was based on a survey of law enforcement agencies and
found 7,755 hate crimes were reported last year. But 83 percent of
the more than 10,000 agencies in the FBI's hate crime data
collection program said none had taken place in their jurisdictions
in the previous year, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the agencies that reported no hate crimes, 31 percent
indicated they still investigated at least one. Clinton noted that
as many as 6,000 law enforcement agencies may have failed to report
a hate crime, underscoring a disconnect between what is reported to
the FBI and what police investigators believe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
