<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police find 15 cars at bottom of lake  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MANCHESTER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Prosecutors are investigating
the discovery of at least 15 cars submerged at the bottom of a
90-foot privately owned lake.
</P>
<P>
   State Police divers pulled six cars, including three sports
utility vehicles and a red Porsche, out of the lake Wednesday. At
least nine more cars are believed to be at the lake's bottom, said
Greg Sakowicz, executive assistant Ocean County prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Sakowicz said the cars were fairly recent models, and said they
had been in the water for at least several months. The cars could
either have been dumped in the lake as part of an insurance fraud
scheme or stolen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were working with Manchester police on an unrelated
investigation when police informed them they had sent scuba divers
to find several cars at the bottom of the lake, Sakowicz said. He
declined to describe the unrelated investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Police divers pulled out the Porsche, a Land Rover, an Explorer,
a Blazer, a Ford Van and a Dodge Dynasty sedan Wednesday, Sakowicz
said. Authorities are tracking the cars' histories through their
vehicle identification numbers, he said. Some had New Jersey
license plates and some had Pennsylvania license plates.
</P>
<P>
   Sakowicz didn't know when authorities would return to retrieve
the other cars.
</P>
<P>
   The lake is located on an 8,000-acre tract of land that was the
former site of a mining company. He said the land was owned by
Hovnanian Enterprises Inc., one of the state's largest developers.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the company, Ed Rand, said Wednesday that he
could not reach key company officials for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
