<HEADLINE> State approves appointment of new Camden business administrator  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - State officials Wednesday approved the
appointment of a new Camden business administrator, rendering
meaningless the mayor's own appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Norton N. Bonaparte Jr. will begin work Oct. 2, replacing
retiring business administrator Preston Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   State officials made and approved the appointment because the
state Division of Local Government Services since May has been
overseeing finances in the city, the poorest in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Camden Mayor Milton Milan on Tuesday named acting business
administrator Heriberto Colon to the position, saying he, not the
state, has the power to hire and fire employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Ulrich Steinberg, director of Local Government Services,
said the mayor is mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not sure he understands the appointment process or how
things have changed with state supervision,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Milan's action this week was reminiscent of July, when he
appointed, then swore in City Attorney John A. Misci Jr. as a
municipal judge. A state Superior Court judge ruled that the
appointment was invalid.
</P>
<P>
   Bonaparte, 47, will earn $98,500 annually. He has been the
Willingboro manager since 1995. He also serves as a senior adjunct
instructor at the School of Management and Business at
National-Louis University in McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Bonaparte previously served as city manager in Glenarden, Md.,
and as a municipal official in Grand Rapids, Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
