<HEADLINE> DEP to ask town to shut off well suspected of affecting Pinelands water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The Department of Environmental Protection
will ask Berlin Borough to shut off a municipal well because it
might be depleting water in the environmentally sensitive Pine
Barrens.
</P>
<P>
   The well, which serves 10,000 residents, will be out of service
for at least two weeks while Berlin officials conduct tests
required by the Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   The borough will monitor water flow at Kettle Run, a stream that
has lost about six inches of water since the well was turned on in
early June. Kettle Run is a habitat for the swamp pink, an
endangered wildflower that has been disappearing from the stream.
</P>
<P>
   The stream, in the Marlton Lakes section of Evesham Township,
ran dry in July. At the same time, residents noticed that many of
the swamp pink had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin officials also must interview nearby residents, who say
the Berlin well has caused their private wells to run dry.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher J. Noll, Berlin Borough's engineer, told The
Philadelphia Inquirer for Wednesday's editions that the borough
would comply with the order, but that it might take a month to get
the funding and the necessary equipment in place. He said the well
would remain operational during that time.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Environmental Protection expects to receive
test results by Nov. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
