<HEADLINE> Salem County slaughterhouse owner accused of threatening investigator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUINTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - The owner of a Salem County
slaughterhouse who has been indicted on charges of improperly
disposing of blood and animal waste threatened an environmental
investigator, the state attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a complaint filed in state Superior Court in Salem
County, Anthony Bonaccurso, owner of Salem Packing Co., threatened
Department of Environmental Protection specialist David Fields on
July 28 when Fields tried to issue him a notice of violation.
</P>
<P>
   Fields was investigating complaints of illegal dumping of bloody
runoff and entrails from the plant, which slaughters pigs, cattle
and lambs. Bonaccurso threatened Fields when he tried to issue the
violation notice, according to the complaint filed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bonaccurso's lawyer, Robert Agre, declined comment Wednesday,
saying he had not seen the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of the disorderly person's offense, Bonaccurso, 70,
of Haddonfield, could face up to $1,000 in fines and six months in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   A state grand jury in July indicted Bonaccurso and the packing
company on charges of improperly disposing of blood and animal
waste, polluting nearby streams. A second indictment in August
included a second, identical count stemming from another
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of the charges in the indictment, Bonaccurso faces
up to five years in prison and a fine of up to $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictments, Bonaccurso or his employees dumped
blood and other animal waste products on the packing house property
between July 6, 1999, and Feb. 23, 2000. The waste flowed into
nearby Keasby Creek and was carried into the Salem River.
</P>
<P>
   The state Division of Criminal Justice launched an investigation
of the company's waste disposal practices after receiving
information from the Salem County Health Department. The state
Department of Environmental Protection assisted in the
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
