<DOCNO> APW20000913.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: School district doctor practiced after surrendering license </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PASSAIC, N.J. (AP) - School officials believe the district's
doctor continued tending to children after surrendering his license
13 months ago, a newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Dr. Edward S. Feldner could face renewed criminal
and civil charges, as well as new charges of practicing without a
license, authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Passaic school district, which has 11,000 students, learned
through an anonymous tip that Feldner gave up his license after
admitting he wrote prescriptions for others that were for his own
use, the Herald News of West Paterson said.
</P>
<P>
   As the district's only doctor, Feldner gave physical exams to
athletes and band members, Superintendent of Schools Robert Holster
told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The district hired Feldner in 1996 and paid him about $50,000 a
year, Holster said. Feldner also practiced in Little Falls, where
he lived.
</P>
<P>
   Holster did not return messages seeking comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Feldner, 44, could not be reached for comment Wednesday. A home
listing was not found and the service answering his office number
said he could be reached only by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Feldner surrendered his license in August 1999 after admitting
that he had written prescriptions in the names of his mother, wife
and a fictitious person for four or five years, but kept the drugs
for his own use, according to a decree he signed with the state
Board of Medical Examiners.
</P>
<P>
   Feldner was required to stop practicing, but did not have to
notify patients or others of the surrender, according to supporting
documents. He was required to remove his name from listings and
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ''As part of the agreement, he did have to stop practicing
medicine, and he did have to take steps to prevent others from
thinking he is a licensed practitioner,'' board spokeswoman Genene
Morris said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did not give us any notice that he was working for the
school district,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which has civil authority, will review the matter for
possible sanctions, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who want to ensure their doctor is licensed can check
with the board.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors have also been notified that Feldner may have
violated his pretrial intervention program, said Marilyn Zdobinski,
Passaic County deputy first assistant prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Feldner pleaded guilty in May to obtaining drugs by fraud and
possessing drugs. He could have faced up to five years in prison,
but was accepted into the pretrial program. Charges would be
dropped and he would face no prison time if he completes the
program.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Board of Medical Examiners, part of the state
Division of Consumer Affairs:
http://www.state.nj.us/lps/ca/home.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
