<DOCNO> APW20000913.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Detainee Denounces Israel  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A spiritual leader of Lebanese guerrillas who
was abducted by Israeli commandos 11 years Wednesday spoke out
against his captors Wednesday and claimed credit for helping to
drive Israel out of southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid, who has been in prisons since 1989,
showed that he has learned the language of his captors when he
spoke to reporters in Hebrew before a hearing in Israel's Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no justice. In this whole country there is no
justice,'' Obeid said as he and fellow detainee Mustafa Dirani, sat
waiting to appeal their detention. The panel of five judges made no
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Obeid, wearing a white knit prayer cap and a dark blue prison
uniform, spoke in simple but direct Hebrew about Israel's May 24
withdrawal from southern Lebanon after 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We kicked them (Israel) out by force,'' said Obedi, who was a
local spiritual leader of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah when he was
kidnapped by Israeli commandos in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Dirani, a military commander for the Amal militia when he was
abducted in 1994, also had bitter words against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there was no (Israeli) oppression I'd be in Lebanon,''
Dirani said in Arabic. ''They occupy your land, arrest you in your
own house, destroy your land, and kill your children.''
</P>
<P>
   Obeid was interviewed on Israel television shortly after he was
abducted. From then until a May 29 open court session, neither he
nor Dirani was seen in public.
</P>
<P>
   The two Lebanese have been held in Israel as bargaining chips in
any negotiations on the release of missing airman Ron Arad, who was
shot down over Lebanon in 1986 and captured alive.
</P>
<P>
   They remain in custody despite a Supreme Court ruling in April
that led to the freeing of 11 other Lebanese detainees, also held
as bargaining chips. The ruling said Israel cannot hold foreigners
unless they are a threat to state security.
</P>
<P>
   The Tel Aviv District Court has ruled that the two still
endanger national security and may be kept temporarily in
administrative detention. They have never been charged or put on
trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
