<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Challenger declares victory as recount looms in Democratic House primary </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLPORT, N.Y. (AP) - Regina ''Reggie'' Seltzer says she ran for
Congress because ''we should have people in there who represent the
ordinary person.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary hardly describes Seltzer, who pulled off a political
shocker by running a dead heat in a Democratic primary against Rep.
Michael Forbes, a three-term congressman who last year switched
from Republican to Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer, who immigrated from Poland at age 8, is a
librarian-turned-lawyer (often working for free), plays tennis
twice a week, has written a book on children's rights and is a
sculptor in her spare time. Her only previous elected office was
one term on the Brookhaven Town Board in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The primary was far from decided Wednesday, but Seltzer - a
71-year-old, gray-haired, suntanned grandmother - bubbled with
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think Washington is going to change me. At least, I
hope not. And if it does, there are enough people around who are
going to let me know that. Then they'll vote me out - and they
should,'' she said in an interview on her screened-in porch
overlooking Long Island's Great South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Although a re-count was planned, unofficial returns showed
Seltzer clinging to a 39-vote lead out of more than 11,000 votes
cast.
</P>
<P>
   It could be at least a week before a winner is officially
announced. Election officials said 600 absentee ballots were sent
out but it was unclear how many will be returned by the Sept. 19
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in Washington, Forbes, a
Republican-turned-Democrat, was not optimistic. ''Clearly, I am a
realistic fellow. When you end an election night with a deficit
vote, the likelihood of making up that deficit is pretty much a
longshot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really can't believe that I won,'' Seltzer said. ''I think
that this is a terrific example for high school kids, for college
kids - it says anybody, anybody in this country, can still have a
shot at running for government.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't have to be a multimillionaire, you don't have to
sell your soul to the private interests. You can just be a plain,
ordinary person - even a little old lady like me.''
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong Democrat, Seltzer moved to Long Island in 1960 with
her late husband, Stanley. With her two children in school, Seltzer
went back to college and got a degree in library science.
</P>
<P>
   She worked as a librarian for 13 years in the Patchogue-Medford
School District. In 1976, she ran and won a seat on the Brookhaven
Town Council. By 1980, however, the political winds shifted, and
she was out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's when a friend came to me and said, 'Now's the time to
go to law school,''' Seltzer said. At age 50, she enrolled at
Hofstra Law School. Today, she mostly works free for groups like
the Long Island Pine Barrens Society.
</P>
<P>
   ''She is a friend to all who need her,'' said Seltzer's longtime
tennis partner, Esther Glass. ''She has done work for no money for
many causes that she believes in.''
</P>
<P>
   About 350 people helped Seltzer in her upset bid, which was
funded on a $40,000 budget. Forbes had amassed a war chest of $1.4
million, some of that coming from a fund-raiser held last April
that featured President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't like to ask people for money,'' Seltzer said,
confessing that she was stunned by the money that came rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer said her dislike of Forbes was fueled less by his change
in parties than his politics. Forbes had backed Republican Newt
Gingrich's ''Contract With America'' and is opposed to legalized
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Forbes sticks his finger out and whatever way the wind
is blowing to suit him, that's what he's goinwinner and
has no regrets about switching parties.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Seltzer took a moment to look back before forging
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my household, my father and mother were strong believers
that people should be involved in government, should be concerned,
and that it was your responsibility as a citizen to do something to
help,'' she said. ''In my house, this country was considered to be
paradise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
