<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Men's Volleyball Has Competition  </HEADLINE>
By DENIS D. GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Still stinging from its last-place
finish in 1996, the U.S. men's volleyball team comes up against a
tough opponent in its first game in Sydney. And it gets worse after
that.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are grouped in Pool B with three teams -- Italy,
Russia and Yugoslavia -- that coach Doug Beal believes are the top
medal prospects. Their first match Sunday is against Argentina, and
Beal says that's no pushover.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're a little stronger than in 1996, maybe have a
little more depth and I think there are more experienced players on
the team,'' Mike Lambert, who also was a member of the team four
years ago, said Thursday (Wednesday night EDT).
</P>
<P>
   At Atlanta, the glory days of American men's volleyball of the
1980s were a distant memory. The team tied for ninth and last with
Poland, Tunisia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll keep the game simple and communicate on the court.
That's a key area for us,'' Lambert, an outside hitter from
Kaneohe, Hawaii, said. The team will focus on serving, passing and
the three-man block.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking should be a key element in the opener against the
aggressive Argentines, described by Beal as ''one of the dangerous
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They have some of the world's top players. It's a very
difficult opening match for us,'' Beal said.
</P>
<P>
   Beal said that seven to nine countries in Sydney are fielding
''legitimate medal teams.'' Pool B standouts include the
Netherlands, Brazil and Cuba, with Spain and Australia not far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there have ever been such a high number of
quality teams in Olympic history,'' Beal said.
</P>
<P>
   A new scoring system, that will make matches shorter, might also
allow less-touted teams such as the Americans to spring surprises.
Beal reasoned that the longer the match, the greater the chance for
a consistently strong team to display its mettle.
</P>
<P>
   With rally scoring, a point will be at stake for every rally,
replacing an earlier system where only the serving team could earn
one. Matches will last about half as long under the new system.
</P>
<P>
   The American men, while faltering in recent years, have a solid
tradition. The United States, where volleyball was invented, took
the men's gold at the Los Angeles Olympics in 1984 and defended
their title successfully four years later at Seoul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 1955 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
