<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Renews Mideast Peace Plans  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- On the day the Palestinians were to have
declared statehood, the Clinton administration launched a fresh
effort Wednesday to restart Mideast peace talks. Israeli Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben Ami said he was ''doubtful about the prospects
of success'' after a meeting with national security adviser Sandy
Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ben Ami agreed to a hurriedly set dinner session Thursday
night with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, and the
Palestinians sent top negotiators to New York to resume the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to try and give it a chance,'' Ben Ami said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Gilad Sher, a specialist on Palestinian issues, met with
Berger as the Clinton administration refused to abandon its drive
to fashion a compromise on the future of Jerusalem and on other key
issues, even with the passing of Wednesday's deadline for a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Ami also took up with Berger promises by the administration
to improve Israel's strategic capabilities. He said U.S. assistance
should not be contingent on whether or not an agreement is reached
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   He also called on the international community to make a strong
statement of support for peacemaking and said the Palestinians were
''regressing'' in their positions since President Clinton hosted a
summit with Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat at Camp David in July.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have made similar complaints about Israel's
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo called
Albright's invitation to send negotiators to New York ''a
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   He said negotiators Saeb Erekat and Mohammed Dahlan would be
there on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's excellent news,'' U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said in New York Wednesday night of the resumption of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton failed to break the deadlock over control of holy sites
in Jerusalem in separate meetings with Arafat and Barak in New York
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians were poised to declare independence Wednesday, the
seventh anniversary of the signing of the first Israel-Palestinian
accord, but put it off to give the talks another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Israel suggested a solution to a territorial issue -- a bridge
over Israel to link the West Bank and Gaza in exchange for Israeli
annexation of parts of the West Bank where most Jewish settlers
live.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Ami said Israel insists on overall sovereignty on the Temple
Mount, known to Muslims as Haram as-Sharif, the Noble Sanctuary.
Ben-Ami said the two sides must ''find some kind of accommodation
that will respect the needs of everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to counter Palestinian concerns that Israel excavate
under the Muslim shrines to uncover the ruins of the Temples,
Ben-Ami told the Al-Ayam newspaper, ''We will obviously take all
commitments not to dig, all international guarantees necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Aburdeneh, an aide to Arafat, rejected compromise.
''Jerusalem is a Palestinian city, and it should be under full
Palestinian sovereignty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has charged that Arafat's inflexible position on Jerusalem
stymied negotiations. Barak's spokesman, Gadi Baltiansky, said,
''We showed openness and flexibility, but the other side was not
ripe for it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 200 Israeli demonstrators marched to the Old City of
Jerusalem at nightfall, demanding that Israel allow the
Palestinians to declare a capital in their part of the city. The
dovish Peace Now group organized the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat complained that interim accords have not been implemented
and demanded international guarantees to force Israel to comply.
''It is sickening, it is frustrating, and Israel cannot get away
with it,'' he told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leftover interim commitments is handing over part of
the West Bank to Palestinian control. Barak hoped to incorporate
that into a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Barak wants to place blocs of West Bank Jewish settlements under
Israeli sovereignty. In exchange, Ben-Ami said, the Palestinians
could freely use a bridge that would be built between the West Bank
and Gaza, separated by 30 miles of Israeli territory.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Ami said Israel would maintain sovereignty over the elevated
road but would conduct no security checks there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 2017 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
