<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Targets Housing Corruption  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Auditors in Washington were
astonished when Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo announced a $130
million settlement of a discrimination suit by Puerto Rico's
housing agency -- despite charges that millions of federal dollars
are misspent, lost or stolen in the nation's second largest housing
program.
</P>
<P>
   Now a U.S. senator is trying to freeze that money ''to make sure
it goes to the people who need it'' -- namely, a quarter million of
Puerto Rico's poor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The deal may have merit. But we want to know how they are
going to spend the money and where it is actually going,'' said
Sen. Christopher Bond, a Missouri Republican whose appropriations
subcommittee oversees the Department of Housing and Urban
Development's budget.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the subcommittee voted to withhold the $130
million until Puerto Rico certifies how it will be spent. ''We
expect (the hold) to go all the way to the White House,'' said Bond
spokesman Ernie Blazar.
</P>
<P>
   HUD spokesman Andrew L. Lluberes insisted the agency ''has zero
tolerance for fraud, waste and abuse'' and ''does not anticipate
any difficulty in satisfying Senator Bond's concerns and, indeed,
has already started on that process.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement -- announced during a Cuomo visit to Puerto Rico
in June -- capped a $500 million lawsuit charging that for 25 years,
HUD had discriminated against Puerto Rico's housing agency in
calculating its annual operating subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   HUD said the action was approved by the Justice Department ''as
being in the best interests of the United States'' -- and argued it
had nothing to do with ongoing efforts to combat corruption or
improve accounting.
</P>
<P>
   But it stunned HUD auditors, including Inspector General Susan
Gaffney, who complained to Cuomo and filed a separate complaint
about Puerto Rico directly with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing the local housing authority of ''flagrant fraud, waste
and abuse,'' Gaffney demanded that a federal judge seize control of
the troubled agency. Deputy HUD Secretary Saul N. Ramirez Jr.
insisted that Puerto Rico was improving its accounting and that
judicial receivership wasn't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation into the alleged embezzlement of $2.5 million
in HUD funds has produced 11 indictments and nine guilty pleas, and
the FBI is conducting its own fraud investigations. A 1998-1999 HUD
audit found $26 million of $39 million in U.S. funds used to pay
contractors was wasted or illegally spent.
</P>
<P>
   The local agency -- second in size to New York City -- has
confronted a host of other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, many residents were virtual captives of heavily
armed drug lords, forcing Puerto Rico's National Guard to seize
control of several projects. Drug-related crime in the projects
accounts for the bulk of Puerto Rico's murder rate -- one of the
highest in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents also live in dangerous conditions with exposed
electric wiring, raw sewage and unsafe playgrounds. HUD has
dispatched teams to ensure repairs are made and monitor accounting
and contracting.
</P>
<P>
   Now the local agency hopes to hang on to its $130 million
settlement. ''Our answer always has been that the cases of fraud
have been reported by the housing authority,'' said agency head
John Blakeman.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, Gaffney asked a federal judge to force Puerto Rico to
turn over documents to determine how Puerto Rico paid up to dlrs
625,000 to defend itself against HUD allegations. HUD regulations
forbid the use of federal funds for litigation against the federal
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 2057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titan's O'Donnell Opts for Comfort  </HEADLINE>
By TERESA M. WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- With a timely off week and one of the
NFL's top backup quarterbacks, the Tennessee Titans are not overly
concerned about Steve McNair's bruised sternum.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans, in perhaps their most important move during the
offseason, kept veteran Neil O'Donnell from signing with anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a huge lift for us,'' tight end Frank Wycheck said.
''I think in this league nowadays you have to have two really
proven starters on your team. Last year Steve goes down, and Neil
picks up the slack, goes 4-1 and was a big, big part of our
championship run.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (1-1) has a bye this Sunday, and McNair will play on
Sept. 24 at Pittsburgh if possible. But coach Jeff Fisher said
O'Donnell will start if McNair isn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell proved his worth yet again last weekend, coming into
the game with 6:25 left and rallying the Titans to a 17-14 victory
in overtime over the Kansas City Chiefs after McNair was hit hard
in the chest by the Chiefs' Duane Clemons.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell was 11-of-17 for 132 yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans nearly lost him to Tampa Bay during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year veteran had only a one-year contract with the Titans
for last season, hoping to find a job as a starter. Tampa Bay came
calling, looking for a backup to Shaun King and offering more money
than the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   After all, O'Donnell ranks 12th all-time among NFL quarterbacks
with his passer rating, and he is the NFL's career leader among
active quarterbacks in lowest interception percentage.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an easy choice.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell was friends with Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy from their
years together in Pittsburgh, and he had people calling, urging him
to join the Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Leslie, was a big factor in his decision to stay. She
had moved the family from New York in 1998 to Cincinnati and to
Nashville in 1999, and it was a joint decision to remain in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell accepted the Titans' three-year contract worth at
least $7.6 million, even though it meant less money.
</P>
<P>
   ''You look at the business-side and the personal/social side,''
O'Donnell said. ''We feel pretty comfortable here. I like the
locker room. I like the players, so let's keep this good thing
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran's performance in rallying the Titans last weekend
started talk on radio shows that McNair should be benched. But
there hasn't been any complaints from O'Donnell or anyone else of a
quarterback controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Fisher credits both O'Donnell and McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their relationship is excellent. You don't realize how well
they work together on the practice field, in the meetings as well
as on the sidelines during the game. Neil understands his role,''
Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell has been through quarterback controversies, and he has
no desire to whip up a problem here.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been at this long enough. I understand all that. It's not
good for the locker room. It's not good for the team. I know it
would make (a reporter's) job easier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
