<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schulters' Return May Help Niners'  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Lance Schulters wants the San
Francisco 49ers' defense to start playing more like he does.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro Bowl safety says the 49ers can begin to solve their
defensive problems by taking risks and being more reckless. It's a
strange prescription for a team as young and inexperienced as the
Niners, but Schulters said it's the only chance San Francisco will
have against Kurt Warner and the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the first two games of the season because of a
sprained left ankle, Schulters plans to lead by example when San
Francisco travels to St. Louis on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We aren't going to play scared this week,'' Schulters said.
''We keep harping on the deep ball, but we've got to forget the
deep ball. We've got to take chances and not worry about giving up
a big play. In this league, you can't play the way we've been
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Schulters spent most of Wednesday's practice resting
on the sidelines and coach Steve Mariucci said a final decision
hadn't been made, Schulters said he'll play against the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ''By game time, I should be close to 100 percent,'' Schulters
said. ''I can cut and break a little better than I could (while
recovering from a similar injury) last year.''
</P>
<P>
   His return would be the first good news in a long while for a
defense that's last in the NFL in points allowed (74), total yards
allowed (809) and passing yards allowed (616). Sunday's game
matches that league-worst defense against the NFL's best offense.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the optimist, Mariucci called the game ''an excellent
test'' for the 49ers' painfully young defense, particularly a
secondary that featured just five healthy players at the end of
Sunday's 38-22 loss to Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Schulters, backup cornerback Zack Bronson didn't
practice Wednesday while recuperating from a stinger suffered on
Sunday. Starting cornerback Monty Montgomery was on crutches
earlier this week but is expected to play as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the 49ers' defensive problems are likely to continue all
season long, regardless of which players are healthy. With one of
the league's youngest rosters and a complete inability to sign
significant free agents because of salary cap constraints, the
49ers have no choice but to rebuild their once-proud defense.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Jim Mora chuckled when he remembered a
sequence against Carolina in which the 49ers fielded eight
defenders who were playing in their second pro game.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at the big picture, you say this is exactly what
we need,'' Mora said. ''The only way they're going to get better is
to play. It's an opportunity that a lot of young players don't
get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, who Mariucci called ''the fastest team ever assembled
on a football field,'' frequently use plays featuring four wide
receivers. That means rookie cornerbacks Ahmed Plummer and Jason
Webster, rookie safety John Keith, second-year safety Pierson
Prioleau and second-year cornerback Anthony Parker all will be on
the field a great deal on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pressure is what makes rough stones into diamonds,'' Webster
said. ''They have great talent, but we can't allow it to rattle
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 2103 </TRAILER>
