<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Task force to address violent crime  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) - After the fifth shooting in six days, city
and county law enforcement officials announced Wednesday they will
form a Major Crimes Investigations Unit to combat violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday morning, police said a soured drug deal led to
the shooting of a man and the arrest of another, bringing to eight
the number of people shot in the city since Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The new task force will be patterned after a federal/state/local
Utica Arson Strike Force formed in 1997 after a series of Cornhill
and East Utica fires, said Oneida County District Attorney Michael
A. Arcuri.
</P>
<P>
   He said the task force will investigate shootings, homicides,
rape and other violent crimes. Planning for the new unit should be
complete within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The task forced is formed in the face of criticism by some in
the community who say the city has acted slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I support this task force and I hope it will eliminate drug
dealers and put an end to these shootings,'' said Councilman Howard
Welch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
