<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriot Leader Skips UN Talks  </HEADLINE>
By ALEX EFTY
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Angered by a statement from the U.N.
chief, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides boycotted the second day
of U.N.-sponsored talks on reunifying Cyprus on Wednesday and gave
no indication he would return Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clerides was upset by a statement from U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan that the Greek Cypriots see as favoring the breakaway
Turkish Cypriot state, said Cyprus government spokesman Michalis
Papapetrou.
</P>
<P>
   Clerides sent Annan a letter ''expressing his interpretation and
views in connection with the statement issued by the
secretary-general yesterday,'' Papapetrou said.
</P>
<P>
   While Clerides spent the day away from U.N. headquarters,
Turkish Cypriot leader Raouf Denktash, who had welcomed Annan's
statement, met as planned with Annan's special adviser on Cyprus,
Alvaro de Soto.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a happy day,'' a beaming Denktash told reporters on
arrival at U.N. Headquarters on Wednesday. After a 75-minute
meeting with de Soto, Denktash said he would return Thursday for
more talks, without revealing what was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Annan had told the rival Cypriot leaders by letter that the time
had come for them to move toward reunification of their war-divided
island.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek Cypriots were upset by the statement, which they
interpreted as a shift in the U.N. position, equating the
internationally recognized Cyprus government of Clerides with the
breakaway Turkish Cypriot state in the Turkish-occupied northern
part of the island.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish Cypriot state is recognized only by Turkey, which
maintains 35,000 troops there.
</P>
<P>
   The Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 2126 </TRAILER>
