<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts from the Clinton-Lazio debate  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Here are excerpts from the
debate Wednesday
between U.S. Senate candidates Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rep. Rick
Lazio.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: Clinton is shown a video clip of her January 1998
appearance on NBC's ''Today'' show in which she said President
Clinton had not been involved with Monica Lewinsky and accused a
''vast right wing conspiracy'' of trying to destroy his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you regret misleading the American people?''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON: ''That was a very painful time for me, for my family,
and for our country. It is something that I regret deeply that
anyone had to go through. ... I'm very hopeful that we can go
forward in a united way. That certainly is what I've tried to do.
And I've tried to be as forthcoming as I could given the
circumstances that I faced.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, I didn't mislead anyone. I didn't know the truth.
And there's a great deal of pain associated with that, and my
husband has certainly acknowledged that and made it clear that he
did mislead the country as well as his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: ''In trying to unite people, however, is it appropriate to
brand anyone who criticized the president as part of a vast right
wing conspiracy?''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON: ''I certainly didn't mean to extend that to anyone who
might criticize the president, especially after the truth came out.
You know I have the greatest respect for Sen. (Joseph) Lieberman,
(a vocal critic of the president). ... But I think there is strong
opposition within the country to the vision that I share with many
about what we'd like to do for our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: ''In your response, Mr. Lazio, would you also address your
fundraising letter of July 2000, where you said the first lady
embarrassed our country?''
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: ''I stand by that fundraising letter. I stand by that
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What's so troubling here with respect to what my opponent just
said is somehow that it only matters what you say when you get
caught. And character and trust is about well more than that. And
blaming others every time you have responsibility, unfortunately
that's become a pattern, I think, for my opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------
</P>
<P>
   Q: Lazio is asked if a vote against a bill that would have
allowed patients to sue health insurance companies showed he was
more loyal to the Republican House leadership than to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: ''I don't think anybody can rationally say that. ... In
fact, if you look at my record, it's a record of independence in
the House.''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON: ''Listening to the congressman's response reminds me of
a word I've heard a lot of this past year, chutzpah. He stands
there and tells us that he's a moderate, mainstream, independent
member of Congress. Well, in fact, he was a deputy whip to Newt
Gingrich, he voted to shut the government down. ..... Time and time
again, when he's had a choice to make ... he's stood with the
Republican leadership and Newt Gingrich.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON: ''Talking about the issues is something that he's not
very comfortable about, because he does have these votes and this
record, not just back when you were deputy whip to Newt Gingrich,
but in the last year or two.''
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: ''It's beyond shameless, I guess. The tactic of naming a
bunch of things and knowing that I don't have enough time to answer
all of them is just positively Clintonesque.''
</P>
<P>
   ''... Newt Gingrich is not running. If you had a record, I
suppose, you wouldn't need to use Newt Gingrich. I'm running. And I
have a strong New York record.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: (after Clinton described her ideas on education).
</P>
<P>
   ''I agree that Mrs. Clinton has got a record on education, and
it's a disaster. She was responsible for educational changes in
Arkansas, and you know what happened? Spending went up, taxes went
up and student performance went down ... I don't think we need that
Little Rock record in the Big Apple.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------
</P>
<P>
   Q: ''Will both of you set an example for the rest of the country
and renounce the use of soft money ads for the rest of this
campaign?''
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: ''Absolutely. ... I have right here a pledge that I sent
over to my opponent. It's a 'ban on soft money' pledge. I'm willing
to say I will neither raise nor spend a dime of soft money, and ask
all outside groups to stay away if my opponent is willing to do the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON: ''Back in May, I made exactly that offer. ... If you
will get signed agreements from all your friends, who say they're
raising $32 million, and will not be running so-called independent
ads, will not be doing push-polling, will not be doing mass
mailings that are filled with these outrageous personal attacks, I
think we can have an agreement. I'd like to see those signed
letters.''
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: ''I want to get it done right now, I don't want any more
wiggle room, I don't want any more evasions. ... Let's just get
this deal done right now. Right here. Here it is. Let's sign it,
it's the New York Freedom from Soft Money Pact. I signed it. ... We
will make sure it's an iron-clad deal.''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON: ''I admire that. That was a wonderful performance.
...''
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: ''Why don't you sign it? I'm not asking you to admire it,
I'm asking you to sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON: ''Well, I would be happy to when you give me the signed
letters.''
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: ''Right here, right here. Sign it right now. (He leaves
his podium and walks across the stage to Clinton, handing her a
sheet of paper.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON: ''We'll shake on it.'' (They shake hands.)
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO: ''No, I want your signature. Everybody wants to see you
sign something that you said you were for. (He points to the
pledge.) ... Why don't you show some leadership, because it goes to
trust and character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
