<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debate was proving ground for Senate candidates  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Trying to show that he's not just a
babyfaced un-Hillary, Rep. Rick Lazio went on the attack against
the first lady in their first debate Wednesday, wielding
soundbite-sized insults and an actual prop in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   NBC spokeswoman Barb Levin said Lazio violated an agreement both
campaigns had made not to use props when he produced a contract
that would ban the use of unregulated donations. Lazio left his
podium and strode over to Hillary Rodham Clinton's side of the
stage with the contract in his hand as he repeatedly asked her to
sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   She said she would only sign it if he got agreements from the
Republican committees that have been sending out letters and
producing TV ads attacking her on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   While the exchange appeared dramatic on TV, with the two
candidates interrupting each other and Lazio shoving the paper in
front of Clinton's face, the studio audience regarded it as a light
moment, laughing nervously as they watched to see how Clinton would
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ''People got to see for themselves that it was a trick for the
TV camera,'' said Ann Lewis, one of Clinton's campaign advisers.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio campaign manager Bill Dal Col defended the gimmick,
saying, ''It was time to stop the Clinton shuffle.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also did plenty of attacking of her own, repeatedly
tarring Lazio with Newt Gingrich's name, while Lazio turned the
tables and accused her of being ''Clintonesque.'' The two
candidates also accused the other of having ''chutzpah.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Miringoff, head of the Poughkeepsie-based Marist Institute
for Public Opinion, described the debate as being ''very combative
... This was really rough stuff. They were in your face the whole
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they decided there weren't a lot of undecided voters.
They weren't trying to convert people that weren't supporting
them,'' he told WNBC-TV. ''What they were trying to do ... was
reinforce their base.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a Marist poll showed voters nearly evenly divided in
their support, with 50 percent going for Clinton and 47 percent
supporting Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Bob McClure, a Syracuse University political science professor,
said ''Hillary had to prove she didn't have horns. Rick had to
prove he had something between his ears. And both of them came out
of the debate with something.''
</P>
<P>
   McClure said Lazio took a risk by confronting Clinton with the
soft money contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has to show he can stand up to her, that he's a person of
principle and substance,'' McClure said. ''At the same time, he
takes the risk of potentially looking churlish and aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio appeared to have been prepped with numerous snappy
one-liners. When Clinton's health care debacle was mentioned, Lazio
said: ''A New Yorker would never have made that proposal. In New
York, we say you gotta tell it like it is.''
</P>
<P>
   In a ''spin'' room set up just outside the auditorium,
representatives from both campaigns stood at podiums and
highlighted their candidates' performance to reporters after the
event. But the spinning began long before the debate. The Clinton
campaign distributed a ''Special Debate Pre-Buttal'' attacking
Lazio, and Lazio staffers distributed e-mails and memos throughout
the debate to dozens of reporters watching it in on large-screen
TVs at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for her part, tried to seem likable, twice taking
precious seconds from her speaking time to thank the organizers of
the debate, and once asking a member of the audience who had
submitted a question to identify himself so she could personally
address him.
</P>
<P>
   She also briefly reincarnated herself as the victimized wife of
a philandering husband, blinking, swallowing and stammering a
response to a question about why she misled the country by
initially denying that President Clinton had an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't mislead anyone,'' she said quietly. ''I didn't know
the truth. There's a great deal of pain associated with that.''
</P>
<P>
   McClure said Clinton ''handled that well ... It actually served
to advance her own standing.''
</P>
<P>
   About 240 people - including 40 guests from each campaign -
attended the debate, which was moderated by Buffalo native Tim
Russert, host of NBC's ''Meet the Press'' and held in the studios
of Buffalo's public television station, WNED-TV.
</P>
<P>
   After the debate was over, Lazio celebrated his wife Pat's 40th
birthday with a cake and party at a nearby hotel. To the cheers of
about 200 guests, Lazio said: ''We New Yorkers don't back down from
a fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-13-00 2143 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
