<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Rural Forest Aid Bill  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal aid for schools and roads in hundreds
of rural counties would increase by $222 million next year under a
bill approved by the Senate Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill by Sens. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, and Ron Wyden, D-Ore.,
changes the formula for distributing aid to counties that have
tax-exempt federal forest land within county boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1908 law, counties with federal forests nearby receive
25 percent of the revenue generated from the forests, mostly from
logging.
</P>
<P>
   But as logging on federal land declined by nearly 80 percent in
the last decade, so did the aid for many rural counties. Rural
school officials were forced to lay off teachers, cut back programs
and cancel equipment purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The Craig-Wyden bill increases and stabilizes the payments to
counties by tying the annual aid amount to a three-year average of
the highest forest payments between 1986 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the payments would come from the U.S. Treasury
regardless of how much timber is cut on federal land, though some
of the aid would still be tied to forest revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ''This legislation is about not abandoning rural America,''
Wyden said after the Senate approved the bill by unanimous consent.
</P>
<P>
   County aid would go from $273 million in 1999 to $495 million
next year, under the bill.
</P>
<P>
   At least some counties in all 50 states receive aid under the
92-year-old program, though most of the money goes to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon would be the biggest beneficiary, with about $260 million
in aid next year, followed by California, with $65 million,
Washington state, with $44 million, and Idaho, with nearly $23
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration favors the Senate bill. ''We applaud
the Senate,'' said Chris Wood, a top aide to Forest Service Chief
Mike Dombeck, after Wednesday's Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials oppose a version of the bill passed
by the House last November, saying that version -- among other
things -- encourages logging.
</P>
<P>
   Senators hope to get the House to agree to the Senate version
with few, if any, changes before Congress adjourns for the year
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists opposed provisions in both bills that allow
counties to use up to 20 percent of the federal aid to develop
joint county-federal projects on federal land such as tourism and
road maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The activists complained that most local projects would focus on
one of the biggest money makers -- logging.
</P>
<P>
   But Craig, Wyden and Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., reached a
compromise with some Democratic colleagues who had environmental
concerns about the bill.
</P>
<P>
   They crafted language that would have proceeds from the county
projects go to the Treasury, not to the counties, and they expanded
the scope of projects allowed under to include more conservation
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a true bipartisan, team effort,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the roles Smith played was to intervene when Sen. Don
Nickles, R-Okla., temporarily held the Craig-Wyden bill hostage as
part of a fight Wyden and Nickles have been having over
physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know of a bill that has had me in more hallway
meetings and pleadings than this one,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.thomas.gov
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is S. 1608.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 2147 </TRAILER>
