<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vt's Flanagan is Gay Senate Nominee  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) -- In a state clearly divided over its
landmark law allowing civil unions for gay couples, a Democratic
state auditor has become the nation's first openly gay major-party
U.S. Senate nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Flanagan said Wednesday he was proud to be a leader in
the gay-rights movement, but added, ''I am asking Vermonters not to
waste a single vote either for me or against me because of my
private life.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan, who narrowly defeated state Sen. Jan Backus in
Tuesday's primary, has been low-key about his sexuality since
making it public five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But he was active in encouraging state lawmakers last winter to
pass Vermont's first-in-the-nation civil unions law, which granted
the rights and responsibilities of marriage to same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   In listing problems he would fight to redress, Flanagan cited 45
million Americans without health insurance and the difficulty many
elderly Americans have affording prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The political consensus within the beltway that things are
just fine is not in touch with the reality that exists here in
Vermont and across the country,'' Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan faces a fall campaign that could create a dilemma for
some gay and lesbian activists.
</P>
<P>
   Two-term incumbent James Jeffords, a Republican, has been among
the senators most supportive of gay issues. He wrote the bill that
created the Ryan White Fund, which provides assistance to people
with AIDS, and currently is the lead sponsor of a bill to outlaw
employment discrimination based on sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords also chairs the Senate Health, Education, Labor and
Pensions committee, which has jurisdiction over many of those
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''The voters in Vermont have a difficult choice and an
embarrassment of riches,'' said Winnie Stachelberg, political
director of the Washington-based Human Rights Campaign. ''It's an
example I hope we see in other states in the coming years.''
</P>
<P>
   Divisions over the civil unions law also created voter backlash
that ousted six state legislators -- five Republicans who supported
the law and one Democrat who opposed it. Not all went quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kinsey, a lawmaker in the state House for 30 years, was
soundly defeated in the Republican primary but won a write-in
campaign among Democrats. He said Wednesday he would accept the
nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 2153 </TRAILER>
