<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNative Women Occupy New Brunswick Fisheries Office
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURNT CHURCH, New Brunswick (AP) -- About 30 native women and
children occupied a federal Fisheries Department office for 2&AMP;frac12;
hours Wednesday, demanding the return of seized lobster traps.
</P>
<P>
   The natives from the Burnt Church reserve entered the office in
nearby Tracadie-Sheila and asked the secretaries for the traps the
department seized over the past five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to get our traps one way or the other,'' said
Martina Parker, one of the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries officers confiscated at least 2,000 traps, roughly 10
boats and arrested dozens of people on fisheries violations and
criminal charges in the weeks since the latest hostilities began on
Miramichi Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Under a band management plan, every man, woman and child in
Burnt Church is entitled to four lobster traps.
</P>
<P>
   The natives occupying the office were told they had to fill out
forms claiming ownership of the traps, then wait a month to get
them back. The catch is that anyone who claims ownership could be
charged with illegal fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Most ended up signing and left peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Protester Gail Paul said the band badly needs the equipment to
keep fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We stand by our treaty rights,'' she said.
---
Stephen Lewis Raises Plight of Kidnapped Sudan Kids
</P>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manatoba (AP) -- Put the lives of children ahead of
oil, Canada's former ambassador to the United Nations urged world
leaders Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Lewis told an international conference on war-affected
children the world must force the government of Sudan to free
thousands of children being held in the country by a Ugandan rebel
group.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every single day that we pretend that moral suasion is the
answer is another day carved out of the life of a child,'' Lewis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The numbers are not that large, the villains are clear, it's
the perfect test.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there cannot be agreement on a policy ... so that
eventually the government of Sudan capitulates and the children are
returned, then this conference risks and warrants a cynical
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated 6,000 children are being held in camps in Sudan
by the Lord's Resistance Army, which is battling the Ugandan
government. Although it claims fundamentalist Christian principles,
the LRA kidnaps and forces children to fight in its army on pain of
death.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy has made saving the
kidnapped children a priority, although he has faced criticism for
allowing Sudan's foreign minister to attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy has said that under Canadian legislation, he cannot
take any action against Talisman unless there is international
agreement.
---
Videotron Agrees To Quebecor Takeover
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- A brand-new multimedia group is about to join
the majors in Canada after Groupe Videotron said Wednesday it has
agreed to be taken over by Quebecor Inc. for about $4.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Videotron, Quebec's largest cable TV operator, also said it has
broken off its merger agreement with Rogers Communications and paid
the Toronto cable and cellphone giant the required $241 million
breakup fee.
</P>
<P>
   Videotron's controlling shareholders, the Chagnon family, have
entered into a lockup agreement with Quebecor and its partner the
Caisse de depot to tender their stake in Videotron. The company
also said the parties have agreed to stop all court actions over
the future of Videotron and reached an out of court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ends nearly seven months of wrangling that had pitted
Quebecor -- one of Canada's multimedia powerhouses -- and the Caisse,
the country's largest pension fund, against Rogers, a deep-pocketed
company well connected to Canada's financial center on Toronto's
Bay Street.
</P>
<P>
   Under Wednesday's deal, Quebecor and Caisse-owned Capital
Communications will make a new or revised all cash takeover bid, at
the same price of $45 a share that it made in August. The offer
will expire three weeks after its mailing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first responsibility of managers and directors of public
companies is to maximize value for all shareholders,'' Andre
Chagnon, chairman, and son Claude, chief executive, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''On that score, we are happy of what we have accomplished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
