<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School Employee Fakes News Release  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GADSDEN, Ala. (AP) -- A school employee says he created and
disseminated a bogus White House news release heralding his
teen-age daughter's volunteerism and sent it to media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hanvey's daughter, a high school junior, was honored for
volunteerism from the President's Student Service Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   She received a packet that included a certificate, form letter
and a lapel pin, said Robin Blaine, the program's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   ''What she did was probably really good,'' Blaine said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Blaine said she told Hanvey to retract the news
release after being notified of its contents, which appeared in at
least one newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, we don't condone anyone improperly using the White
House image,'' said Jason Schechter, a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Hanvey, trade industrial education coordinator for the Gadsden
school system, said the incident was ''the worst mistake of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The fake release included a picture doctored to look as if
President Clinton handed her the award. It also quoted the girl's
remarks, implying that she delivered a speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
