<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Sept. 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FAA, Boeing Agree on Rudder Repair
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Under an agreement with the Federal Aviation
Administration, Boeing is to redesign the rudders of all its 737s, the most
widely used jetliner in the world. The rudders have been suspect following a
pair of fatal accidents in Colorado and Pennsylvania. Three changes have
previously been mandated in 737 rudder controls and officials said they have had
no reports of rudder problems since. Because the redesign could take years, the
FAA will announce new training procedures for pilots on the more than 3,000
twin-engine jets now in service.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Clinton, Lazio Debate in N.Y.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton repeatedly attacked Republican
Rep. Rick Lazio as too conservative for New York in the first debate of their
Senate campaign. Lazio responded by trying to link his Democratic rival to the
policies and the peccadilloes of President Clinton, her husband. The often testy
exchanges included one where Lazio walked to her side and tried unsuccessfully
to get her to sign a pledge to bar soft money from their Senate campaigns.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
First Lady's Guest List Checked
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House is considering media requests for names of
overnight guests after suggestions today that Hillary Rodham Clinton offered
stays at the White House to supporters of her Senate campaign. ''We're reviewing
the requests,'' deputy White House spokesman Jake Siewert said. The senior
spokesman, Joe Lockhart, confirmed that political supporters have stayed at the
White House, but dismissed the notion that the first lady did anything improper.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nuke Scientist Wen Ho Lee Is Free
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Wen Ho Lee was set free today after pleading guilty
to one count under a deal in which prosecutors all but abandoned their crumbling
case against him, nine months after he was placed in solitary confinement as a
national security threat. U.S. District Judge James Parker said he was bound by
the plea agreement to sentence the fired Los Alamos scientist to 278 days, one
day less than he already has served since his arrest last December. In court,
Lee read a statement in which he admitted using an unsecure computer to download
a document relating to national defense onto a tape.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Army To Align National Guard
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army for the first time will align National Guard
divisions with active-duty Army corps, making it more likely that part-time
soldiers will ship out if war erupts in Korea or the Persian Gulf, Army
officials said today. The change reflects Army leaders' search for ways to make
better use of the National Guard at a time when the active-duty force is
stretched thin by a variety of peacetime missions across the globe. Gen. Eric
Shinseki, the Army chief of staff, is to announce the plan tomorrow at a
National Guard convention in New Jersey.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lieberman: Campaign Will Open Doors
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Democratic Vice Presidential candidate Joseph I.
Lieberman told prominent Jewish leaders today that he hopes his candidacy opens
doors for people from all walks of life. ''I'm here for a principle, the
principle of inclusiveness and opportunity,'' he said at a fund-raiser in the
Boston area. Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, made his remarks at a $10,000-a-plate
fund-raising event at the home of Ahron Solomont, brother of former Democratic
National Committee finance chairman Alan Solomont.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chase To Acquire J.P. Morgan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp. has agreed to acquire J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co. for about $36 billion in stock, uniting two of the oldest and most
prestigious financial firms in the United States. Company officials decided to
retain both names in the newly formed J.P. Morgan Chase &AMP; Co. The combined firm
will have about $668 billion in assets, rivaling Bank of America Corp., with
about $679 billion in assets, as the second largest bank holding company in the
United States.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Advance
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks advanced early Thursday, supported by gains in
technology stocks on Wall Street. The dollar was lower against the yen. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 64.84 points, or 0.40 percent,
to 16,255.36 in early trading. On Wednesday, the average closed up 150.29
points, or 0.94 percent. In New York, the Nasdaq composite index rose 44.38
points to 3,893.89 at Wednesday's finish, and the Dow Jones industrial average
fell 51.05 to close at 11,182.18.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knight Delivers Farewell Speech
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Bob Knight bid farewell to Indiana University,
saluting cheering students and urging them to forget about the freshman who
played a part in the coach's firing. ''Let that kid be a student and let him get
on with life,'' Knight said tonight. ''That kid is not responsible for my not
coaching at Indiana, and make sure you understand that.'' The peaceful crowd at
Dunn Meadow was estimated by police at about 6,000.
AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER 
</P>
