<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Authority OKs Pro Bowl Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- The Hawaii Tourism Authority approved a contract
to keep the Pro Bowl in Hawaii for another four years.
</P>
<P>
   The contract approved Wednesday by a voice vote calls for the
state to pay the NFL nearly $19.75 million for games from 2002-05.
</P>
<P>
   The current contract ends with the 2001 game.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract pledges ''best efforts'' by the state to
provide a natural playing surface at Aloha Stadium by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   It also creates a partnership between the state and the NFL that
would pave the way for cooperation on Pro Bowl travel packages, a
Pro Bowl museum, and other sources of revenue, according to former
tourism authority member Mark Rolfing, who negotiated the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has approved the contract terms, Rolfing said.
</P>
</TEXT>
