<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians 10, Red Sox 3  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Bartolo Colon was finally the No. 1 starter
Cleveland needs him to be and Manny Ramirez homered and drove in
four runs Wednesday night, leading the Indians to a 10-3 win over
the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved Cleveland 1&AMP;frac12; games ahead of Oakland and three
games up on Boston in the AL wild card race. And the timing
couldn't have been better for the Indians -- Pedro Martinez will
start for the Red Sox on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is 8-0 in his career against Cleveland and will be
pitching in Jacobs Field for the first time since April 30 when he
hit Roberto Alomar and was suspended for five games.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez hit a three-run double off Tomo Ohka (3-5) in the fourth
and later added his 29th homer. He has eight RBIs in the first two
games of the series and 102 in just 97 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Branyan and David Segui added two-run homers for the
Indians, who play the Red Sox six more times in the next eight
days.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Varitek homered for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Colon (13-8) allowed two earned runs and six hits in seven
innings. In his last start, Colon was leading 3-1 and needed one
out to get through the seventh, when he told Indians manager
Charlie Manuel he was tired.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't what Manuel wanted to hear and he sat the
25-year-old down for a talk. Apparently, Colon took it to heart. He
hit 100 mph in striking out Carl Everett in the first, and was
never in real trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Colon didn't have a 1-2-3 inning until the seventh when he made
a nice play covering first for an out after David Segui knocked
down a hard liner. Branyan then made a nice running catch on Nomar
Garciaparra to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's three-run double with two outs in the fourth off Ohka
gave the Indians a 6-1 lead. Einar Diaz singled with one out and
Ohka walked Omar Vizquel with two down. Roberto Alomar then battled
the right-hander for nine pitches before walking.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez went ahead 3-0 in the count before lining his double
into the right-field gap.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox got a run back in the fifth on Troy O'Leary's RBI
groundout and Varitek's 10th homer brought Boston within 6-3 in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland blew it open in the seventh on Ramirez's homer and
Segui's 435-foot blast to center off Hector Carrasco.
</P>
<P>
   Branyan, who will be getting the bulk of the playing time in
left field with Wil Cordero out with a broken hand, put the Indians
up 2-0 in the second with his 15th homer.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland added another run in the inning on Vizquel's RBI
single.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox got a run back in the third on Troy O'Leary's RBI
double.
</P>
<P>
Notes: TV actor George Wendt, best known as Norm from ''Cheers''
was spotted having dinner in the Terrace Club in Jacobs Field. When
Wendt appeared on the stadium scoreboard, he raised a pint of beer
and toasted the crowd. ... Branyan has 15 homers in 136 at-bats.
... Boston manager Jimy Williams couldn't have been happy to see
seven TV cameras perched atop the wall in center. Last season,
Williams made the Indians cover one camera he thought they were
using to steal signs. ... Ramirez moved into sole possession of
third place on the Indians' career homer list with 227. He passed
Hall of Famer Earl Averill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
