<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers keep working under expired contract; negotiations continue </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Students and teachers were expected to
remain in school Thursday and Friday as labor negotiations between
Buffalo teachers and administrators continued to move toward a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd have to say we're cautiously encouraged by the movement on
the part of the federation. That's not to say we've been rigid,''
said board of education spokesman Andrew Maddigan Wednesday night.
Maddigan said the school board was briefed by the district's
negotiating team for several hours Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Maddigan said he expected talks to resume Thursday in the labor
dispute that canceled classes for two days last week when teachers
abruptly struck, stranding the city's 47,000 students. School has
been in session since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Buffalo Teachers Federation said the
union's executive board had gone home for the night and would
likely meet at 6 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   School Board President Paul Buchanan said contract talks between
the district and the teachers have come down to a handful of
issues, many of which, ''revolve around money.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's 3,700 teachers, meanwhile, continued to suspend their
strike and work under the terms of a contract that expired in June
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Offers and counteroffers center on the length of the contract
and salary increases. Late last week, the union was seeking 3.5
percent annual increases, while the district was offering 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The union also opposes health insurance concessions sought by
the district and the district's plan to contract with outside
agencies to provide social services to students and their families.
</P>
<P>
   While the district has obtained a preliminary injunction
ordering the teachers to refrain from striking, union leaders have
not ruled out another work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore and other union leaders face potential jail terms for
calling the strike, illegal under the state's Taylor Law. Teachers
also face a fine of two days' pay for every day they strike. Court
hearings on contempt charges brought by the district are set for
Thursday and Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
