<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korean Leader To Visit S. Korea  </HEADLINE>
By KYONG-HWA SEOK
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Senior officials of South and North
Korea worked out details Thursday on a visit to South Korea by
North Korean leader Kim Jong Il and other measures aimed at easing
tension on the divided Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Yong Sun, a visiting special envoy of the North Korean
leader, and his South Korean counterpart, Lim Dong-won, were
expected to issue a joint statement later Thursday after their
talks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They were trying to set dates for Kim Jong Il's Seoul visit, a
meeting of their defense ministers and more reunions of separated
families.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Yong Sun was to pay a courtesy call on South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung before returning home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean pool reports, citing unnamed government officials,
said Wednesday that the two sides agreed to arrange for Kim Jong Il
to make his first visit to Seoul next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Both Koreas also will hold their first meeting of defense
ministers in Hong Kong later this month, said the pool reports.
</P>
<P>
   They will also hold another round of Red Cross talks in the
North as early as Monday to discuss more reunions of Koreans
separated from relatives since the 1950-53 Korean War, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The reports were filed by South Korean journalists. Foreign news
media were not included in the press pool organized by South Korean
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jong Il had promised to visit Seoul in return for Kim
Dae-jung's visit to Pyongyang in June.
</P>
<P>
   Inter-Korea relations have warmed significantly since the June
summit, when Kim Dae-jung and Kim Jong Il pledged to put the past
behind and work together for peace. No North Korean head of state
has visited Seoul and the planned trip would be a new milestone in
improving ties.
</P>
<P>
   The Koreas allowed 200 people to cross the border in August for
temporary reunions with families they haven't seen for half a
century. Two more reunions are expected by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The Koreas have also agreed to reconnect a cross-border railway
and let their athletes march together behind a unification flag
during the opening ceremonies at the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Yong Sun toured Cheju island off the southern coast on
Tuesday and Wednesday. Kim Jong Il reportedly wants to visit the
resort island during his trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean Peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
pro-Western South Korea in 1945. Their 1950-53 Korean War ended
without a peace treaty, and their border remains the world's most
heavily fortified, with almost 2 million troops deployed on both
sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 2259 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000913.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif Handyman Spared Death Penalty  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTINE HANLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- A motel handyman was convicted of murder
Wednesday for killing a Yosemite National Park naturalist but still
faces trial and a possible death penalty for allegedly killing
three tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Stayner pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court to
kidnapping, attempting to sexually assault and killing Joie
Armstrong on July 21, 1999. In exchange for his plea to
first-degree murder, he will be sentenced in November to life in
prison with no chance of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner displayed little emotion during a subdued 30-minute
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It brings back a lot of painful memories for him,'' his lawyer
Robert Rainwater said later. ''A young woman died in the prime of
her life and a young man will stand the rest of his life in prison.
And there are two grieving families.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement that Stayner, his lawyer and prosecutors signed
Sept. 6 requires that he take his story to his grave to spare the
family from any additional media attention. The only exception is
any testimony or communication with his lawyer regarding other
state or federal murder cases.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner also agreed to a $10 million restitution order to go to
a fund in Armstrong's name and to meet with her family if they
wish.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will never be a time when Joie will not be a vital part
of our lives,'' said a statement from the Armstrong family. ''Her
life was full of laughter and love and, at the time of her death,
she was enthusiastic about her future and was in the happiest
period of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   The plea is a pivotal stage in a case that has gained worldwide
attention, embarrassed the FBI and left federal and state
prosecutors quarreling. It shifts Stayner's fate to state court,
where prosecutors have been awaiting the chance to try him in the
slayings of three Yosemite tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner, 39, still faces the death penalty if convicted in the
slayings of Carole Sund, 42, her daughter Juli, 15, and their
Argentine friend Silvina Pelosso, 16.
</P>
<P>
   The women were killed five months before Armstrong, during a
sightseeing trip to Yosemite. They had been staying at the Cedar
Lodge, a remote and rustic motel outside the park's western gate
where Stayner lived and worked.
</P>
<P>
   It was their disappearance in February 1999 that prompted an FBI
manhunt, as scores of agents fanned out across the rugged and
rolling terrain of the western Sierra to search for clues.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner was interviewed early in the investigation but ruled out
as a suspect. He later helped agents collect evidence from the
motel rooms and was in their midst as the case unfolded and the
investigation went astray.
</P>
<P>
   Based on circumstantial evidence and what was later believed to
be a false confession, investigators plunged into the region's
methamphetamine netherworld and focused on a group of violent
ex-cons. At one point, an FBI agent said he was confident most of
the main suspects in the sightseer case were behind bars on other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   It was Stayner, arrested three days after Armstrong's murder,
who finally unraveled the mystery, admitting to a top FBI
interrogator that he killed all four women, according to court
documents. He also led investigators to weapons and other physical
evidence, and later re-enacted the crimes on videotape, according
to law enforcement sources.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariposa County District Attorney's office, which has
jurisdiction, can go forward with its case against Stayner as soon
as he is formally sentenced in Armstrong's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas C. Hastings, a Santa Clara County judge who presided over
the high-profile Polly Klaas murder trial, has been assigned to
hear the sightseer case. But no hearing dates have been set, no
pleas entered, and an attorney has not been appointed or hired to
represent Stayner.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Plea agreement filed in court: http://www2.caed.uscourts.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-13-00 2300 </TRAILER>
