<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Gymnast Hurts Ankle in Practice  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- With one gymnast already out with an
injury, the U.S. women's team got another scare when Jamie
Dantzscher rolled her right ankle during training.
</P>
<P>
   Dantzscher continued practicing Thursday (Wednesday night EDT)
after getting her ankle taped and said the injury isn't serious.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should be better by tomorrow, hopefully,'' she said. ''If
not, at least in a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's team competition begins Sunday (Saturday night EDT).
</P>
<P>
   Dantzscher was doing a warmup dance move when she landed short
in a corner. She winced, but continued practicing for a few minutes
before taking a seat at the edge of the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's that bad,'' said Steve Rybacki, her coach.
''I saw her twist it and she didn't have her full weight on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dantzscher had a brief conversation with Rybacki, who is also
the U.S. assistant coach, and head coach Bela Karolyi before
hopping off the podium. She had her ankle taped during the team's
rest period and sat out again when the U.S. team moved to the
vault.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to pound on it right after that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the United States moved to the uneven bars, Dantzscher
rejoined her teammates. She ran through her routine without any
problems, taking a small step backward on her dismount.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a small surprise,'' Karolyi said. ''But I believe it's
a temporary difficulty. It's nothing we're concerned about very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Dantzscher was in good spirits as she left the practice floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm having fun,'' she said. ''The arena's really cool. You get
a good feeling when you walk in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have already had to replace one of their athletes.
Morgan White, one of the most consistent gymnasts on the team,
withdrew Tuesday because of a stress fracture in her left foot. She
was replaced by Tasha Schwikert, the second alternate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
