<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Images Show Suspect Hit by Cops  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Three officers were placed on administrative duty
after live television shots showed them throwing a suspect to the
ground and punching and kicking him in the head Wednesday after a
high-speed chase.
</P>
<P>
   ''We saw some actions that concerned us,'' said Frank Boni,
assistant director of the Miami-Dade Police Department. ''If action
is warranted, we'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The chase began when a driver in a sport utility vehicle with
stolen plates flashed a gun at an officer, police said.
</P>
<P>
   During the chase, Miami television stations showed a
gunshot-pierced windshield on a pursuing police car. No officers
were hit by any gunfire, but one officer was struck by the SUV and
may have suffered a broken arm.
</P>
<P>
   Live helicopter shots showed a black SUV speeding down busy
streets and through residential neighborhoods from Miami-Dade
County north into Broward County. The SUV swerved through traffic
and up on sidewalks, narrowly missing cars and pedestrians before
being clipped by another car.
</P>
<P>
   The driver then drove into a neighborhood, where he jumped out
of the moving SUV and jumped a fence into a back yard. The vehicle
crashed into a front yard, the images showed.
</P>
<P>
   Television shots then showed an officer throwing the suspect
face down to the ground and punching him three times in the head.
Another officer ran up and kicked the suspect three times in the
head. Other officers arrived, handcuffed the suspect and led him
away.
</P>
<P>
   Police later identified the SUV driver as Jerome McCellion.
Charges against him were pending.
</P>
<P>
   The license tag on the SUV was reported stolen, but it is
unknown if the vehicle itself was stolen, Miami-Dade police Sgt.
Pete Andreau said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas issued a memo to Boni saying he
was troubled by the images and ''what initially appears to be
unnecessary force used by some officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Penelas also said he agreed with the decision to reassign
officers pending the outcome of the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
