<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressHerbert Friedman:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Herbert Friedman, an astrophysicist whose
work resulted in the discovery of X-ray sources outside the solar
system, died Saturday of cancer. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman published roughly 300 papers during his 60-year career
and was awarded the National Science Medal, the nation's top
scientific prize, in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   His work in the field of rocket astronomy, which he helped
pioneer in the late 1940s, led to a better understanding of the
sun's activities, including solar flares and their effect on radio
communications and weather.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, he discovered X-rays from the Crab Nebula, the remains
of a supernova explosion.
George Oakley:
</P>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) -- George Oakley, one of the city's most loyal
boosters and founder of Viking Tours, died Sunday of lung cancer.
He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly 40 years ago when Oakley bought an old school bus
and offered the first public, narrated tours of Newport. That
venture led to Viking Motor Tours, a family-run business that now
has 28 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley was among the first to recognize the significance of the
Tall Ships in Newport when they visited in 1976. He chartered a
fleet of boats throughout New England to provide passengers with a
water view of the classic ships.
</P>
<P>
   He also operated spectator boats for the America's Cup Races
from 1970 through 1983.
</P>
<P>
   He was on the board of directors of the Newport County Chamber
of Commerce and was vice chairman of the Newport Tourist and
Convention Authority, now the Newport County Convention and
Visitors Bureau.
Gary Olsen:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- British actor Gary Olsen, who played a bumbling
suburban father in a popular British Broadcasting Corp. sitcom,
died Wednesday. He was 42. The cause of death was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen starred in the sitcom ''2 Point 4 Children,'' but was also
known for work in film and theater. He had more than 30 screen
productions to his credit, including a role in Peter Greenaway's
film ''The Cook, The Thief, His Wife and Her Lover.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, he had a starring role in the British gangster
movie ''24 Hours in London,'' which came out in July.
Benjamin W. Rawlins:
</P>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Benjamin W. Rawlins, Jr., chairman and CEO
of Union Planters Corp., died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlins served as CEO of Union Planters for more than 16 years.
Under his leadership, the company grew from a $2 billion Memphis
bank to a 12-state, $34 billion financial services company.
</P>
<P>
   Union Planters operates banks in Alabama, Arkansas, Florida,
Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kentucky, Louisiana, Mississippi,
Missouri, Tennessee, and Texas.
Jan Sariman:
</P>
<P>
   UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) -- Jan Sariman, a former Surinamese
minister who fled to the Netherlands in 1983 as a political
refugee, committed suicide Monday on the eve of his embezzlement
trial. He was in his early 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Sariman was minister for agriculture, fisheries and animal
husbandry in the former Dutch colony, located in northeastern South
America, before a Dec. 8, 1992 bloody purge of opponents of former
dictator Desi Bouterse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Sariman fled to the Netherlands where he became active
in the immigrant Surinamese community, serving as treasurer of the
Foundation of Collaborating Ethnic Minorities in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with misappropriating $132,000 from the
foundation in a trial that was scheduled to begin Tuesday at the
district court in this central Dutch city.
Ronn Teitelbaum:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ronn Teitelbaum, founder of the 138-store
Johnny Rockets hamburger diner chain, died Monday of brain cancer.
He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum had been operating the Eric Ross &AMP; Co. men's clothing
store in Beverly Hills when he came up with the Johnny Rockets malt
shop idea.
</P>
<P>
   His first 1940s-style restaurant opened on Melrose Avenue in
June 1986.
</P>
<P>
   It grew to 138 stores in 25 states and nine countries, featuring
gleaming white counters, nickel jukeboxes, wide-top Coca-Cola
tumblers, hand-pressed burgers, chili fries and malts served in
frosty chrome canisters.
</P>
<P>
   Freshly baked apple pie is served with a paper American flag
stuck in each slice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
