<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cops Rule Out Ramsey in Sex Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Boulder police have ruled out a connection
between a 1997 sexual assault on a 14-year-old girl and the 1996
slaying of JonBenet Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   Police began investigating a possible link in May after a
newspaper article suggested police may have overlooked a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-old victim in the September 1997 case attended the
same dance academy as JonBenet, and lived within two miles of the
Ramseys' home. The victim in the 1997 attack reported being
sexually assaulted by an intruder who may have been lurking in her
home for hours. The girl's mother interrupted the attack and no
suspect was ever identified.
</P>
<P>
   A palm print found at the Ramsey crime scene does not match a
palm print discovered in the 14-year-old's home, police Chief Mark
Beckner said Tuesday. Despite some parallels between the two
unsolved cases, Beckner said police ''have found no connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old JonBenet was found beaten and strangled in the
basement of her parents' Boulder home Dec. 26, 1996. A grand jury
investigating her death adjourned last year with no indictments
issued.
</P>
<P>
   Beckner also said investigators have more work to do following
their August interviews with JonBenet's parents, John and Patsy
Ramsey, who remain under suspicion in their daughter's death.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys' lawyer, Lin Wood, said they have agreed not to
release tapes of the interviews ''at this time'' because they want
to cooperate with officers who believe the releasing would
jeopardize the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day session in Atlanta, where the Ramseys live now, was
the first time the parents and police had talked since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wood released a short portion of the interview in which a
prosecutor grew agitated during an exchange with Wood. District
Attorney Alex Hunter and Beckner asked Wood not to release any
more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
