<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian sailors show national pride in effort to promote homeland </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - For now the Bat'kivshchyna is docked in
Connecticut, but the ship's soul is firmly anchored in its native
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-foot black-hulled gaff-rigged schooner whose name means
''Motherland'' in Ukrainian is stalled in the midst of a sometimes
tumultuous voyage with a message as strong as the storms it has
endured.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our country is very new but has an old heritage,'' Dmytro
Biriukovich, the ship's 63-year-old captain, said in his native
tongue Tuesday. ''We lost our independence, but now we are a free
country. We want people to know what Ukraine is.''
</P>
<P>
   With the blue and yellow Ukrainian flag at its helm, the cement
ship that Biriukovich rebuilt from a fishing trawler 10 years ago
is showing signs of wear from it difficulties at sea.
</P>
<P>
   But the crew from Kiev beams with pride that districts visitors
from its rough exterior and turns their focus to the colorful
culture that Biriukovich wants the world to recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Russia traces its roots to the Kievan state of Rus in the 9th
century, but for most of the time that followed, Ukraine had been
dominated by Moscow. For seven decades, Ukraine was a republic of
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, leaders from both nations have made efforts to
improve relations, focusing on a Slavic brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in a traditional white shirt with red embroidery,
Biriukovich's wife, Nina, takes visitors down the steps at the
front of the ship into the cramped master sleeping quarters.
</P>
<P>
   She shows off a bottle of vodka shaped like a Cossack and
clutches a golden key chain embossed with the image of the Orthodox
saint, Michael (Mikhail).
</P>
<P>
   ''St. Michael blesses us on our voyage,'' Nina Biriukovich says
in Ukrainian, her green eyes about to well with tears. ''There is a
new statue of St. Michael in the center of Kiev. Everyone prays to
him there, and we pray to him here.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 7, the Biriukoviches - both retired civil engineers -
and the rest of the crew set sail on the icy Dnieper River.
Bombarded by storms and lost at sea with a failed communications
system, the Bat'kivshchyna missed the first in a series of OpSail
events in San Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course it wasn't all easy,'' said Nina Biriukovich, 64.
''But we persevered. Ukrainians are very strong people.''
</P>
<P>
   Atop the ship's tallest mast waves an American flag. During
stops in countries including Italy, Spain and Turkey, the crew
raised the native flag honoring the people that welcomed them to
their ports.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here in America are very soulful, generous and kind people,''
said Nina Biriukovich. ''People ask, 'What can we do? How can we
help? What can we bring?' It makes me cry.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, two men stopped by to help repair an engine, and a
woman took Nina Biriukovich to the store so she could buy cucumbers
and tomatoes to make a traditional salad.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to thank everyone,'' Dmytro Biriukovich said.
</P>
<P>
   The city is allowing the Bat'kivshchyna to remain docked here
until the Amistad freedom schooner returns next week. The Thames
Shipyard donated a dry dock for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Bat'kivshchyna has been offered a winter home in Norwich.
The city and the chairman of the Norwich Harbor Management
Commission - co-owners of the large-vessel ferry dock - said the
tall ship can stay until April.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Friends of Ukraine Expedition worked to raise
and collect some $8,500 when the Bat'kivshchyna's finances
dwindled. Now CFUE has teamed up with the New Haven chapter of
Children of Chornobyl Relief Fund in an effort to raise tens of
thousands of dollars to send the ship to a Great Lakes tall ships
festival next spring. Plans for the Great Lakes Tall Ships
Challenge include stops in eight ports from Oswego, N.Y. to
Muskegon, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was such a warm response in southern Connecticut where
there is a small Ukrainian-American population compared to the
Great Lakes area,'' said Alex Kuzma, executive director of the New
Haven chapter of CCRF. ''The Bat'kivshchyna is really a symbol of
the resilience and the forward-looking of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   During OpSail festivities here, large crowds gathered around the
Bat'kivshchyna as crew members donned velvet Ukrainian Cossack
suits and sang folk songs.
</P>
<P>
   Tugging at his graying beard the ship's cook, Lenoid Deragin
longed for his homeland. His wife and two children are back home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 52-year-old retired civil engineer said that after 35
years of traditional work, he needed a change.
</P>
<P>
   He says he has lived his life without regrets. Perhaps he has
just one as it pertains to this visit.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother told me to study English,'' he said in Ukrainian.
''I guess I should have listened.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sun belted his bare chest Tuesday, Deragin recalled the
trip from its frigid start.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love all weather because I love life. I am very happy. The
sea puts your soul at peace,'' he said. ''Being a guest here is
great, but I belong to Ukraine.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
