<HEADLINE> Two Die in Military Training Jump  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   YUMA, Ariz. (AP) -- An instructor and a student at a military
parachute training school were killed during a nighttime jump,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the accident, which happened late Tuesday, wasn't
known, said Chuck Wullenjohn, a spokesman for the Army's Yuma
Proving Ground.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were identified as Tech. Sgt. Christopher Sheaffer,
an instructor at the Military Freefall School, and a student --
Engineman First Class Shawn Mustard, 31, of the Naval Amphibious
Base Little Creek in Norfolk, Va. Mustard's hometown is Morrow,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Sheaffer's age was not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from Fort Bragg, N.C., and Fort Rucker, Ala., will
investigate the accident at the school, which teaches advanced
parachute techniques to all branches of the military.
</P>
<P>
   The school has been at the Yuma Proving Ground since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1999, another student at the school was killed when his
parachute malfunctioned.
</P>
</TEXT>
