<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Airlines plane forced to return to JFK after bomb threat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A plane reportedly carrying the president of
Pakistan was forced to turn around and land at John F. Kennedy
International Airport late Wednesday after a bomb threat was phoned
in.
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority spokesman Alan Hicks said the Boeing 747 took off
for Pakistan from Kennedy Airport Wednesday night with 121
passengers and crew aboard. Pakistan International Airlines Flight
722 was scheduled to leave New York at 9 p.m. on its way to
Manchester, England, and then on to Karachi.
</P>
<P>
   At some point after takeoff, a bomb threat was received, and the
plane turned around and landed at Kennedy shortly before 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said authorities were in the process of removing
passengers and luggage from the craft late Wednesday. Luggage would
then be matched to passengers. No further incidents were
immediately reported.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said K-9 units would then check the plane for anything
unusual. He said the plane would be moved to an isolated area,
adding that he was ''very confident'' that nothing else would
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said dogs had checked the luggage before it had taken off.
</P>
<P>
   A call to the Consulate General of Pakistan in New York was not
immediately returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
