<HEADLINE> Calif. Brush Blazes Burn 5,200 Acres  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGUA DULCE, Calif. (AP) -- Five wind-driven fires sent walls of
flame roaring over at least 5,200 acres of Southern California
brush Wednesday, destroying at least three homes and threatening
more than a dozen others.
</P>
<P>
   The fires dotted an area stretching hundreds of miles, from San
Diego to an Air Force base more than 100 miles north of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen homes were evacuated in the Agua Dulce area about 50
miles northeast of Los Angeles after the homes were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last people out of the area, Dan Dawson, said the
fire destroyed a shed containing his six motorcycles, all
uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was the last one out of here,'' he said. ''I was trying to
get as much as I could. Even the fire department pushed me out of
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The blaze had burned some 400 acres, while the other fires were
not immediately threatening any homes. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The blazes broke out during a second day of scorching
temperatures across Southern California.
</P>
</TEXT>
