<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal officer accused of trying to arrange a murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - A federal prison guard who found
romance online asked an inmate to help him find a hit man to bump
off a rival, prosecutors said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the guard, the inmate went to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Norval of Hamlin, Pa., a correction officer at the
federal prison in Otisville, N.Y., was arrested Tuesday and charged
with murder for hire and murder conspiracy, which are punishable by
10 and 25 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said Norval wanted to find someone
who would kill a person in Mexico ''who would interfere with
Norval's relationship with a woman in Mexico whom he had met on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   He reached out to an inmate at Otisville, but the inmate
reported the approach and arranged for Norval to call an undercover
officer in Texas, White said. The undercover officer posed as a
relative of the inmate and Norval solicited the murder, the
prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   Norval was arrested by agents from the Justice Department's
Office of the Inspector General. He was arraigned in White Plains
and was held pending a bail hearing scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''American law enforcement officers who violate their trust are
few and far between,'' said Glenn Fine, acting inspector general.
''But when we identify ones that do, the (inspector's office) will
vigorously investigate and prosecute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
