<HEADLINE> Tex. Budgets $4M for Kids' Health  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE MABIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- In a move which followed criticism of Gov.
George W. Bush's health care policies, the Texas Health and Human
Services Commission on Wednesday announced an increase in its
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said it had allocated an additional $4 million to
its state budget for Children's Health Insurance Program outreach.
</P>
<P>
   The extra money comes two weeks after a federal judge blasted
the state for failing to solve problems with its children's
Medicaid program, and as Bush, the Republican presidential nominee,
countered accusations that he was not doing enough to give poor
Texans access to health care.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has defended the state's Medicaid program, and his campaign
has cited the health program as one way his administration has
tried to get children insured.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has the nation's second-highest rate of uninsured
children. Some 1.4 million of the nearly 11 million children
nationwide who lack health insurance are Texans. Only Arizona has a
worse rate.
</P>
<P>
   Commission spokesman Charles Stuart said the budget decision was
not political and that there had been no pressure from Bush's
office to spend more on publicizing the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just trying to increase our outreach efforts,'' Stuart
said. ''Our plans and our goals are not influenced by any election
cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Mike Jones also denied politics played a role.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just a prudent, common-sense decision by the Health
and Human Services Commission,'' he said. ''The program still has
plenty of room to grow and in a state as big and as diverse as
Texas, this is a reasonable step to help spread the word.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.texcarepartnership.com
</P>
</TEXT>
