<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-13 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florence still could strengthen again, threaten Bermuda  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo FLAC101
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) - Hurricane Florence weakened into a tropical storm
Wednesday, a day after being blamed for at least two deaths in
North Carolina, but forecasters said the system could regenerate
into a hurricane and threaten Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   ''Florence will have an opportunity to restrengthen to hurricane
status once it begins to move away from its present location toward
warmer waters,'' said Lixion Avila, a hurricane specialist at the
National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Florence, which had sustained winds of 70 mph, remained a
slow-moving mass of wind and rain off the southeast United States
late Wednesday. The storm has moved slightly to the west since
developing into a hurricane Tuesday, but was forecast to move to
the east-northeast and away from the U.S. mainland in the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Avila said Bermuda should monitor Florence's progress and a
hurricane watch may be required early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 p.m. EDT, Florence, the sixth named storm of the 2000
Atlantic hurricane season, was centered near latitude 30.2 north,
longitude 73.3 west, or about 525 miles west-southwest of Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   A tropical wave in the Caribbean also has forecasters on alert.
The wave could become a tropical depression within the next 24
hours, meteorologist Eric Blake said. It is located southeast of
Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula and is moving to the northwest between
10 and 15 mph, Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   A man and a woman died at Kure Beach, N.C., and seven other
people were rescued Tuesday after strong rip currents associated
with Florence caught swimmers by surprise. Another man was missing
after falling out of a kayak at Carolina Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they did not intend to reopen two beaches
closed Tuesday until Florence is no longer a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Florence will continue to generate dangerous surf and rip
tides along portions of the southeastern U.S. coast,'' Avila said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/
</P>
